 2000\n|23 October 2003\n|[[Rear admiral (United States)|RADM]]\n|Michael R. Johnson\n|Naval Facilities Engineering Command\n|-\n|40\n|[http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=10229 24 October 2003]\n|26 October 2006\n|[[Rear admiral (United States)|RADM]]\n|[http://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/navybio.asp?bioID=183 Michael K. Loose]\n|Naval Facilities Engineering Command\n|-\n|41\n|[http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=26307 27 October 2006]\n|20 May 2010\n|[[Rear admiral (United States)|RADM]]\n|[[Wayne G. Shear Jr.|Wayne \"Greg\" Shear]]\n|Naval Facilities Engineering Command\n|-\n|42\n|[http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=53538 21 May 2010]\n|25 October 2012\n|[[Rear admiral (United States)|RADM]]\n|[http://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/navybio.asp?bioID=361 Christopher J. Mossey]\n|Naval Facilities Engineering Command\n|-\n|43\n|[http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=70374 26 October 2012]\n|3 November 2015\n|[[Rear admiral (United States)|RADM]]\n|[[Katherine L. Gregory]]\n|Naval Facilities Engineering Command\n|-\n|44\n|[http://www.navy.mil/submit/display.asp?story_id=91850 4 November 2015]\n|18 October 2018\n|[[Rear admiral (United States)|RADM]]\n|[http://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/bio.asp?bioID=750 Bret J. Muilenburg]\n|Naval Facilities Engineering Command\n|-\n|45\n|19 October 2018\n|Present\n|[[Rear admiral (United States)|RADM]]\n|[https://www.navy.mil/navydata/bios/bio.asp?bioID=890 John W. Korka]\n|Naval Facilities Engineering Command\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Military engineering of the United States]]\n*[[Seabees]]\n*Admiral [[Ben Moreell]]\n*[[Navy lighterage pontoon]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.navfac.navy.mil/jobs/students_and_grads/CEC_Collegiate_Program.html CEC Accessions Website]\n* [https://www.seabee.navy.mil/ Seabee Website]\n* [http://www.netc.navy.mil/centers/csfe/cecos/ Civil Engineer Corps Officer School (CECOS) Website]\n\n{{US Navy navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Administrative corps of the United States Navy]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1867]]\n[[Category:Engineering units and formations of the United States military]]\n", "name_user": "Mcb133aco", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Civil_Engineer_Corps"}
{"title_page": "West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|image_name     = West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine logo.gif\n|image_size     = 200px\n|name           = West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine\n|established    = 1974\n|type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] [[medical school]]\n|budget          = $35.64 million<ref>{{cite web|title=Fiscal Year 2013 Revenues and Expenditures by Osteopathic Medical College|url=https://www.aacom.org/docs/default-source/data-and-trends/fy2013-RevandExpbyCOM.pdf?sfvrsn=28|publisher=[[American Association of Colleges of Osteopathic Medicine|AACOM]]|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> \n|dean           = Craig Boisvert, D.O., FACOFP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wvsom.edu/About/senior-staff|title=WVSOM Senior Leadership - West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine|website=www.wvsom.edu}}</ref>\n|president      = James W. Nemitz, Ph.D.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wvsom.edu/news/2018/feb/nemitz|title=Nemitz named next WVSOM president - West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine|website=www.wvsom.edu}}</ref>\n|city           = [[Lewisburg, West Virginia|Lewisburg]] \n|state          = [[West Virginia]] \n|country        = United States\n|coor           = {{Coord|37.8058|-80.4373|display=inline,title|type:edu}}\n|students       = 778\n|faculty        = 57<ref>{{cite web|title=West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-medical-schools/west-virginia-school-of-osteopathic-medicine-04145|publisher=U.S.News & World Report|accessdate=11 August 2012}}</ref>\n|campus         = [[Rural]] \n|website= {{url|http://www.wvsom.edu/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine''' ('''WVSOM''') is a [[Public university|public]] [[medical school]] for [[Osteopathic Medicine|osteopathic medicine]] located in [[Lewisburg, West Virginia]].  Founded in 1974, WVSOM is one of three medical schools in [[West Virginia]] and the sole institution that grants the [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.) degree.  WVSOM currently has 778 students,<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wvsom.edu/applicants/glance.cfm|title=WVSOM at a Glance|publisher=}}</ref> and focuses on [[primary care]] and rural medicine.\n\n== History ==\nPurchasing a facility once used as [[Greenbrier Military School]] (1812\u20131972), the Greenbrier College of Osteopathic Medicine began as a private school with a class of 36 students in 1974. Two years later, in 1976, the board of governors of the school donated it to the state, which accepted establishing it as a state-funded public institution now named the West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine. In 1978, WVSOM graduated its first class of 33 students.<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\" /> \nExtensive renovations started in 1992 and continue into the present time, with construction just completed on a new {{convert|19000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building that includes exam rooms and laboratory space. \nWVSOM has spent more than $38 million on construction and renovation projects while increasing from one building in 1974 to 12 campus facilities across its more than {{convert|50|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus, all of this was accomplished while maintaining a debt free financial status.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.register-herald.com/local/local_story_003225746.html\n|title= New WVSOM building on tap for \u201909\n|accessdate= 2008-04-20\n|author= Christian Giggenbach\n|publisher= The Register-Herald \n|date= 2008-01-03\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|url= http://dailymail.com/News/statenews/200801040154\n|title= Osteopathic school to build $9.3 million facility\n|accessdate = 2008-04-20 \n|author= The Associated Press\n|publisher= Charleston Daily Mail\n|date=2008-01-04\n}}\n</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2016, State Senator [[Craig Blair]] proposed privatizing the institution.  Blair stated that the institution was diverting money from other functions and could thrive as a private institution freed from state bureaucratic regulations.\n\n== Academics ==\n\nWVSOM was founded on the principles of [[Osteopathic medicine in the United States|osteopathic medicine]], a branch of medicine founded by frontiersman [[Andrew Taylor Still]] in the mid-to-late 19th century. The basic premise of osteopathic medicine is that a physician's primary role is to facilitate the body's inherent ability to heal itself. While originally designed as an improvement on the traditional medicine of 19th century America, osteopathic medicine became a reformation within the U.S. healthcare system while remaining distinct from other forms of medicine.<ref name=\"About Osteopathic Medicine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aacom.org/become-a-doctor/about-om|title=What is Osteopathic Medicine|website=www.aacom.org}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to a medical education, students at WVSOM also learn holistic techniques and are trained in [[Osteopathic Manipulative Medicine]] (OMM), manual-based therapies used to relieve pain, restore range of motion and foster the body's own ability to heal itself.<ref name=\"About Osteopathic Medicine\" />\nMedical school at WVSOM is a four-year program, with two years of training located at the Lewisburg-based campus and the final two years taking place off-campus during clinical rotations.<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\" />\n\n== Demographics ==\nWVSOM's current enrollment stands at 778 students, with out-of-state students composing the majority (557 out of state :221 in state). The median age is 27, and there are students from 46 states currently attending WVSOM.  The male female ratio is roughly equal with 369 females and 409 males.  WVSOM maintains a diverse ethnic community on campus, with 161 minority students.  AACOMAS reports that 3,283 students applied for admission into WVSOM's most recent class (Class of 2013).<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://wvsom.edu/ Official website]\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Osteopathic medical schools}}\n{{Medical education in the United States}}\n{{Colleges and universities in West Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Virginia School Of Osteopathic Medicine}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Greenbrier County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Education in Greenbrier County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1974]]\n[[Category:Osteopathic medical schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Medical schools in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in West Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|image_name     = West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine logo.gif\n|image_size     = 200px\n|name           = West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine\n|established    = 1974\n|type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] [[medical school]]\n|budget          = $35.64 million<ref>{{cite web|title=Fiscal Year 2013 Revenues and Expenditures by Osteopathic Medical College|url=https://www.aacom.org/docs/default-source/data-and-trends/fy2013-RevandExpbyCOM.pdf?sfvrsn=28|publisher=[[American Association of Colleges of Osteopathic Medicine|AACOM]]|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> \n|dean           = Craig Boisvert, D.O., FACOFP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wvsom.edu/About/senior-staff|title=WVSOM Senior Leadership - West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine|website=www.wvsom.edu}}</ref>\n|president      = James W. Nemitz, Ph.D.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wvsom.edu/news/2018/feb/nemitz|title=Nemitz named next WVSOM president - West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine|website=www.wvsom.edu}}</ref>\n|city           = [[Lewisburg, West Virginia|Lewisburg]] \n|state          = [[West Virginia]] \n|country        = United States\n|coor           = {{Coord|37.8058|-80.4373|display=inline,title|type:edu}}\n|students       = 778\n|faculty        = 57<ref>{{cite web|title=West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-medical-schools/west-virginia-school-of-osteopathic-medicine-04145|publisher=U.S.News & World Report|accessdate=11 August 2012}}</ref>\n|campus         = [[Rural]] \n|website= {{url|http://www.wvsom.edu/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine''' ('''WVSOM''') is a [[Public university|public]] [[medical school]] for [[Osteopathic Medicine|osteopathic medicine]] located in [[Lewisburg, West Virginia]].  Founded in 1974, WVSOM is one of three medical schools in [[West Virginia]] and the sole institution that grants the [[Doctor of Osteopathic Medicine]] (D.O.) degree.  WVSOM currently has 778 students,<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wvsom.edu/applicants/glance.cfm|title=WVSOM at a Glance|publisher=}}</ref> and focuses on [[primary care]] and rural medicine.\n\n== History ==\nPurchasing a facility once used as [[Greenbrier Military School]] (1812\u20131972), the Greenbrier College of Osteopathic Medicine began as a private school with a class of 36 students in 1974. Two years later, in 1976, the board of governors of the school donated it to the state, which accepted establishing it as a state-funded public institution now named the West Virginia School of Osteopathic Medicine. In 1978, WVSOM graduated its first class of 33 students.<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\" /> \nExtensive renovations started in 1992 and continue into the present time, with construction just completed on a new {{convert|19000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} building that includes exam rooms and laboratory space. \nWVSOM has spent more than $38 million on construction and renovation projects while increasing from one building in 1974 to 12 campus facilities across its more than {{convert|50|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus, all of this was accomplished while maintaining a debt free financial status.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.register-herald.com/local/local_story_003225746.html\n|title= New WVSOM building on tap for \u201909\n|accessdate= 2008-04-20\n|author= Christian Giggenbach\n|publisher= The Register-Herald \n|date= 2008-01-03\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n|url= http://dailymail.com/News/statenews/200801040154\n|title= Osteopathic school to build $9.3 million facility\n|accessdate = 2008-04-20 \n|author= The Associated Press\n|publisher= Charleston Daily Mail\n|date=2008-01-04\n}}\n</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2016, State Senator [[Craig Blair]] proposed privatizing the institution.  Blair stated that the institution was diverting money from other functions and could thrive as a private institution freed from state bureaucratic regulations.\n\n== Academics ==\n\nWVSOM was founded on the principles of [[Osteopathic medicine in the United States|osteopathic medicine]], a branch of medicine founded by frontiersman [[Andrew Taylor Still]] in the mid-to-late 19th century. The basic premise of osteopathic medicine is that a physician's primary role is to facilitate the body's inherent ability to heal itself. While originally designed as an improvement on the traditional medicine of 19th century America, osteopathic medicine became a reformation within the U.S. healthcare system while remaining distinct from other forms of medicine.<ref name=\"About Osteopathic Medicine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.aacom.org/become-a-doctor/about-om|title=What is Osteopathic Medicine|website=www.aacom.org}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to a medical education, students at WVSOM also learn holistic techniques and are trained in [[Osteopathic Manipulative Medicine]] (OMM), manual-based therapies used to relieve pain, restore range of motion and foster the body's own ability to heal itself.<ref name=\"About Osteopathic Medicine\" />\nMedical school at WVSOM is a four-year program, with two years of training located at the Lewisburg-based campus and the final two years taking place off-campus during clinical rotations.<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\" />\n\n== Demographics ==\nWVSOM's current enrollment stands at 778 students, with out-of-state students composing the majority (557 out of state :221 in state). The median age is 27, and there are students from 46 states currently attending WVSOM.  The male female ratio is roughly equal with 369 females and 409 males.  WVSOM maintains a diverse ethnic community on campus, with 161 minority students.  AACOMAS reports that 3,283 students applied for admission into WVSOM's most recent class (Class of 2013).<ref name=\"WVSOM at a Glance\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://wvsom.edu/ Official website]\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{Osteopathic medical schools}}\n{{Medical education in the United States}}\n{{Colleges and universities in West Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:West Virginia School Of Osteopathic Medicine}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Greenbrier County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Education in Greenbrier County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1974]]\n[[Category:Osteopathic medical schools in the United States]]\n[[Category:Medical schools in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in West Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "ElKevbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Virginia_School_of_Osteopathic_Medicine"}
{"title_page": "Charles Mackerras", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n[[File:Sir Charles Mackerras.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.15|Mackerras in 2005]]\n'''Sir Alan Charles Maclaurin Mackerras''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AC|CH|CBE}} ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|k|\u025br|\u0259|s}}; {{Nowrap|17 November}} 1925{{spaced ndash}}{{Nowrap|14 July}} 2010)<ref name=\"Australian\">{{Cite news| url  =http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/arts/symphony-mourns-death-of-conductor-charles-mackerras/story-e6frg8n6-1225892114358  | title =Symphony mourns death of conductor Charles Mackerras  | last =Wilson | first =Ashleigh | work =[[The Australian]]|date=15 July 2010| accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/music/sir-charles-mackerras-dies/story-e6frexl9-1225892206801 | title =Sir Charles Mackerras dies | work =[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> was an Australian [[conducting|conductor]]. He was an authority on the operas of [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek|Jan\u00e1\u010dek]] and [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], and the [[comic opera]]s of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]].  He was long associated with the [[English National Opera]] (and its predecessor) and [[Welsh National Opera]] and was the first Australian chief conductor of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMackerras was born in [[Schenectady, New York]], to Australian parents, Alan Mackerras and Catherine MacLaurin.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/music-obituaries/7892957/Sir-Charles-Mackerras.html | title =Sir Charles Mackerras  | date  =15 July 2010 | work  =[[The Daily Telegraph]] | publisher =[[Telegraph Media Group]]  | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> His father was an electrical engineer and a [[Quaker]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> In 1928, when Charles was aged two, the family returned to [[Sydney]], Australia.  They initially lived in the suburb of [[Rose Bay, New South Wales|Rose Bay]], and in 1933 they moved to the then semi-rural suburb of [[Turramurra]].<ref name=\"Herald obit\">{{Cite news | url =http://www.smh.com.au/national/obituaries/scion-of-an-australian-dynasty-conducted-for-the-whole-world-20100715-10ck6.html | title =Scion of an Australian dynasty conducted for the whole world | last =Maunder | first =Patricia | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher =[[Fairfax Media]] | date =16 July 2010 | accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref> Mackerras was the eldest of seven children. His siblings were Alastair (1928\u201399), [[Neil Mackerras|Neil]] (1930\u201387), Joan (b. 1934), Elisabeth (b. 1937) and twins [[Malcolm Mackerras|Malcolm]] and [[Colin Mackerras|Colin]] (b. 1939).<ref name=Birthday90>Simeone, Nigel. \"Sir Charles Mackerras (1925\u20132010): A Lifetime of Gilbert and Sullivan\" (Part I), ''Gilbert and Sullivan News'', Vol. V, No. 9, Autumn/Winter 2015, pp. 12\u201314, The Gilbert and Sullivan Society</ref> They are descendants of the pioneer Australian musician [[Isaac Nathan]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Mackerras studied violin at the age of seven and later the flute.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> He was setting poems to music at eight and wrote a piano concerto when he was 12.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/>\n\nMackerras initially attended his father's alma mater, [[Sydney Grammar School]], and also [[St Aloysius' College (Sydney)|St Aloysius College]] in Sydney.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> While at Sydney Grammar, he showed a precocious talent by composing operas and conducting student performances in his early teens, but his non-musical studies suffered.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> At all-male St Aloysius, he participated in the school's [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] productions, playing the roles of Kate in ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'', Leila in ''[[Iolanthe]]'' and Ko-Ko in ''[[The Mikado]]''.<ref name=Birthday90/> Unconvinced that music was a viable profession, his parents removed the young Mackerras from temptation by sending him to board at [[The King's School, Parramatta|The King's School]]. The school's focus on sport and discipline led the young artist to run away several times, and he was eventually expelled.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> At age 16, Mackerras studied oboe, piano and composition at the [[Sydney Conservatorium of Music|NSW State Conservatorium of Music]]. He earned additional income from writing orchestral scores from recordings.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/>\n\n==Early career==\nBy 1941, while still at the conservatory, Mackerras began to get professional performing jobs in Sydney, partly because he was too young to join the military, while older musicians had been called up to go to the war. From 1941 to 1942, Mackerras played the oboe for the [[J. C. Williamson]] Company during one of their Gilbert and Sullivan seasons, and he was a rehearsal pianist for the Kirsova ballet company.<ref name=Birthday90/> In 1943, Mackerras joined the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra|ABC Sydney Orchestra]], under [[Malcolm Sargent]], as second oboist and at age 19, became principal oboist.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/><ref name=\"ClassicFM\">{{Cite web | url =http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/music-news-and-features/sir-charles-mackerras-dies | title =Sir Charles Mackerras dies | date =15 July 2010 | work =[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] | publisher =[[Global Radio]] | accessdate =15 July 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianWeaver\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/15/conductor-charles-mackerras-dies | title =Conductor Charles Mackerras dies | last =Weaver | first =Matthew | work =[[The Guardian]]|date=15 July 2010 | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> On {{Nowrap|6 February}} 1947, Mackerras sailed for England on the RMS Rangitiki<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> intending to pursue conducting.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> He joined [[Sadler's Wells Theatre]] as an orchestral oboist and [[Cor anglais (English horn)|cor anglais]] player.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> He later won a [[British Council]] Scholarship, enabling him to study conducting with [[V\u00e1clav Talich]] at the Prague Academy of Music.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> While there, he formed a strong friendship with [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Tancibudek]], Principal Oboe of the [[Czech Philharmonic]], who introduced him to the operas of [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek]], thus commencing Mackerras's lifelong passion for that composer's music.<ref>[http://www.adrs.org.au/jiri_tancibudek.html Australasian Double Reed Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219150559/http://www.adrs.org.au/jiri_tancibudek.html |date=19 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 1947, shortly before the couple set off for Prague, Mackerras married Judy Wilkins, a clarinettist at Sadlers' Wells.<ref name=Birthday90/> They had two daughters, Fiona and Catherine.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/><ref name=\"GuardianObituary\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/15/sir-charles-mackerras-obituary | title =Sir Charles Mackerras obituary | last =Blyth | first =Alan | date =15 July 2010 | work =[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> Fiona died of cancer in September 2006.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/news/conductor-led-concert-hours-after-death-of-his-daughter-1-1139314 \"Conductor led concert hours after death of his daughter\"], ''The Scotsman'', 8 September 2006. Retrieved 16 October 2014</ref> He was also the uncle of the Australian conductor [[Alexander Briger]]<ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.smh.com.au/news/arts/a-dream-comes-true/2006/08/21/1156012471023.html?page=fullpage | title =A Dream Comes True | last =Meacham | first =Steve | date =22 August 2006 | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher =[[Fairfax Media]] | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> and the British-born American conductor Drostan Hall, Music Director of [[Camerata Chicago]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Camerata Chicago celebrates 10th anniversary|url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-05-15/entertainment/ct-ent-0515-classical-camerata-20130515_1_chamber-orchestra-small-orchestra-charles-mackerras|website = tribunedigital-chicagotribune|accessdate = 2015-12-13}}</ref>\n\nReturning to England from Prague in 1948, Mackerras rejoined Sadler's Wells as an assistant conductor and began his lifelong association with the Sadler's Wells Opera, now [[English National Opera]], conducting, among others, [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek|Jan\u00e1\u010dek]], [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]], [[Christoph Willibald Gluck|Gluck]], [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]], and [[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> In the 1950s, well before the \"authenticity\" movement had come to general notice, Mackerras focused on the study and practical realization of period performance techniques, culminating in his landmark 1959 recording of Handel's ''[[Music for the Royal Fireworks]]'' using the original wind band instrumentation. In his 1965 performance of ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'', he added the [[ornament (music)|ornamentation]] in a [[historically informed performance|historically informed]] style.\n\nMackerras also strongly championed the music of Jan\u00e1\u010dek outside Czechoslovakia, where Mackerras himself judged his work with Jan\u00e1\u010dek as his single most important legacy to music.<ref name=\"Moss\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/aug/20/classicalmusicandopera | title =The modest maestro | last =Moss | first =Stephen | work =[[The Guardian]]|date=20 August 2005|accessdate=18 September 2007}}</ref> In 1951, he conducted the British premiere of ''[[K\u00e1\u0165a Kabanov\u00e1]]''. He was also a noted authority on [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s operas and those of Sir [[Arthur Sullivan]]. His ballet with [[John Cranko]], ''[[Pineapple Poll]]'', is an arrangement of Sullivan music with a story based on one of [[W. S. Gilbert]]'s ''[[Bab Ballads]]''. The piece premiered in 1951, soon after the expiration of copyright on Sullivan's music, and continues to be a popular light music favourite in English speaking countries.<ref name=Birthday90/> Mackerras later arranged music by [[Giuseppe Verdi]] for the ballet ''[[The Lady and the Fool]]''. He also arranged a suite from [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]]'s score for the 1946 film ''[[The Overlanders (film)|The Overlanders]]'', after Ireland's death in 1962.\n\nHe was principal conductor of the [[BBC Concert Orchestra]] from 1954 to 1956.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news | url =http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-50143820100715 | title =Factbox \u2013 Orchestra conductor Charles Mackerras dies | last =Cutler | first =David | work =[[Reuters]] | date =15 July 2010 | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> \nIn 1962, he conducted the [[S.A. Symphony Orchestra]] in the Australian premi\u00e8re of Strauss's ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'' as part of the [[Adelaide Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catalog.slsa.sa.gov.au:443/record=b2092816~S1|title=S.A. Symphony Orchestra rehearsal|publisher=State Library of South Australia|year=1962|access-date=30 October 2019}} Photograph may only be viewed at the Library.</ref> with Adelaide-born [[Una Hale]] in the title role.\nIn 1963, he made his debut at London's Covent Garden conducting Shostakovich's ''[[Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District (opera)|Katerina Izmailova]]''. He directed the [[Hamburg State Opera]] from 1965 to 1969 and the [[English National Opera]] from 1970 to 1977.<ref>Phelan 1987, p. ?? {{Page needed|date=May 2014}}</ref> In 1972, he made his [[Metropolitan Opera]] debut in New York conducting [[Christoph Willibald Gluck|Gluck]]'s ''[[Orfeo ed Euridice]]''. Mackerras worked closely with [[Benjamin Britten]] for a time until 1958, when, during rehearsals for the first performance of Britten's opera ''[[Noye's Fludde]]'', he made comments about Britten liking prepubescent boys' company and Britten subsequently stopped speaking to him.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> The events are described in John Bridcut's ''[[Britten's Children]]''.\n\nHe conducted the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]] and [[Birgit Nilsson]] in the opening concert of the Concert Hall of the [[Sydney Opera House]], in the presence of Queen Elizabeth&nbsp;II, in 1973.<ref name=\"GuardianWeaver\"/><ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/national-treasure-made-music-until-the-end-20100715-10clx.html | title =National treasure made music until the end | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher =[[Fairfax Media]] | date =16 July 2010 | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nMackerras had conducted a few Gilbert and Sullivan productions for English National Opera, but his first experience as a guest conductor of the [[D'Oyly Carte Opera Company]] was for ''[[Trial by Jury]]'', ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'' and ''[[The Mikado]]'' during the 1975 D'Oyly Carte centenary season at the Savoy. He conducted ''[[Patience (opera)|Patience]]'' at the Proms in 1976, the first full-length Gilbert and Sullivan opera given complete at the Proms. In 1980 he joined the D'Oyly Carte Opera Trust and later its Board of Trustees. In the early 1980s he conducted two New Year's Eve broadcasts of [[Savoy opera]]s for the BBC, and his recordings of eight of the operas were broadcast in 1989 by BBC Radio 2 as part of a complete Gilbert and Sullivan series. He also conducted a centennial performance of Sullivan's ''[[The Golden Legend (cantata)|The Golden Legend]]'' in Leeds and the first staging of a complete Gilbert and Sullivan opera at the [[Royal Opera House]], ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]'', with [[Welsh National Opera]] in 1995.<ref name=GSNews>Simeone, Nigel. \"Sir Charles MacKerras (1925\u20132010): A Lifetime of Gilbert and Sullivan\", ''Gilbert and Sullivan News'', The Gilbert and Sullivan Society (London), Vol. V, No. 10, Spring 2016, pp. 4\u20137</ref> In 1980, also, he became the first non-Briton to conduct the [[BBC Symphony Orchestra]] at the [[Last Night of the Proms]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/>\n\nIn 1982 Mackerras was the first Australian national appointed chief conductor of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]], a post he held until 1985.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> he directed the [[Welsh National Opera]] from 1987 to 1992, where his Jan\u00e1\u010dek productions won particular praise. One of the highlights of the 1991 season was the reopening of the Estates Theatre in Prague, scene of the original premiere of Mozart's ''[[Don Giovanni]]'', in which Mackerras conducted a new production of that opera to mark the bicentenary of Mozart's death. As Conductor Emeritus of Welsh National Opera, his successes included ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]'', and ''[[La clemenza di Tito]]'' (all of which productions were brought to London). He was the principal guest conductor of the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] (SCO) from 1992 to 1995, and held the title of Conductor Laureate with the SCO.  He was principal guest conductor of the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] from 1993 to 1996. During the same period, he was also principal guest conductor of the [[San Francisco Opera]]. From 1998 to 2001 he was the music director of the [[Orchestra of St. Luke's]]. From 1987, he regularly conducted the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]] and was appointed Emeritus Conductor in 2007.\n\nIn 2004 he became principal guest conductor of the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]]. He was also principal guest conductor of the [[Czech Philharmonic]]. With the Royal Opera, he conducted productions of [[Charles Gounod|Gounod]]'s ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'' and [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s ''[[Semele]]''. Mackerras also had a long association with the [[Metropolitan Opera]], where he conducted ''[[The Makropulos Affair (opera)|The Makropulos Case]]'', ''[[K\u00e1\u0165a Kabanov\u00e1]]'', ''[[Le proph\u00e8te]]'', ''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'', ''[[Billy Budd (opera)|Billy Budd]]'', ''[[Hansel and Gretel]]'' and ''[[The Magic Flute]]''.\n\nIn August 2008, Mackerras was announced as the new [[Title of honor|Honorary President]] of the [[Edinburgh International Festival]] Society.<ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.eif.co.uk/news/edinburgh-international-festival-society-announces-sir-charles-mackerras-new-honorary-president | title =Edinburgh International Festival Society Announces Sir Charles Mackerras as New Honorary President | year =2008 | accessdate =2008-08-24 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080823141033/http://www.eif.co.uk/news/edinburgh-international-festival-society-announces-sir-charles-mackerras-new-honorary-president | archivedate =23 August 2008 | df =dmy-all }}</ref> He was only the second person to hold this role, after [[Yehudi Menuhin]]. As the original part of the [[Edinburgh Festival|largest arts festival in the world]], the Edinburgh International Festival featured performances from Mackerras throughout six decades since his first in 1952. Mackerras summarised his strategy for working with an orchestra as follows:\n{{quote|I believe it's very important to edit orchestral parts explicitly and as thoroughly as possible, so that the musicians can play them without too much rehearsal. For instance, the other day I did all the [[Robert Schumann|Schumann]] symphonies with very little rehearsal at all. Because the parts were clearly marked, particularly with regard to dynamics, we were able to play them without needing to do that much preliminary work, focusing our attention on the interpretation rather than the technical business of who plays too loud or too soft.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.classicstoday.com/features/f1_0200.asp |title=A Talk With Sir Charles Mackerras |publisher=Classics Today |last=Hurwitz |first=David |year=2000 |accessdate=15 April 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705084026/http://www.classicstoday.com/features/f1_0200.asp |archivedate=5 July 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>}}\n\nMackerras was the President of [[Trinity College of Music]], London.<ref name=\"ClassicFM\"/> He also served as Music Advisor to [[City Opera of Vancouver]], a professional chamber opera company led by conductor [[Charles Barber (conductor)|Charles Barber]].<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://cityoperavancouver.com/about/whos-who | title =Who's Who | publisher  =[[City Opera of Vancouver]] | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> He was also a Patron of [[Bampton Classical Opera]].<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yaCfBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=mackerras+bampton&source=bl&ots=WLRVB5d3T6&sig=ACfU3U3Fs5aHuL6eD4J_x58uk_wTNTeWPg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiD2Jq87s_oAhUHHMAKHaCLByIQ6AEwAnoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=mackerras%20bampton&f=false</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Anderson |first=Martin |date=16 July 2010 |title=Sir Charles Mackerras: Energetic and perceptive conductor celebrated in particular for popularising the works of Janacek |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/sir-charles-mackerras-energetic-and-perceptive-conductor-celebrated-in-particular-for-popularising-2027753.html |work=Independent |location= |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> From 1999 Mackerras was a Patron of the Australian children's cancer charity Redkite.<ref>[http://www.redkite.org.au Redkite website]</ref>\n\n\n\nOn 18 December 2008, Mackerras served as the conductor for [[Alfred Brendel]]'s final concert performance with the [[Vienna Philharmonic]]. Mackerras's last performance at the [[BBC Proms]] included Gilbert and Sullivan's ''[[Patience (opera)|Patience]]''.<ref name=Birthday90/> His final public performance saw him conduct ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' at [[Glyndebourne]] in the summer of 2010.<ref>{{Cite news | url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/opera/7891990/A-tribute-to-Sir-Charles-Mackerras.html | title =A tribute to Sir Charles Mackerras |last=Christiansen|first=Rupert|authorlink=Rupert Christiansen| work =[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMackerras died in London on 14 July 2010 at the age of 84, having suffered from cancer.<ref name=\"Australian\"/><ref name=\"SMH\">{{Cite news | url =http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/conductor-sir-charles-mackerras-dies-20100715-10c2w.html | title =Conductor Sir Charles Mackerras dies | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher  =[[Fairfax Media]] | date =15 July 2010 | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> Throughout his final illness, he had continued to conduct, and had been scheduled to direct two of the [[BBC Proms]] on {{Nowrap|25 July}} and {{Nowrap|29 July}} 2010. He was also due to conduct the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] performing Mozart's ''[[Idomeneo]]'' at the [[Edinburgh International Festival]] in August 2010, which would have been his 56th appearance at the festival.<ref name=SMH/><ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment+arts-10646000 | title =Conductor Sir Charles Mackerras dies aged 84 | work =[[BBC News]] | publisher =[[BBC]] | date =15 July 2010 | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> The director of the BBC Proms, Roger Wright, announced that a Prom would be dedicated to Mackerras's memory.<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Wright paid tribute to Mackerras, saying \"Sir Charles was a great conductor and his loss will be deeply felt by musicians and audiences alike\",<ref name=\"BBC\"/> while Rory Jeffes of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]] said that Australia had \"lost a living treasure\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/>  Mackerras is survived by his wife, Judy, and their daughter, Catherine.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/><ref>{{Cite news | url =http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/15/charles-mackerras-a-wide-ranging-conductor-dies/ | title      =Charles Mackerras, a Wide-Ranging Conductor, Dies at 84 | last =Wakin | first =Daniel J | date =15 July 2010 | work =[[The New York Times]] | publisher =[[The New York Times Company]] |accessdate  =15 July 2010}}</ref> His funeral was held at [[St Paul's, Covent Garden]] on 23 July 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://announcements.thetimes.co.uk/obituaries/timesonline-uk/obituary.aspx?n=charles-mackerras&pid=144188105|title=Charles Mackerras|work=The Times (personal announcements)|date=20 July 2010|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nMackerras made his earliest records for [[EMI]], in the final days of 78 rpm records, and he continued recording well into the era of compact discs in the multi-channel [[Super Audio CD]] format.  In 1952, he conducted his first recording of his own ''[[Pineapple Poll]]'' ballet, which was issued on twelve sides, and subsequently transferred to LP. He later conducted two more complete recordings of the ballet.<ref name=GSNews/> Some of his early recording sessions were for [[Walter Legge]], standing in when [[Otto Klemperer]] and other eminent conductors were ill.<ref name=Gramophone>{{Cite news|url= |title=Charles Mackerras|work=The Gramophone|author=[[Alan Blyth|Blyth, Alan]]|date=March 1975|pages=1, 626}}</ref> He did not always restrict himself to the classical repertoire.  For example, on {{Nowrap|4 May}} 1955 he recorded [[Albert Arlen]]'s song ''[[Clancy of the Overflow]]'' (to [[Banjo Paterson]]'s poem) with [[Peter Dawson (bass-baritone)|Peter Dawson]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]].<ref>[http://members.optusnet.com.au/johnhrogers/c.htm optus net]</ref>\n\nA smaller UK record company, [[Pye Records]], asked Mackerras to record Handel's ''[[Music for the Royal Fireworks]]''. 'We had to do that in the middle of the night, in order to get our twenty-six oboes together.'<ref name=Gramophone/> The recording, issued in 1959, was received with critical acclaim for attempting to reproduce the sound Handel would have heard, rather than the smoother orchestral arrangements usually played at that time.\n\nIn the 1960s Mackerras made the first recording of the Italian version of Gluck's ''[[Orfeo ed Euridice|Orfeo]]''. For [[Deutsche Grammophon|DG]] he conducted Purcell's ''[[Dido and Aeneas]]'', and for EMI a 'new-look' ''[[Messiah (Handel)|Messiah]]'', with scholarly texts, small forces and sprightly tempi. He followed that up with Handel's ''[[Saul (Handel)|Saul]]'' and ''[[Israel in Egypt]]'' for DG. He also recorded the first complete ''[[Roberto Devereux]]'' with [[Beverly Sills]]. In 1986, he conducted the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] in the soundtrack to [[Carroll Ballard]]'s film version of ''[[The Nutcracker]]'' (better known as ''Nutcracker: The Motion Picture''), the first full-length film version of [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]]'s ballet to be given a major release in theatres.\n\nMackerras recorded three [[Gustav Mahler|Mahler]] symphonies and all of the symphonies of Mozart, [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]] and [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]].<ref name=\"Reuters\"/> Along with the Mozart operas, these recordings continue to attract critical acclaim; as do his recordings of the operas of Jan\u00e1\u010dek (Decca, Supraphon, and Chandos), and major works of Handel, [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], [[Bohuslav Martin\u016f|Martin\u016f]], [[Richard Strauss]], [[Dmitri Shostakovich|Shostakovich]], [[Jean Sibelius|Sibelius]], [[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]], [[Edward Elgar|Elgar]], [[Frederick Delius|Delius]], [[William Walton|Walton]], [[Gustav Holst|Holst]], and [[Joseph Haydn|Haydn]], among many others.\n\nIn 1953, he conducted Sullivan's [[Cello Concerto (Sullivan)|cello concerto]], broadcast on the BBC.<ref name=GSNews/> Sullivan's manuscript and most of the orchestra parts were destroyed in a fire, and more than three decades after that single BBC performance, in collaboration with David Mackie, Mackerras reconstructed the concerto, conducting its first performance with cellist [[Julian Lloyd Webber]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] at [[Barbican Centre|Barbican Hall]], London, in April 1986, and a recording for EMI shortly afterwards.<ref>Shepherd, Marc. [http://gasdisc.oakapplepress.com/sullorch.htm#concerto \"Concerto for Cello and Orchestra in D (1866)\"], Discography of Sir Arthur Sullivan: Orchestral and Band Music, Gilbert and Sullivan Discography, 12 July 2009, retrieved 2 October 2015</ref><ref>{{Cite web  | url =https://www.gsarchive.net/whowaswho/M/MackerrasCharles.htm | title =D'Oyly Carte Opera Company: Charles Mackerras | publisher =The Gilbert and Sullivan Archive | last  =Stone | first =David | year =2002 | accessdate =11 June 2007}}</ref> For [[Telarc]] in the 1990s, with [[Welsh National Opera]]'s chorus and orchestra, he also conducted Gilbert and Sullivan's ''[[Trial by Jury]]'', ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'', ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'', ''[[The Mikado]]'' and ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]''.<ref name=GSNews/>\n\nMackerras's discography also includes a recording of Britten's ''[[Gloriana]]'', which won ''Gramophone'' magazine's \"Best Opera Recording\" in 1994.<ref name=\"Reuters\"/> In 1997,  Mackerras recorded ''Le delizie dell'amor'', with the soprano [[Andrea Rost]], for Sony Classical. His most recent release for that label was ''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' with the Hanover Band (S2K 63174). Other recent recordings for Sony Classical include [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin|Chopin]]'s two piano concertos with [[Emanuel Ax]] and the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]] (SK 60771) and (SK 63371). He also recorded Dvo\u0159\u00e1k's ''[[Rusalka (opera)|Rusalka]]'' (Decca) and ''Slavonic Dances (Supraphon)'', [[Josef Suk (composer)|Josef Suk]]'s ''A Summer Tale'' (Decca), Mozart's [[Piano Concerto]]s Nos. 20 and 24 with [[Alfred Brendel]] (Philips), and Brahms's two orchestral serenades (Telarc). For [[Linn Records]] he recorded a two-SACD set of Mozart's last four symphonies with the Scottish Chamber Orchestra in August 2007.<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://www.sa-cd.net/showtitle/5062 | title =Entry for Mozart Symphonies 38\u201341 | publisher =SA-CD.net | accessdate =5 June 2008}}</ref>  His final recording was Suk's ''[[Asrael Symphony]]'', which was the composer's response to the deaths of his father-in-law Dvo\u0159\u00e1k and wife in quick succession.  It was recorded not long after the death of Mackerras's own daughter Fiona.\n\n==Honours==\nCharles Mackerras was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[1974 New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46162|supp=y|page=8|date=1 January 1974}}</ref> and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[1979 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47723|supp=y|page=1|date=30 December 1978}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47792|page=3365|date=13 March 1979}}</ref> In 1978, he was presented with the [[Jan\u00e1\u010dek Medal]] for services to Czech music, on stage at the [[Coliseum Theatre]], by the Czechoslovak ambassador.<ref>Phelan 1987, p. ? {{Page needed|date=September 2010}}</ref> In 1990, he was awarded an Honorary Degree by the [[University of Hull]]. In 1996, he received the Medal of Merit from the Czech Republic, and, in 1997 he was made a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC) for services to music and Australian music.<ref name=\"ClassicFM\"/><ref name=AC>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=870019&search_type=advanced&showInd=true Companion of the Order of Australia], AC, 26 January 1997, itsanhonour.gov.au. Citation: \"For service to music as an operatic conductor and for the promotion of the international status of Australian music.\"</ref> In 2000 he was awarded the [[Hanno R. Ellenbogen Citizenship Award]] by the [[Prague Society for International Cooperation]].<ref name=HR>[http://praguesociety.org/content/hre-awards-history-winners-origin Hanno R. Ellenbogen Citizenship Award] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903124001/http://praguesociety.org/content/hre-awards-history-winners-origin |date=3 September 2014 }}, 3 September 2014, praguesociety.org</ref>  In 2001, he was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]], created to mark the centenary of the [[Federation of Australia]].<ref name=CM>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1127011&search_type=quick&showInd=true Centenary Medal], 1 January 2001, itsanhonour.gov.au. Citation: \"For service to Australian society and music\"</ref> In 2003 he was made a [[Companion of Honour]] (CH) in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56963|supp=1|page=4|date=14 June 2003}}</ref> In 2005, he was presented with the [[Royal Philharmonic Society]] Gold Medal,<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://www.royalphilharmonicsociety.org.uk/?page=awards/gold/goldmedallist2001.html | title =Gold Medallists 2000 to date | publisher =Royal Philharmonic Society | accessdate  =14 September 2009}}</ref> and he was also the first recipient of the [[Queen's Medal for Music]], announced by the [[Master of the Queen's Music]], Sir [[Peter Maxwell Davies]], on the stage of the [[Royal Albert Hall]] before a Proms performance of ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]''.<ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/07_july/16/proms.shtml | title =First winner of The Queen's Medal for Music announced at BBC Proms | publisher  =[[BBC]] | date =16 July 2005 | accessdate  =14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*{{Cite book| last=Phelan  | first=Nancy | title=Charles Mackerras: A Musician's Musician | location=London | publisher=Victor Gollancz | year=1987 | isbn=0-575-03620-6 }}\n* Priest, Joan (1986). ''Gentlemen and Scholars: A Biography of the Mackerras Family''. Brisbane: Boolarong Publications. {{ISBN|0-86439-013-0}}.\n*{{Cite book| editor=Simeone, Nigel |editor2=John Tyrrell |title=Charles Mackerras | location=Woodbridge | publisher=Boydell Press | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-84383-966-8 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=q38032|label=Charles Mackerras}}\n*[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Mackerras-Charles.htm Charles Mackerras] at the Bach Cantatas Website\n*{{IMDb name|0533431}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070705084026/http://www.classicstoday.com/features/f1_0200.asp Charles Mackerras profile and interview] at ClassicsToday.com\n*[http://www.philharmonia.co.uk/thephilharmoniaorchestra/sircharlesmackerras/ Charles Mackerras biography] [http://www.philharmonia.co.uk/thesoundexchange/backstage/interviews/charles_mackerras/ and interview] at the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110609140627/http://www.cbso.co.uk/?page=mycbso%2Fpodcasts%2Fdetail.html&id=4 Interview with Charles Mackerras] at the [[City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra]]\n*[https://www.gsarchive.net/whowaswho/M/MackerrasCharles.htm Profile focusing on Mackerras's Sullivan connections]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060928221149/http://www.askonasholt.co.uk/green/green/home.nsf/ArtistDetails/Sir%20Charles%20Mackerras%20CH%20AC%20CBE Recent profile of Mackerras]\n*{{YouTube|EZtSJeJzFh8|Clip of Mackerras conducting}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/music/gallery/2010/jul/15/charles-mackerras-in-pictures#/?picture=364906254&index=0 Photos of Mackerras throughout his life]\n*Mackerras and the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]] at the  [http://aso.gov.au/titles/music/sydney-opera-house-opening 'Sydney Opera House Opening Concert'] in 1973\n*[http://www.bruceduffie.com/mackerras.html Interview with Charles Mackerras], 6 November 1986\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-culture}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[BBC Concert Orchestra|Principal Conductor, BBC Concert Orchestra]] | before=Gilbert Vinter | years=1954\u20131956 | after=[[Vil\u00e9m Tausk\u00fd]]\n}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[English National Opera|Music Director, Sadler's Wells (English National Opera from 1974)]] | before=[[Bryan Balkwill]] and [[Mario Bernardi]]| years=1970\u20131977 | after=[[Charles Groves]]\n}}\n{{Succession box| title=[[Welsh National Opera|Music Director, Welsh National Opera]] | before=[[Richard Armstrong (conductor)|Richard Armstrong]] | years=1987\u20131992 | after=[[Carlo Rizzi (conductor)|Carlo Rizzi]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Sydney Symphony conductors}}\n{{Queen's Medal for Music}}\n{{Gramophone Hall of Fame}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Classical music}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mackerras, Charles}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Australian classical oboists]]\n[[Category:Male oboists]]\n[[Category:Australian music arrangers]]\n[[Category:People from Schenectady, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Sydney]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Parramatta]]\n[[Category:Sydney Conservatorium of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Music directors (opera)]]\n[[Category:Pye Records artists]]\n[[Category:Honorary Members of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Honorary Members of the Royal Philharmonic Society]]\n[[Category:Australian Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Australia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Centenary Medal]]\n[[Category:Australian Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Conductors (music) awarded knighthoods]]\n[[Category:Australian Members of the Order of the Companions of Honour]]\n[[Category:Royal Philharmonic Society Gold Medallists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Recipients of Medal of Merit (Czech Republic)]]\n[[Category:People educated at Sydney Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Aloysius' College (Sydney)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2012}}\n[[File:Sir Charles Mackerras.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.15|Mackerras in 2005]]\n'''Sir Alan Charles Maclaurin Mackerras''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AC|CH|CBE}} ({{IPAc-en|m|\u0259|\u02c8|k|\u025br|\u0259|s}}; {{Nowrap|17 November}} 1925{{spaced ndash}}{{Nowrap|14 July}} 2010)<ref name=\"Australian\">{{Cite news| url  =http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/arts/symphony-mourns-death-of-conductor-charles-mackerras/story-e6frg8n6-1225892114358  | title =Symphony mourns death of conductor Charles Mackerras  | last =Wilson | first =Ashleigh | work =[[The Australian]]|date=15 July 2010| accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url =http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/music/sir-charles-mackerras-dies/story-e6frexl9-1225892206801 | title =Sir Charles Mackerras dies | work =[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> was an Australian [[conducting|conductor]]. He was an authority on the operas of [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek|Jan\u00e1\u010dek]] and [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]], and the [[comic opera]]s of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]].  He was long associated with the [[English National Opera]] (and its predecessor) and [[Welsh National Opera]] and was the first Australian chief conductor of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMackerras was born in [[Schenectady, New York]], to Australian parents, Alan Mackerras and Catherine MacLaurin.<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/music-obituaries/7892957/Sir-Charles-Mackerras.html | title =Sir Charles Mackerras  | date  =15 July 2010 | work  =[[The Daily Telegraph]] | publisher =[[Telegraph Media Group]]  | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> His father was an electrical engineer and a [[Quaker]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> In 1928, when Charles was aged two, the family returned to [[Sydney]], Australia.  They initially lived in the suburb of [[Rose Bay, New South Wales|Rose Bay]], and in 1933 they moved to the then semi-rural suburb of [[Turramurra]].<ref name=\"Herald obit\">{{Cite news | url =http://www.smh.com.au/national/obituaries/scion-of-an-australian-dynasty-conducted-for-the-whole-world-20100715-10ck6.html | title =Scion of an Australian dynasty conducted for the whole world | last =Maunder | first =Patricia | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher =[[Fairfax Media]] | date =16 July 2010 | accessdate=16 July 2010}}</ref> Mackerras was the eldest of seven children. His siblings were Alastair (1928\u201399), [[Neil Mackerras|Neil]] (1930\u201387), Joan (b. 1934), Elisabeth (b. 1937) and twins [[Malcolm Mackerras|Malcolm]] and [[Colin Mackerras|Colin]] (b. 1939).<ref name=Birthday90>Simeone, Nigel. \"Sir Charles Mackerras (1925\u20132010): A Lifetime of Gilbert and Sullivan\" (Part I), ''Gilbert and Sullivan News'', Vol. V, No. 9, Autumn/Winter 2015, pp. 12\u201314, The Gilbert and Sullivan Society</ref> They are descendants of the pioneer Australian musician [[Isaac Nathan]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Mackerras studied violin at the age of seven and later the flute.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> He was setting poems to music at eight and wrote a piano concerto when he was 12.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/>\n\nMackerras initially attended his father's alma mater, [[Sydney Grammar School]], and also [[St Aloysius' College (Sydney)|St Aloysius College]] in Sydney.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> While at Sydney Grammar, he showed a precocious talent by composing operas and conducting student performances in his early teens, but his non-musical studies suffered.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> At all-male St Aloysius, he participated in the school's [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] productions, playing the roles of Kate in ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'', Leila in ''[[Iolanthe]]'' and Ko-Ko in ''[[The Mikado]]''.<ref name=Birthday90/> Unconvinced that music was a viable profession, his parents removed the young Mackerras from temptation by sending him to board at [[The King's School, Parramatta|The King's School]]. The school's focus on sport and discipline led the young artist to run away several times, and he was eventually expelled.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> At age 16, Mackerras studied oboe, piano and composition at the [[Sydney Conservatorium of Music|NSW State Conservatorium of Music]]. He earned additional income from writing orchestral scores from recordings.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/>\n\n==Early career==\nBy 1941, while still at the conservatory, Mackerras began to get professional performing jobs in Sydney, partly because he was too young to join the military, while older musicians had been called up to go to the war. From 1941 to 1942, Mackerras played the oboe for the [[J. C. Williamson]] Company during one of their Gilbert and Sullivan seasons, and he was a rehearsal pianist for the Kirsova ballet company.<ref name=Birthday90/> In 1943, Mackerras joined the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra|ABC Sydney Orchestra]], under [[Malcolm Sargent]], as second oboist and at age 19, became principal oboist.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/><ref name=\"ClassicFM\">{{Cite web | url =http://www.classicfm.co.uk/music/music-news-and-features/sir-charles-mackerras-dies | title =Sir Charles Mackerras dies | date =15 July 2010 | work =[[Classic FM (UK)|Classic FM]] | publisher =[[Global Radio]] | accessdate =15 July 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"GuardianWeaver\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/15/conductor-charles-mackerras-dies | title =Conductor Charles Mackerras dies | last =Weaver | first =Matthew | work =[[The Guardian]]|date=15 July 2010 | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> On {{Nowrap|6 February}} 1947, Mackerras sailed for England on the RMS Rangitiki<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> intending to pursue conducting.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> He joined [[Sadler's Wells Theatre]] as an orchestral oboist and [[Cor anglais (English horn)|cor anglais]] player.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> He later won a [[British Council]] Scholarship, enabling him to study conducting with [[V\u00e1clav Talich]] at the Prague Academy of Music.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> While there, he formed a strong friendship with [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Tancibudek]], Principal Oboe of the [[Czech Philharmonic]], who introduced him to the operas of [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek]], thus commencing Mackerras's lifelong passion for that composer's music.<ref>[http://www.adrs.org.au/jiri_tancibudek.html Australasian Double Reed Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110219150559/http://www.adrs.org.au/jiri_tancibudek.html |date=19 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn August 1947, shortly before the couple set off for Prague, Mackerras married Judy Wilkins, a clarinettist at Sadlers' Wells.<ref name=Birthday90/> They had two daughters, Fiona and Catherine.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/><ref name=\"GuardianObituary\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jul/15/sir-charles-mackerras-obituary | title =Sir Charles Mackerras obituary | last =Blyth | first =Alan | date =15 July 2010 | work =[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> Fiona died of cancer in September 2006.<ref>[http://www.scotsman.com/news/conductor-led-concert-hours-after-death-of-his-daughter-1-1139314 \"Conductor led concert hours after death of his daughter\"], ''The Scotsman'', 8 September 2006. Retrieved 16 October 2014</ref> He was also the uncle of the Australian conductor [[Alexander Briger]]<ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.smh.com.au/news/arts/a-dream-comes-true/2006/08/21/1156012471023.html?page=fullpage | title =A Dream Comes True | last =Meacham | first =Steve | date =22 August 2006 | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher =[[Fairfax Media]] | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref> and the British-born American conductor Drostan Hall, Music Director of [[Camerata Chicago]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Camerata Chicago celebrates 10th anniversary|url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-05-15/entertainment/ct-ent-0515-classical-camerata-20130515_1_chamber-orchestra-small-orchestra-charles-mackerras|website = tribunedigital-chicagotribune|accessdate = 2015-12-13}}</ref>\n\nReturning to England from Prague in 1948, Mackerras rejoined Sadler's Wells as an assistant conductor and began his lifelong association with the Sadler's Wells Opera, now [[English National Opera]], conducting, among others, [[Leo\u0161 Jan\u00e1\u010dek|Jan\u00e1\u010dek]], [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]], [[Christoph Willibald Gluck|Gluck]], [[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]], and [[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> In the 1950s, well before the \"authenticity\" movement had come to general notice, Mackerras focused on the study and practical realization of period performance techniques, culminating in his landmark 1959 recording of Handel's ''[[Music for the Royal Fireworks]]'' using the original wind band instrumentation. In his 1965 performance of ''[[The Marriage of Figaro]]'', he added the [[ornament (music)|ornamentation]] in a [[historically informed performance|historically informed]] style.\n\nMackerras also strongly championed the music of Jan\u00e1\u010dek outside Czechoslovakia, where Mackerras himself judged his work with Jan\u00e1\u010dek as his single most important legacy to music.<ref name=\"Moss\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/aug/20/classicalmusicandopera | title =The modest maestro | last =Moss | first =Stephen | work =[[The Guardian]]|date=20 August 2005|accessdate=18 September 2007}}</ref> In 1951, he conducted the British premiere of ''[[K\u00e1\u0165a Kabanov\u00e1]]''. He was also a noted authority on [[Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Mozart]]'s operas and those of Sir [[Arthur Sullivan]]. His ballet with [[John Cranko]], ''[[Pineapple Poll]]'', is an arrangement of Sullivan music with a story based on one of [[W. S. Gilbert]]'s ''[[Bab Ballads]]''. The piece premiered in 1951, soon after the expiration of copyright on Sullivan's music, and continues to be a popular light music favourite in English speaking countries.<ref name=Birthday90/> Mackerras later arranged music by [[Giuseppe Verdi]] for the ballet ''[[The Lady and the Fool]]''. He also arranged a suite from [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]]'s score for the 1946 film ''[[The Overlanders (film)|The Overlanders]]'', after Ireland's death in 1962.\n\nHe was principal conductor of the [[BBC Concert Orchestra]] from 1954 to 1956.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news | url =http://in.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-50143820100715 | title =Factbox \u2013 Orchestra conductor Charles Mackerras dies | last =Cutler | first =David | work =[[Reuters]] | date =15 July 2010 | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> \nIn 1962, he conducted the [[S.A. Symphony Orchestra]] in the Australian premi\u00e8re of Strauss's ''[[Ariadne auf Naxos]]'' as part of the [[Adelaide Festival]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catalog.slsa.sa.gov.au:443/record=b2092816~S1|title=S.A. Symphony Orchestra rehearsal|publisher=State Library of South Australia|year=1962|access-date=30 October 2019}} Photograph may only be viewed at the Library.</ref> with Adelaide-born [[Una Hale]] in the title role.\nIn 1963, he made his debut at London's Covent Garden conducting Shostakovich's ''[[Lady Macbeth of the Mtsensk District (opera)|Katerina Izmailova]]''. He directed the [[Hamburg State Opera]] from 1965 to 1969 and the [[English National Opera]] from 1970 to 1977.<ref>Phelan 1987, p. ?? {{Page needed|date=May 2014}}</ref> In 1972, he made his [[Metropolitan Opera]] debut in New York conducting [[Christoph Willibald Gluck|Gluck]]'s ''[[Orfeo ed Euridice]]''. Mackerras worked closely with [[Benjamin Britten]] for a time until 1958, when, during rehearsals for the first performance of Britten's opera ''[[Noye's Fludde]]'', he made comments about Britten liking prepubescent boys' company and Britten subsequently stopped speaking to him.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> The events are described in John Bridcut's ''[[Britten's Children]]''.\n\nHe conducted the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]] and [[Birgit Nilsson]] in the opening concert of the Concert Hall of the [[Sydney Opera House]], in the presence of Queen Elizabeth&nbsp;II, in 1973.<ref name=\"GuardianWeaver\"/><ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/national-treasure-made-music-until-the-end-20100715-10clx.html | title =National treasure made music until the end | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher =[[Fairfax Media]] | date =16 July 2010 | accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nMackerras had conducted a few Gilbert and Sullivan productions for English National Opera, but his first experience as a guest conductor of the [[D'Oyly Carte Opera Company]] was for ''[[Trial by Jury]]'', ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'' and ''[[The Mikado]]'' during the 1975 D'Oyly Carte centenary season at the Savoy. He conducted ''[[Patience (opera)|Patience]]'' at the Proms in 1976, the first full-length Gilbert and Sullivan opera given complete at the Proms. In 1980 he joined the D'Oyly Carte Opera Trust and later its Board of Trustees. In the early 1980s he conducted two New Year's Eve broadcasts of [[Savoy opera]]s for the BBC, and his recordings of eight of the operas were broadcast in 1989 by BBC Radio 2 as part of a complete Gilbert and Sullivan series. He also conducted a centennial performance of Sullivan's ''[[The Golden Legend (cantata)|The Golden Legend]]'' in Leeds and the first staging of a complete Gilbert and Sullivan opera at the [[Royal Opera House]], ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]'', with [[Welsh National Opera]] in 1995.<ref name=GSNews>Simeone, Nigel. \"Sir Charles MacKerras (1925\u20132010): A Lifetime of Gilbert and Sullivan\", ''Gilbert and Sullivan News'', The Gilbert and Sullivan Society (London), Vol. V, No. 10, Spring 2016, pp. 4\u20137</ref> In 1980, also, he became the first non-Briton to conduct the [[BBC Symphony Orchestra]] at the [[Last Night of the Proms]].<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/>\n\nIn 1982 Mackerras was the first Australian national appointed chief conductor of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]], a post he held until 1985.<ref name=\"Herald obit\"/> he directed the [[Welsh National Opera]] from 1987 to 1992, where his Jan\u00e1\u010dek productions won particular praise. One of the highlights of the 1991 season was the reopening of the Estates Theatre in Prague, scene of the original premiere of Mozart's ''[[Don Giovanni]]'', in which Mackerras conducted a new production of that opera to mark the bicentenary of Mozart's death. As Conductor Emeritus of Welsh National Opera, his successes included ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'', ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]'', and ''[[La clemenza di Tito]]'' (all of which productions were brought to London). He was the principal guest conductor of the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] (SCO) from 1992 to 1995, and held the title of Conductor Laureate with the SCO.  He was principal guest conductor of the [[Royal Philharmonic Orchestra]] from 1993 to 1996. During the same period, he was also principal guest conductor of the [[San Francisco Opera]]. From 1998 to 2001 he was the music director of the [[Orchestra of St. Luke's]]. From 1987, he regularly conducted the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]] and was appointed Emeritus Conductor in 2007.\n\nIn 2004 he became principal guest conductor of the [[Philharmonia Orchestra]]. He was also principal guest conductor of the [[Czech Philharmonic]]. With the Royal Opera, he conducted productions of [[Charles Gounod|Gounod]]'s ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette]]'' and [[George Frideric Handel|Handel]]'s ''[[Semele]]''. Mackerras also had a long association with the [[Metropolitan Opera]], where he conducted ''[[The Makropulos Affair (opera)|The Makropulos Case]]'', ''[[K\u00e1\u0165a Kabanov\u00e1]]'', ''[[Le proph\u00e8te]]'', ''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'', ''[[Billy Budd (opera)|Billy Budd]]'', ''[[Hansel and Gretel]]'' and ''[[The Magic Flute]]''.\n\nIn August 2008, Mackerras was announced as the new [[Title of honor|Honorary President]] of the [[Edinburgh International Festival]] Society.<ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.eif.co.uk/news/edinburgh-international-festival-society-announces-sir-charles-mackerras-new-honorary-president | title =Edinburgh International Festival Society Announces Sir Charles Mackerras as New Honorary President | year =2008 | accessdate =2008-08-24 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080823141033/http://www.eif.co.uk/news/edinburgh-international-festival-society-announces-sir-charles-mackerras-new-honorary-president | archivedate =23 August 2008 | df =dmy-all }}</ref> He was only the second person to hold this role, after [[Yehudi Menuhin]]. As the original part of the [[Edinburgh Festival|largest arts festival in the world]], the Edinburgh International Festival featured performances from Mackerras throughout six decades since his first in 1952. Mackerras summarised his strategy for working with an orchestra as follows:\n{{quote|I believe it's very important to edit orchestral parts explicitly and as thoroughly as possible, so that the musicians can play them without too much rehearsal. For instance, the other day I did all the [[Robert Schumann|Schumann]] symphonies with very little rehearsal at all. Because the parts were clearly marked, particularly with regard to dynamics, we were able to play them without needing to do that much preliminary work, focusing our attention on the interpretation rather than the technical business of who plays too loud or too soft.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.classicstoday.com/features/f1_0200.asp |title=A Talk With Sir Charles Mackerras |publisher=Classics Today |last=Hurwitz |first=David |year=2000 |accessdate=15 April 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705084026/http://www.classicstoday.com/features/f1_0200.asp |archivedate=5 July 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>}}\n\nMackerras was the President of [[Trinity College of Music]], London.<ref name=\"ClassicFM\"/> He also served as Music Advisor to [[City Opera of Vancouver]], a professional chamber opera company led by conductor [[Charles Barber (conductor)|Charles Barber]].<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://cityoperavancouver.com/about/whos-who | title =Who's Who | publisher  =[[City Opera of Vancouver]] | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> He was also a Patron of [[Bampton Classical Opera]].<ref>https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yaCfBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA143&lpg=PA143&dq=mackerras+bampton&source=bl&ots=WLRVB5d3T6&sig=ACfU3U3Fs5aHuL6eD4J_x58uk_wTNTeWPg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiD2Jq87s_oAhUHHMAKHaCLByIQ6AEwAnoECAwQKQ#v=onepage&q=mackerras%20bampton&f=false</ref> From 1999 Mackerras was a Patron of the Australian children's cancer charity Redkite.<ref>[http://www.redkite.org.au Redkite website]</ref>\n\nOn 18 December 2008, Mackerras served as the conductor for [[Alfred Brendel]]'s final concert performance with the [[Vienna Philharmonic]]. Mackerras's last performance at the [[BBC Proms]] included Gilbert and Sullivan's ''[[Patience (opera)|Patience]]''.<ref name=Birthday90/> His final public performance saw him conduct ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]'' at [[Glyndebourne]] in the summer of 2010.<ref>{{Cite news | url =https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/opera/7891990/A-tribute-to-Sir-Charles-Mackerras.html | title =A tribute to Sir Charles Mackerras |last=Christiansen|first=Rupert|authorlink=Rupert Christiansen| work =[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=15 July 2010|accessdate=15 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMackerras died in London on 14 July 2010 at the age of 84, having suffered from cancer.<ref name=\"Australian\"/><ref name=\"SMH\">{{Cite news | url =http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-national/conductor-sir-charles-mackerras-dies-20100715-10c2w.html | title =Conductor Sir Charles Mackerras dies | work =[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] | publisher  =[[Fairfax Media]] | date =15 July 2010 | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> Throughout his final illness, he had continued to conduct, and had been scheduled to direct two of the [[BBC Proms]] on {{Nowrap|25 July}} and {{Nowrap|29 July}} 2010. He was also due to conduct the [[Scottish Chamber Orchestra]] performing Mozart's ''[[Idomeneo]]'' at the [[Edinburgh International Festival]] in August 2010, which would have been his 56th appearance at the festival.<ref name=SMH/><ref name=\"BBC\">{{Cite news | url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment+arts-10646000 | title =Conductor Sir Charles Mackerras dies aged 84 | work =[[BBC News]] | publisher =[[BBC]] | date =15 July 2010 | accessdate =15 July 2010}}</ref> The director of the BBC Proms, Roger Wright, announced that a Prom would be dedicated to Mackerras's memory.<ref name=\"BBC\"/> Wright paid tribute to Mackerras, saying \"Sir Charles was a great conductor and his loss will be deeply felt by musicians and audiences alike\",<ref name=\"BBC\"/> while Rory Jeffes of the [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]] said that Australia had \"lost a living treasure\".<ref name=\"BBC\"/>  Mackerras is survived by his wife, Judy, and their daughter, Catherine.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/><ref name=\"Herald obit\"/><ref>{{Cite news | url =http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/15/charles-mackerras-a-wide-ranging-conductor-dies/ | title      =Charles Mackerras, a Wide-Ranging Conductor, Dies at 84 | last =Wakin | first =Daniel J | date =15 July 2010 | work =[[The New York Times]] | publisher =[[The New York Times Company]] |accessdate  =15 July 2010}}</ref> His funeral was held at [[St Paul's, Covent Garden]] on 23 July 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://announcements.thetimes.co.uk/obituaries/timesonline-uk/obituary.aspx?n=charles-mackerras&pid=144188105|title=Charles Mackerras|work=The Times (personal announcements)|date=20 July 2010|accessdate=20 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nMackerras made his earliest records for [[EMI]], in the final days of 78 rpm records, and he continued recording well into the era of compact discs in the multi-channel [[Super Audio CD]] format.  In 1952, he conducted his first recording of his own ''[[Pineapple Poll]]'' ballet, which was issued on twelve sides, and subsequently transferred to LP. He later conducted two more complete recordings of the ballet.<ref name=GSNews/> Some of his early recording sessions were for [[Walter Legge]], standing in when [[Otto Klemperer]] and other eminent conductors were ill.<ref name=Gramophone>{{Cite news|url= |title=Charles Mackerras|work=The Gramophone|author=[[Alan Blyth|Blyth, Alan]]|date=March 1975|pages=1, 626}}</ref> He did not always restrict himself to the classical repertoire.  For example, on {{Nowrap|4 May}} 1955 he recorded [[Albert Arlen]]'s song ''[[Clancy of the Overflow]]'' (to [[Banjo Paterson]]'s poem) with [[Peter Dawson (bass-baritone)|Peter Dawson]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]].<ref>[http://members.optusnet.com.au/johnhrogers/c.htm optus net]</ref>\n\nA smaller UK record company, [[Pye Records]], asked Mackerras to record Handel's ''[[Music for the Royal Fireworks]]''. 'We had to do that in the middle of the night, in order to get our twenty-six oboes together.'<ref name=Gramophone/> The recording, issued in 1959, was received with critical acclaim for attempting to reproduce the sound Handel would have heard, rather than the smoother orchestral arrangements usually played at that time.\n\nIn the 1960s Mackerras made the first recording of the Italian version of Gluck's ''[[Orfeo ed Euridice|Orfeo]]''. For [[Deutsche Grammophon|DG]] he conducted Purcell's ''[[Dido and Aeneas]]'', and for EMI a 'new-look' ''[[Messiah (Handel)|Messiah]]'', with scholarly texts, small forces and sprightly tempi. He followed that up with Handel's ''[[Saul (Handel)|Saul]]'' and ''[[Israel in Egypt]]'' for DG. He also recorded the first complete ''[[Roberto Devereux]]'' with [[Beverly Sills]]. In 1986, he conducted the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] in the soundtrack to [[Carroll Ballard]]'s film version of ''[[The Nutcracker]]'' (better known as ''Nutcracker: The Motion Picture''), the first full-length film version of [[Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky|Tchaikovsky]]'s ballet to be given a major release in theatres.\n\nMackerras recorded three [[Gustav Mahler|Mahler]] symphonies and all of the symphonies of Mozart, [[Johannes Brahms|Brahms]] and [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]].<ref name=\"Reuters\"/> Along with the Mozart operas, these recordings continue to attract critical acclaim; as do his recordings of the operas of Jan\u00e1\u010dek (Decca, Supraphon, and Chandos), and major works of Handel, [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k|Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]], [[Bohuslav Martin\u016f|Martin\u016f]], [[Richard Strauss]], [[Dmitri Shostakovich|Shostakovich]], [[Jean Sibelius|Sibelius]], [[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]], [[Edward Elgar|Elgar]], [[Frederick Delius|Delius]], [[William Walton|Walton]], [[Gustav Holst|Holst]], and [[Joseph Haydn|Haydn]], among many others.\n\nIn 1953, he conducted Sullivan's [[Cello Concerto (Sullivan)|cello concerto]], broadcast on the BBC.<ref name=GSNews/> Sullivan's manuscript and most of the orchestra parts were destroyed in a fire, and more than three decades after that single BBC performance, in collaboration with David Mackie, Mackerras reconstructed the concerto, conducting its first performance with cellist [[Julian Lloyd Webber]] and the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] at [[Barbican Centre|Barbican Hall]], London, in April 1986, and a recording for EMI shortly afterwards.<ref>Shepherd, Marc. [http://gasdisc.oakapplepress.com/sullorch.htm#concerto \"Concerto for Cello and Orchestra in D (1866)\"], Discography of Sir Arthur Sullivan: Orchestral and Band Music, Gilbert and Sullivan Discography, 12 July 2009, retrieved 2 October 2015</ref><ref>{{Cite web  | url =https://www.gsarchive.net/whowaswho/M/MackerrasCharles.htm | title =D'Oyly Carte Opera Company: Charles Mackerras | publisher =The Gilbert and Sullivan Archive | last  =Stone | first =David | year =2002 | accessdate =11 June 2007}}</ref> For [[Telarc]] in the 1990s, with [[Welsh National Opera]]'s chorus and orchestra, he also conducted Gilbert and Sullivan's ''[[Trial by Jury]]'', ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]'', ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]'', ''[[The Mikado]]'' and ''[[The Yeomen of the Guard]]''.<ref name=GSNews/>\n\nMackerras's discography also includes a recording of Britten's ''[[Gloriana]]'', which won ''Gramophone'' magazine's \"Best Opera Recording\" in 1994.<ref name=\"Reuters\"/> In 1997,  Mackerras recorded ''Le delizie dell'amor'', with the soprano [[Andrea Rost]], for Sony Classical. His most recent release for that label was ''[[Lucia di Lammermoor]]'' with the Hanover Band (S2K 63174). Other recent recordings for Sony Classical include [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Chopin|Chopin]]'s two piano concertos with [[Emanuel Ax]] and the [[Orchestra of the Age of Enlightenment]] (SK 60771) and (SK 63371). He also recorded Dvo\u0159\u00e1k's ''[[Rusalka (opera)|Rusalka]]'' (Decca) and ''Slavonic Dances (Supraphon)'', [[Josef Suk (composer)|Josef Suk]]'s ''A Summer Tale'' (Decca), Mozart's [[Piano Concerto]]s Nos. 20 and 24 with [[Alfred Brendel]] (Philips), and Brahms's two orchestral serenades (Telarc). For [[Linn Records]] he recorded a two-SACD set of Mozart's last four symphonies with the Scottish Chamber Orchestra in August 2007.<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://www.sa-cd.net/showtitle/5062 | title =Entry for Mozart Symphonies 38\u201341 | publisher =SA-CD.net | accessdate =5 June 2008}}</ref>  His final recording was Suk's ''[[Asrael Symphony]]'', which was the composer's response to the deaths of his father-in-law Dvo\u0159\u00e1k and wife in quick succession.  It was recorded not long after the death of Mackerras's own daughter Fiona.\n\n==Honours==\nCharles Mackerras was appointed a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[1974 New Year Honours]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=46162|supp=y|page=8|date=1 January 1974}}</ref> and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[1979 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47723|supp=y|page=1|date=30 December 1978}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=47792|page=3365|date=13 March 1979}}</ref> In 1978, he was presented with the [[Jan\u00e1\u010dek Medal]] for services to Czech music, on stage at the [[Coliseum Theatre]], by the Czechoslovak ambassador.<ref>Phelan 1987, p. ? {{Page needed|date=September 2010}}</ref> In 1990, he was awarded an Honorary Degree by the [[University of Hull]]. In 1996, he received the Medal of Merit from the Czech Republic, and, in 1997 he was made a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] (AC) for services to music and Australian music.<ref name=\"ClassicFM\"/><ref name=AC>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=870019&search_type=advanced&showInd=true Companion of the Order of Australia], AC, 26 January 1997, itsanhonour.gov.au. Citation: \"For service to music as an operatic conductor and for the promotion of the international status of Australian music.\"</ref> In 2000 he was awarded the [[Hanno R. Ellenbogen Citizenship Award]] by the [[Prague Society for International Cooperation]].<ref name=HR>[http://praguesociety.org/content/hre-awards-history-winners-origin Hanno R. Ellenbogen Citizenship Award] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903124001/http://praguesociety.org/content/hre-awards-history-winners-origin |date=3 September 2014 }}, 3 September 2014, praguesociety.org</ref>  In 2001, he was awarded the [[Centenary Medal]], created to mark the centenary of the [[Federation of Australia]].<ref name=CM>[http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1127011&search_type=quick&showInd=true Centenary Medal], 1 January 2001, itsanhonour.gov.au. Citation: \"For service to Australian society and music\"</ref> In 2003 he was made a [[Companion of Honour]] (CH) in the [[Queen's Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=56963|supp=1|page=4|date=14 June 2003}}</ref> In 2005, he was presented with the [[Royal Philharmonic Society]] Gold Medal,<ref>{{Cite web | url =http://www.royalphilharmonicsociety.org.uk/?page=awards/gold/goldmedallist2001.html | title =Gold Medallists 2000 to date | publisher =Royal Philharmonic Society | accessdate  =14 September 2009}}</ref> and he was also the first recipient of the [[Queen's Medal for Music]], announced by the [[Master of the Queen's Music]], Sir [[Peter Maxwell Davies]], on the stage of the [[Royal Albert Hall]] before a Proms performance of ''[[H.M.S. Pinafore]]''.<ref>{{Cite news | url =http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2005/07_july/16/proms.shtml | title =First winner of The Queen's Medal for Music announced at BBC Proms | publisher  =[[BBC]] | date =16 July 2005 | accessdate  =14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*{{Cite book| last=Phelan  | first=Nancy | title=Charles Mackerras: A Musician's Musician | location=London | publisher=Victor Gollancz | year=1987 | isbn=0-575-03620-6 }}\n* Priest, Joan (1986). ''Gentlemen and Scholars: A Biography of the Mackerras Family''. Brisbane: Boolarong Publications. {{ISBN|0-86439-013-0}}.\n*{{Cite book| editor=Simeone, Nigel |editor2=John Tyrrell |title=Charles Mackerras | location=Woodbridge | publisher=Boydell Press | year=2015 | isbn=978-1-84383-966-8 }}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=q38032|label=Charles Mackerras}}\n*[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Mackerras-Charles.htm Charles Mackerras] at the Bach Cantatas Website\n*{{IMDb name|0533431}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070705084026/http://www.classicstoday.com/features/f1_0200.asp