.google.com/books?id=skYIAQAAMAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Courage Books|isbn=978-0-89471-412-2}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|editor-last=Edmondson|editor-first=Jacqueline|title=Music in American Life: An Encyclopedia of the Songs, Styles, Stars, and Stories that Shaped our Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TQPXAQAAQBAJ|year=2013|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39348-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Lenig|first=Stuart|title=The Twisted Tale of Glam Rock|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xGmj-tCfYC0C|year=2010|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-37986-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Hewitt|first1=Paolo|authorlink1=|last2=Hellier|first2=John|title=Steve Marriott: All Too Beautiful|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CxhzCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT162|year=2015|publisher=Dean Street Press|isbn=978-1-910570-69-2}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Macan|first=Edward|title=Rocking the Classics: English Progressive Rock and the Counterculture|url=https://archive.org/details/rockingclassicse0000maca|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-509887-7}}\n* {{Citation|last=Martin|first=Bill|authorlink=Bill Martin (philosophy)|year=1996|title=Music of Yes: Structure and Vision in Progressive Rock|publisher=Open Court|location=Chicago}}\n*{{cite book|last=Martin|first=Bill|authorlink=Bill Martin (philosophy)|title=Listening to the Future: The Time of Progressive Rock, 1968\u20131978|year=1998|publisher=[[Open Court Publishing Company|Open Court]]|isbn=0-8126-9368-X|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan|title=The Beatles: Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4y-oDmH2YzYC|year=1997|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-57484-6}}\n* {{Citation|last=Moore|first=Allan|title=Jethro Tull's Aqualung|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DMWoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA22|date=2004|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4411-1315-3|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Moore|first=Allan|title=Song Means: Analysing and Interpreting Recorded Popular Song|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S6DeCwAAQBAJ|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-05265-4}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Palmberg|first1=Mai|last2=Baaz|first2=Maria Eriksson|title=Same and Other: Negotiating African Identity in Cultural Production|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O7JSZaj51z8C&pg=PA51|year=2001|publisher=Nordic Africa Institute|isbn=978-91-7106-477-6}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Philo|first=Simon|title=British Invasion: The Crosscurrents of Musical Influence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WqiDBQAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-0-8108-8627-8}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Prown|first1=Pete|last2=Newquist|first2=Harvey P.|title=Legends of Rock Guitar: The Essential Reference of Rock's Greatest Guitarists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=60Jde3l7WNwC&pg=PA78|year=1997|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=978-0-7935-4042-6}}\n* {{Citation|ref=harv|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|authorlink=Simon Reynolds|title=On Record: Rock, Pop and the Written Word|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lauJAgAAQBAJ|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-93951-0|chapter=New Pop and its Aftermath}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Roberts|first1=Jim|last2=Rooksby|first2=Rikky|title=The Songwriting Sourcebook: How to Turn Chords Into Great Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6FMCdIDSsmgC&pg=PA137|year=2003|publisher=Hal Leonard|isbn=978-1-61780-033-7}}\n* {{cite book |ref=harv |last=Sanchez |first=Luis |title=The Beach Boys' Smile |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FC0_AwAAQBAJ |year=2014 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-62356-956-3}}\n* {{Citation|ref=harv|last1=Shepherd|first1=John|last2=Virden |first2=Phil|last3=Vulliamy |first3=Graham|title=Whose Music?: A Sociology of Musical Languages|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mxk5JqiEu9AC&pg=PA199|year=1977|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-4147-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Turner|first=Steve|title=Beatles '66: The Revolutionary Year|year=2016|publisher=HarperLuxe|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-06-249713-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Willis|first=Paul E.|authorlink=Paul Willis|title=Profane Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7oWBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA219|year=2014|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-6514-7}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Zoppo|first=Donato|title=Prog: Una suite lunga mezzo secolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oAThBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT121|year=2014|publisher=Arcana|isbn=978-88-6231-639-2|language=Italian}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Lee|first=Edward|title=Music of the People: A Study of Popular Music in Great Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AgTaAAAAMAAJ|year=1970|publisher=Barrie & Jenkins}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Stump|first=Paul|title=The Music's All that Matters: A History of Progressive Rock|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OJ0mAQAAIAAJ|year=1997|publisher=Quartet Books|isbn=978-0-7043-8036-3}}\n\n{{Pop music}}\n{{Progressive music}}\n\n[[Category:Progressive pop| ]]\n[[Category:Pop music genres]]\n[[Category:Rock music genres]]\n[[Category:Progressive rock]]\n[[Category:20th-century music genres]]\n[[Category:Progressive music genres|Pop]]\n", "name_user": "41.114.110.101", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Simple)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progressive_pop"}
{"title_page": "Fred Rosen (author)", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|image =\n|imagesize =\n| name = Fred Rosen\n| caption =\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date= \n| birth_place = Brooklyn, [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = true crime author, [[journalist]]\n| nationality = American\n| period = \n| genre = [[Non-fiction]]\n| subject = [[True crime]], history\n| movement =\n| notableworks = ''Murdering the President'', ''Lobster Boy''\n| spouse =\n| partner =\n| children =\n| relatives =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| signature =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Fred Rosen''' is a former [[columnist]] for the Arts and Leisure Section of ''[[The New York Times]]'' and a [[true crime]] author in the United States.\n\n==Biography==\nRosen was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==Writing==\nRosen's published works include ''Lobster Boy'' about the murder of [[Grady Stiles]]. Rosen gave evidence in the trial against the killer.<ref name=Chronogram />\n\nHis two books for [[HarperCollins]] in 2007, ''There But For the Grace: Survivors of the 20th Century\u2019s Infamous Serial Killers'' and ''When Satan Wore a Cross,'' were best-sellers at the Doubleday Book Club, Literary Guild, Mystery Guild, and Book-of-the-Month Club. He has written other works of historical non-fiction including ''Cremation in America'', ''Contract Warriors'' and ''Gold!''.\n\nIn 2016, his book ''Murdering the President: Alexander Graham Bell and the Race to Save James Garfield'' was released by [[Potomac Books]].<ref>https://nypost.com/2016/09/22/the-inept-doctor-who-killed-president-garfield/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nHe won the 2005 Library Journal Best Reference Source Award for ''The Historical Atlas of American Crime''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fredrosen.com Official site]\n*[http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/30574/Fred_Rosen/index.aspx?authorID=30574 Fred Rosen at HarperCollins]\n*[http://www.nebraskapress.unl.edu/product/Murdering-the-President,677268.aspx University of Nebraska Press's Review of ''Murdering the President'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosen, Fred}}\n[[Category:American crime writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:The New York Times columnists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American newspaper journalists]]\n[[Category:People with mood disorders]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|image =\n|imagesize =\n| name = Fred Rosen\n| caption =\n| pseudonym =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date= \n| birth_place = Brooklyn, [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| occupation = true crime author, [[journalist]]\n| nationality = American\n| period = \n| genre = [[Non-fiction]]\n| subject = [[True crime]], history\n| movement =\n| notableworks = ''Murdering the President'', ''Lobster Boy''\n| spouse =\n| partner =\n| children =\n| relatives =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| signature =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Fred Rosen''' is a former [[columnist]] for the Arts and Leisure Section of ''[[The New York Times]]'' and a [[true crime]] author in the United States.\n\n==Biography==\nRosen was born in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. He suffered from [[dysthymia]] for a number of years.<ref name=Chronogram>[http://www.chronogram.com/issue/2004/05/book_shelf/index.html Chronogram - The Art of Business - Book Shelf > Where the Bodies are Buried]</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nRosen's published works include ''Lobster Boy'' about the murder of [[Grady Stiles]]. Rosen gave evidence in the trial against the killer.<ref name=Chronogram />\n\nHis two books for [[HarperCollins]] in 2007, ''There But For the Grace: Survivors of the 20th Century\u2019s Infamous Serial Killers'' and ''When Satan Wore a Cross,'' were best-sellers at the Doubleday Book Club, Literary Guild, Mystery Guild, and Book-of-the-Month Club. He has written other works of historical non-fiction including ''Cremation in America'', ''Contract Warriors'' and ''Gold!''.\n\nIn 2016, his book ''Murdering the President: Alexander Graham Bell and the Race to Save James Garfield'' was released by [[Potomac Books]].<ref>https://nypost.com/2016/09/22/the-inept-doctor-who-killed-president-garfield/</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nHe won the 2005 Library Journal Best Reference Source Award for ''The Historical Atlas of American Crime''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.fredrosen.com Official site]\n*[http://www.harpercollins.com/authors/30574/Fred_Rosen/index.aspx?authorID=30574 Fred Rosen at HarperCollins]\n*[http://www.nebraskapress.unl.edu/product/Murdering-the-President,677268.aspx University of Nebraska Press's Review of ''Murdering the President'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosen, Fred}}\n[[Category:American crime writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:The New York Times columnists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American newspaper journalists]]\n[[Category:People with mood disorders]]\n", "name_user": "Britponsit2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fred_Rosen_(author)"}
{"title_page": "Gil Evans", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Gil Evans\n|image           = Ryo-gil.jpg\n|landscape       = yes\n|caption         = Evans (left) with guitarist [[Ryo Kawasaki]] at [[Sweet Basil Jazz Club|Sweet Basil]],  New York City, 1982\n|background      = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|birth_name      = Ian Ernest Gilmore Green\n|birth_date      = May 13, 1912\n|birth_place     = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n|death_date      = {{death date and age|1988|3|20|1912|5|13}}\n|death_place     = [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico\n|instrument      = [[Piano]]\n|genre           = [[Jazz]], [[third stream]], [[cool jazz]], [[modal jazz]], [[jazz fusion]], [[free jazz]]\n|occupation      = Musician, composer, arranger, bandleader\n|years_active    = 1933\u201388\n|label           = [[Prestige Records|Prestige]], [[World Pacific Records|World Pacific]], [[Impulse! Records|Impulse!]], [[RCA Records|RCA]], [[Verve Records|Verve]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[King Records (Japan)|King]], [[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]]\n|associated_acts = [[Miles Davis]], [[Masabumi Kikuchi]], [[Ryo Kawasaki]], [[Kenny Burrell]], [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]], [[Lew Soloff]]\n|website         = {{URL|www.gilevans.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Ian Ernest Gilmore Evans''' (born '''Green'''; May 13, 1912 \u2013 March 20, 1988)<ref name=\"nytobit\"/> was a Canadian-American [[jazz]] pianist, [[Music arranger|arranger]], composer and [[bandleader]]. He is widely recognized as one of the greatest orchestrators in jazz, playing an important role in the development of [[cool jazz]], [[modal jazz]], [[free jazz]], and [[jazz fusion]]. He is best known for his acclaimed collaborations with [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=ALLMUSIC>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=gil-evans-mn0000551815|tab=biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Gil Evans Biography|author=[[Scott Yanow|Yanow, Scott]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGil Evans was born to Ian Ernest Green and Margaret Julia McConnachy on May 13, 1912. Originally named Ian Ernest Gilmore Green, he would eventually change his name from Green to Evans, taking the name of his step-father, John Evans. His father was a doctor and his mother was a homemaker and he had two siblings, Jean and Montgomery.{{fact|date=September 2019}}\n\nFrom a young age, Evans moved many times; from his birthplace in Toronto to western Canada, then to Washington State before finally settling in [[Stockton, California]]. He graduated from [[Stockton High School (California)|Stockton High School]] and [[Modesto Junior College]]. Evans remained a Canadian citizen until he entered the US Army during the second World War. After 1946, he lived and worked primarily in [[New York City]], living for many years at [[Westbeth Artists Community]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBetween 1941 and 1948, Evans worked as an arranger for the [[Claude Thornhill]] Orchestra.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=1997|edition=Concise|isbn=1-85227-745-9|pages=441/2}}</ref> Even then, early in his career, his arrangements were such  a challenge to musicians that bassist Bill Crow recalled that bandleader Thornhill would bring out Evans\u2019s arrangements \"when he wanted to punish the band.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Gil-Evans|title=Gil Evans Canadian composer|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref> Evans' modest basement apartment behind a New York City Chinese laundry soon became a meeting place for musicians looking to develop new musical styles outside of the dominant [[bebop]] style of the day. Those present included the leading bebop performer, [[Charlie Parker]], as well as [[Gerry Mulligan]] and [[John Carisi]]. In 1948, Evans, with [[Miles Davis]], Mulligan, and others, collaborated on a band book for a nonet.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> These ensembles, larger than the trio-to-quintet \"combos\", but smaller than the \"big bands\" which were on the brink of economic unviability, allowed arrangers to have a larger palette of colors by using [[French horn in Jazz|French horns]] and [[tuba]]. [[Claude Thornhill]] had employed hornist [[John Graas]] in 1942, and composer-arranger [[Bob Graettinger]] had scored for horns and tubas with the [[Stan Kenton]] orchestra, but the \"Kenton sound\" was in the context of a dense orchestral wall of sound that Evans avoided.\n\nThe Miles Davis-led group was booked for a week at the \"[[Royal Roost]]\" as an intermission group on the bill with the [[Count Basie]] Orchestra. [[Capitol Records]] recorded 12 numbers by the nonet at three sessions in 1949 and 1950. These recordings were reissued on a 1957 Miles Davis LP titled ''[[Birth of the Cool]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>\n\nLater, while Davis was under contract with [[Columbia Records]], producer [[George Avakian]] suggested that Davis could work with any of several arrangers. Davis immediately chose Evans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/nov/23/george-avakian-jazz-scholar-miles-davis-dies|title=George Avakian, jazz producer of Miles Davis and more, dies at 98|work=[[The Guardian]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=November 23, 2007|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref> The three albums that resulted from the collaboration are ''[[Miles Ahead (album)|Miles Ahead]]'' (1957), ''[[Porgy and Bess (Miles Davis album)|Porgy and Bess]]'' (1958), and ''[[Sketches of Spain]]'' (1960).<ref name=\"Larkin\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.jazziz.com/miles-davis-gil-evans-miles-ahead/|author=Brian Zimmerman|title=Miles Davis & Gil Evans \u2013 \u201cMiles Ahead\u201d|magazine=Jazziz|date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> Another collaboration from this period, ''[[Quiet Nights (Miles Davis and Gil Evans album)|Quiet Nights]]'' (1962) was issued later, against the wishes of Davis, who broke with his then-producer [[Teo Macero]] for a time as a result. Although these four records were marketed primarily under Davis's name (and credited to ''Miles Davis with Orchestra Under the Direction of Gil Evans''), Evans's contribution was as important as Davis's. Their work coupled Evans's classic [[big band]] jazz stylings and arrangements with Davis's solo playing. Evans also contributed behind the scenes to Davis' classic quintet albums of the 1960s.\n\nThe demands of the score for ''[[Porgy and Bess]]'' were legendary, from the very first note for the lead trumpet. The limited time allotted for rehearsals revealed that the ability to read such a challenging score was not consistent among jazz musicians, and there are many audible errors. Yet the recording is now regarded by many as one of the greatest reinterpretations of [[George Gershwin|Gershwin]]'s music in any musical style, because Evans and Davis were each devoted to going outside the \"mainstream\" of commercial expectations for jazz musicians. Evans was a great influence on Davis's interest in \"non-jazz\" music, especially orchestral music. Unfortunately, Evans's orchestral scores from the ''Porgy and Bess'' sessions were later found to be incomplete (or simply lost), and [[Quincy Jones]] and [[Gil Goldstein]] attempted to reconstruct these for Miles Davis's final 1991 concerts at [[Montreux]], recorded as ''[[Miles & Quincy Live at Montreux]]''. Davis had relented after years of refusing to revisit this material, but he was clearly ill, recovering from [[pneumonia]], and trumpeter [[Wallace Roney]], who was mentored by Davis, covered many of the challenging passages. Davis died before the release of the album.\n\nFrom 1957 onwards, Evans recorded albums under his own name. Tubist [[Bill Barber (musician)|Bill Barber]] and trumpeter Louis Mucci from Thornhill's band were both stalwarts in Evans's early ensembles, with Mucci finding a spot on nearly every pre1980s Evans recording. Among the featured soloists on these records were [[Lee Konitz]], [[Jimmy Cleveland]], [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]], [[Johnny Coles]] and [[Cannonball Adderley]]. In 1965 he arranged the big band tracks on [[Kenny Burrell]]'s ''[[Guitar Forms]]'' album.\n\nEvans was influenced by Spanish composers [[Manuel de Falla]] and [[Joaqu\u00edn Rodrigo]], and by other Latin and Brazilian music, as well as by German expatriate [[Kurt Weill]]. His arrangements of pieces already well known to some listeners from their original cabaret, concert hall or Broadway stage arrangements, revealed aspects of the music in a wholly original way. Sometimes in an unexpected contrast to the original atmosphere of the piece, and sometimes taking a dark ballad such as Weill's \"Barbara Song\" into an even darker place. The personnel list for ''[[The Individualism of Gil Evans]]'' (1964), not only features [[Bill Barber (musician)|Bill Barber]] and hornists [[James Buffington]] and [[Julius Watkins]] (along with two others), but each section features the cream of the younger (some more classically trained) musicians who were making their names in jazz. The presence of four of the most acclaimed young bassists ([[Richard Davis (bassist)|Richard Davis]], [[Paul Chambers]], [[Ron Carter]], and [[Ben Tucker]]) along with veteran [[Milt Hinton]] would ordinarily indicate that each is used individually for separate tracks, but Evans's scores usually required at least two bassists on any given track, some playing ''arco'' (with the bow) and some ''pizzicato'' (plucking with fingers, the standard jazz method). These arrangements frequently featured greatly slowed-down tempos with [[polyrhythmic]] percussion and no prevailing \"beat\". To his by-now standard French horns and tuba, Evans's scores added [[Alto flute|alto]] and [[bass flute]]s, [[double reed]]s, and [[harp]]; orchestral instruments not associated with \"swing\" bands, providing a larger pallette of orchestral colors, and allowing him to attain the ethereal quality heard in his arrangements during his Thornhill days.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He frequently wrote a part for the [[tenor violin]] of [[Harry Lookofsky]]. Yet, this album featured an orchestral arrangement of \"[[Spoonful]]\" by bluesman [[Willie Dixon]], an early indication of Evans's breadth and a hint of things to come.\n\nIn 1966, he recorded an album with Brazilian singer [[Astrud Gilberto]], ''[[Look to the Rainbow (Astrud Gilberto album)|Look to the Rainbow]]''.<ref name=book>{{cite book|title=Gil Evans: Out of the Cool: His Life and Music|url=https://archive.org/details/gilevansoutofco00stei|url-access=registration|author=Crease, Stephanie Stein|publisher=A Capella Books|pages=[https://archive.org/details/gilevansoutofco00stei/page/362 362-366]|year=2002|isbn=1556529864}}</ref> He was discouraged by the commercial direction [[Verve Records]] was taking with the Gilberto sessions, and he went into a period of hiatus.\n\nDuring this period while he was somewhat depressed about the commercial and logistical difficulties of his previous scoring requirements, his wife suggested that he listen to the guitarist [[Jimi Hendrix]]. Evans developed a particular interest in the work of the rock guitarist. Evans gradually built another orchestra in the 1970s, with none of the coloration instruments from his past arrangements. Working in the [[free jazz]] and [[jazz-rock]] idioms, he gained a new generation of admirers. These ensembles, rarely more than fifteen and frequently smaller, allowed him to make more contributions on keyboards, and with the development of truly portable [[synthesizers]], he began using these to provide additional color.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> Hendrix's 1970 death precluded a scheduled meeting with Evans to discuss having Hendrix collaborate with a big band led by Evans.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jerryjazzmusician.com/2001/12/stephanie-stein-crease-author-of-gil-evans-out-of-the-cool/|title=Gil Evans: Out of the Cool: His Life and Music|author=Crease, Stephanie Stein|publisher=[[Chicago Review Press]]|year=2003|isbn=978-1556524936}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, he released an album of his, and other band member's, arrangements of music by Hendrix with guitarists [[John Abercrombie (guitarist)|John Abercrombie]] and [[Ryo Kawasaki]].<ref name=book/> From then on Evans's ensembles featured electric instruments, i.e. guitars, basses, and synthesizers including a collaboration with bassist [[Jaco Pastorius]]. In contrast to his intricate scores for large ensembles, which required precision orchestral playing accompanying a single soloist, his later arrangements would feature more unison playing by the entire ensemble, such as on Hendrix's \"[[Little Wing]]\", with improvisational touches added throughout by the musicians.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> Live recordings demonstrate that some entire pieces were collaborative efforts, and Evans can be heard giving cues from the keyboard (behind the band) to guide the band. Before the 1970s, his keyboard playing was generally sparse on recordings but after the 1970s he took a more active role in the rhythm section of the band.\n\n''[[Where Flamingos Fly]]'' (recorded 1971, released 1981) demonstrated his ability to contract the most accomplished musicians, with veterans Coles, [[Harry Lookofsky]], [[Richard Davis (double bassist)|Richard Davis]] and [[Jimmy Knepper]] (who played the solo on the \"Where Flamingos Fly\" track on 1961's ''[[Out of the Cool]]'') alongside young multi-instrumentalist [[Howard Johnson (jazz musician)|Howard Johnson]], synthesizer player [[Don Preston]] (at that time still a member of [[The Mothers of Invention]]), and [[Billy Harper]].\n\nIn April 1983, the Gil Evans Orchestra was booked into the [[Sweet Basil Jazz Club]] ([[Greenwich Village]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) by jazz producer and Sweet Basil owner [[Horst Liepolt]]. This turned out to be a regular Monday night engagement for Evans for nearly five years and also resulted in the release of a number of successful albums by ''Gil Evans and the Monday Night Orchestra''.<ref name=aaj>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/hidden-treasures-vol-1-monday-nights-the-gil-evans-orchestra-bopper-spock-suns-music-review-by-jerome-wilson.php|author=Jerome Wilson|title=The Gil Evans Orchestra: Hidden Treasures Vol. 1, Monday Nights|website=All About Jazz|date=December 31, 2018|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Nakayama |first=Yasuki |date=2018 |title=\u30b9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u30ca\u30eb\u6642\u4ee3\u306e\u4e2d\u5c71\u5eb7\u6a39 |trans-title=Yasuki Nakayama in \"Swing Journal\" era |url= |language=Japanese |location=Tokyo, Japan |publisher=Shinko Music Entertainment |chapter=\u30ae\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30b9\u306e\u30de\u30f3\u30c7\u30a3\u30fb\u30ca\u30a4\u30c8\u30fb\u30bb\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 |trans-chapter=Gil Evans' Monday night sessions |pages=68-78 |isbn=}}</ref> Evans's ensemble featured many of the top-call musicians in New York, many of whom were also in the [[NBC]] [[Saturday Night Live Band]] and there were many conflicts, so their \"deputies\" for the night might be other world-class musicians. Yet Evans was also known to let newcomers \"sit in\" occasionally. The band also performed arrangements by band members, current and past. Stalwarts in this ensemble were [[Lew Soloff]], [[Alan Rubin]], [[Marvin Peterson]], [[Tom Malone (musician)|Tom \"Bones\" Malone]], [[George Adams (musician)]], [[David Sanborn]], [[Hiram Bullock]], Mark Eagan, drummer Kenwood Dennard, saxophonist [[Bill Evans (saxophonist)|Bill Evans]] (no relation) and Gil Goldstein. In 1987, Evans recorded a live album with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], featuring big band arrangements of songs by and with [[The Police]]. In the same spirit of introducing new talent in his bands, he collaborated with [[Maria Schneider (musician)|Maria Schneider]] with her as an apprentice arranger on this and other final projects. His final project was Nov. 3 & 26, 1987, his arrangements for the Laurent Cugny Big Band in Paris, on the recording \u201cGolden Hair\u201d on Emarcy/Polygram.\n\n===Ryan Truesdell presents the Gil Evans Project===\n[[Ryan Truesdell]] [[:de:Ryan Truesdell|(de)]] began the Gil Evans Project, which resulted in a 2012 CD entitled ''Centennial'', featuring previously unrecorded compositions and arrangements. These were produced with the permission of the Gil Evans estate, who gave Truesdell access to these scores and materials. Miles Evans, Gil's son, also led the Gil Evans Orchestra for a centennial concert at New York's [[Highline Ballroom]], featuring many of the musicians heard in the orchestra during Evans's lifetime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/ryan-truesdell-the-gil-evans-project-ryan-truesdell-by-victor-l-schermer.php|title=Ryan Truesdell: The Gil Evans Project|author=Victor L. Schermer|website=[[All About Jazz]]|date=July 25, 2011|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Film music==\nIn 1986, Evans produced and arranged the soundtrack to the film of the [[Colin MacInnes]] book ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]'', thereby working with such contemporary artists as [[Sade Adu]], [[Patsy Kensit]]'s Eighth Wonder, [[the Style Council]], [[Jerry Dammers]], [[Smiley Culture]], [[Edward Tudor-Pole]], and [[David Bowie]].\n\nHe also arranged the music for the 1986 [[Martin Scorsese]] film ''[[The Color of Money]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nEvans first married following the 1949 ''[[Birth of the Cool]]'' recording sessions to Lillian Grace. Very little is known about this marriage. In 1963, he would marry again. Evans was survived by his second wife Anita (Cooper) and two children, Noah and Miles. His son Miles played trumpet in his ''Monday Night Orchestra''.<ref name=aaj/>\n\nEvans died of [[peritonitis]] in [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico, contracting it shortly after a surgery for his prostate and subsequent travel to Mexico to recover. Evans died at the age of 75.<ref name=nytobit>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/22/obituaries/gil-evans-a-key-jazz-composer-and-orchestrator-is-dead-at-75.html|title=Gil Evans, a Key Jazz Composer And Orchestrator, Is Dead at 75|author=Watrous, Peter|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 22, 1988}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, [[Columbia Studio Recordings]] had released a box set which besides the masterpieces, featured outtakes and rarities of Miles Davis and Gil Evans.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Picks and Pans Review: Miles Davis & Gil Evans: the Complete Columbia Studio Recordings|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=October 14, 1996|volume=46|number=16}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Gil Evans among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Rosen, Jody|title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html|magazine=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*In 1986, Evans was inducted into the ''[[Down Beat]]'' Jazz Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://downbeat.com/archives/detail/downbeat-hall-of-fame|title=DownBeat Hall of Fame|magazine=[[DownBeat]]}}</ref> He was also inducted into the Canadian Music Hall of Fame in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadianmusichalloffame.ca/inductee/gil-evans/|title=Gil Evans \u2013 Canadian Music Hall Of Fame|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Grammy Awards===\nAwarded as followings:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/gil-evans |title=Artist: Gil Evans |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=The GRAMMYs|publisher=Recording Academy |access-date=March 23, 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n*[[3rd Annual Grammy Awards|1960]]: ''[[Sketches of Spain]]'' (with [[Miles Davis]], [[Grammy Award for Best Original Jazz Composition|Best Jazz Composition of More Than Five Minutes Duration]])\n*[[31st Annual Grammy Awards|1988]]: ''[[Bud and Bird]]'' (posthumously with the Monday Night Orchestra, [[Grammy Award for Best Large Jazz Ensemble Album|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Big Band]])\n*[[39th Annual Grammy Awards|1997]]: (''[[Miles Davis & Gil Evans: The Complete Columbia Studio Recordings]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Historical Album|Best Historical Album]] for the Compilation Producers and/or Mastering Engineers))\n*[[55th Annual Grammy Awards|2012]]: \"How About You\" in ''[[Centennial - Newly Discovered Works of Gil Evans]]'' (posthumously with Gil Evans Project, [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement|Best Instrumental Arrangement]])\n\n====Grammy Award nominations====\n*[[4th Annual Grammy Awards|1961]]: ''[[Out of the Cool]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Performance Solo or Small Group]])\n*[[5th Annual Grammy Awards|1962]]: ''[[Miles Davis at Carnegie Hall]]'' (with [[Miles Davis]], [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Performance Solo or Small Group (Instrumental)]])\n*[[7th Annual Grammy Awards|1964]]: ''[[The Individualism of Gil Evans]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Instrumental Jazz Performance \u2013 Small Group or Soloist]])\n*1964: ''[[Quiet Nights (Miles Davis and Gil Evans album)|Quiet Nights]]'' (with Miles Davis, Best Instrumental Jazz Performance \u2013 Small Group or Soloist)\n*[[8th Annual Grammy Awards|1965]]: [[Kenny Burrell]]'s ''[[Guitar Forms]]'' (with Kenny Burrell, [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Instrumental Jazz Performance \u2013 Soloist or Small Group]])\n*1965: \"Greensleeves\" in Kenny Burrell's ''Guitar Forms'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Instrumental Arrangement]])\n*[[16th Annual Grammy Awards|1973]]: ''[[Svengali (album)|Svengali]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Performance by a Group]])\n*[[26th Annual Grammy Awards|1983]]: ''[[Priestess (album)|Priestess]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Group]])\n*[[55th Annual Grammy Awards|2012]]: \"Look to the Rainbow\" in ''[[Centennial - Newly Discovered Works of Gil Evans]]'' (posthumously with Gil Evans Project & [[Luciana Souza]], [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)]])\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Gil Evans & Ten]]'' ([[Prestige Records|Prestige]], 1958) \u2013 recorded in 1957\n* ''[[New Bottle Old Wine]]'' ([[World Pacific Records|World Pacific]], 1958)\n* ''[[Great Jazz Standards]]'' (World Pacific, 1959)\n* ''[[Out of the Cool]]'' ([[Impulse! Records|Impulse!]], 1961) \u2013 recorded in 1960\n* ''[[Into the Hot (Gil Evans album)|Into the Hot]]'' (Impulse!, 1962) \u2013 recorded in 1961\n* ''[[The Individualism of Gil Evans]]'' ([[Verve Records|Verve]], 1964) \u2013 recorded in 1963 and 1964\n* ''Gil Evans'' ([[Ampex#Record labels|Ampex]], 1969) - rereleased as ''[[Blues in Orbit (Gil Evans album)|Blues in Orbit]]'' ([[Enja Records|Enja]], 1971) \u2013 rerecorded two tracks\n* ''[[Satin Doll (Kimiko Kasai album)|Satin Doll]]'' ([[Sony Music Entertainment Japan|CBS/Sony]], 1972) \u2013 with [[Kimiko Kasai]]\n* ''[[Masabumi Kikuchi with Gil Evans]]'' ([[Philips Records|Philips]] [Japan], 1972) \u2013 CD version ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]], 1989)\n* ''[[The Gil Evans Orchestra Plays the Music of Jimi Hendrix]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]], 1974)\n* ''[[There Comes a Time (album)|There Comes a Time]]'' (RCA, 1976)  \u2013 recorded in 1975\n* ''[[Parabola (album)|Parabola]]'' (Horo, 1979) \u2013 recorded in 1978\n* ''[[Where Flamingos Fly]]'' ([[Artists House]], 1981) \u2013 recorded in 1971\n* ''[[Collaboration (Helen Merrill and Gil Evans album)|Collaboration]]'' (EmArcy, 1987) - with [[Helen Merrill]]\n'''Posthumous releases'''\n* ''[[Paris Blues (album)|Paris Blues]]'' (Owl, 1988) - recorded in 1987 with [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]]\n* ''[[Rhythm A Ning (album)|Rhythm A Ning]]'' (EmArcy, 1988) \u2013 recorded in 1987 with [[Laurent Cugny]] Big Band Lumiere\n* ''[[Golden Hair (album)|Golden Hair]]'' (EmArcy, 1989) - recorded in 1987 with Laurent Cugny Big Band Lumiere\n* ''The Mother of the Book'' (InRespect, 1994<!--; [[Entertainment One Music|Koch Jazz]], 1996-->) - recorded in <!--February 23-24, -->1985 with {{ill|Glen Hall (musician)|de|Glen Hall}}\n\n===Live albums===\n''In recorded date order''\n*1973: ''[[Svengali (album)|Svengali]]'' ([[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], 1973)\n*1974: ''Montreux Jazz Festival '74'' ([[Philips Records|Philips]] [Japan], 1975)\n*<!--May 24 \u2013 June 8, -->1976: ''Tokyo Concert'' (Studio Songs, 2010) \u2013 remastering by [[Ryo Kawasaki]]\n*<!--October 23, -->1976: ''Synthetic Evans'' (PolJazz, unknown)  also released as ''Live 76'' (EPM Zeta, 1988) \u2013 unofficial release\n*<!--October 30, -->1976: ''Live in Dortmund 1976'' (Jazz Trafffic, 2012) \u2013 with guest [[Roland Kirk]]\n*1977: ''[[Priestess (album)|Priestess]]'' (Antilles, 1983)\n*<!--February 25, -->1978: ''[[Gil Evans Live at the Royal Festival Hall London 1978]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]], 1979)\n*<!--February 25, -->1978: ''The Rest of Gil Evans at the Royal Festival Hall 1978'' (Mole Jazz, 1981)\n*<!--October 19, -->1978: ''Little Wing: Live in Germany'' ([[Circle Records (Germany)|Circle]], 1978)\n*1980: ''[[Heroes (Gil Evans and Lee Konitz album)|Heroes]]'' (Verve/Remark, 1991) \u2013 with [[Lee Konitz]]\n*1980: ''[[Anti-Heroes (Lee Konitz and Gil Evans album)|Anti-Heroes]]'' (Verve/Remark, 1991) - with Lee Konitz\n*1980: ''[[Live at the Public Theater (New York 1980)]]'' Vol.1 (Trio, 1980)\n*1980: ''Live at the Public Theater (New York 1980)'' Vol.2 (Trio, 1981)\n*1981: ''Lunar Eclypse'' (Newtone, 2000)\n*1983: ''British Orchestra: the Complete Concert'' (Mole Jazz, 1983)\n*1984: ''[[Live at Sweet Basil (Gil Evans album)|Live at Sweet Basil]]'' ([[King Records (Japan)|King]]/Electric Bird, 1985)\n*1984: ''[[Live at Sweet Basil Vol. 2]]'' (King/Electric Bird, 1987)\n*1986: ''Live 1986 - Unissued'' (Musica Jazz, 1994) \u2013 also released as ''The Honey Man'' (New Tone, 1995)\n*1986: ''[[Bud and Bird]]'' (King, 1987) \u2013 [[31st Annual Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Best Large Jazz Ensemble Album|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Big Band]]\n*1986: ''[[Farewell (Gil Evans album)|Farewell]]'' (King, 1992)\n*1987: ''75th Birthday Concert'' ([[BBC Music|BBC Legends]], 2001)\n*1987: ''Last Session - Live at \"Perugia Jazz Festival\" July 11, 1987'' (Jazz Door, 1992) \u2013 with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], unofficial release.\n*1987: ''Live at Umbria Jazz'' Volume 1 (Egea, 2000)\n*1987: ''Live at Umbria Jazz'' Volume 2 (Egea, 2001)\n\n===Arranged albums===\n''In recorded date order''\n*1947-49: [[Claude Thornhill]] Orchestra, ''The Real Birth of the Cool: Studio Recordings'' ([[Sony Music Entertainment Japan|CBS/Sony]], 1971)\n*1949-50: [[Miles Davis]], ''[[Birth of the Cool]]'' ([[Capitol Records|Capitol]], 1957)\n*1950-52: [[Charlie Parker]], ''[[Big Band (Charlie Parker album)|Big Band]]'' ([[Clef Records|Clef]], 1954)\n*<!--December -->1955: [[Hal McKusick]], ''The Jazz Workshop'' ([[RCA Victor Records|RCA Victor]], 1956)\n*1956: [[Johnny Mathis]], ''[[Johnny Mathis (album)|Johnny Mathis]]'' ([[Columbia Records|Columbia]], 1956)\n*1956: Marcy Lutes, ''Debut'' ([[Decca Records|Decca]], 1956)\n*<!--January -->1957: [[Lucy Reed]], ''This Is Lucy Reed'' ([[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]], 1957)\n*1956-<!--February -->57: [[Helen Merrill]], ''[[Dream of You (Helen Merrill album)|Dream of You]]'' ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]], 1957)\n*<!--May & August -->1957: Miles Davis, ''[[Miles Ahead (album)|Miles Ahead]]'' (Columbia, 1957)\n*1958?: [[Don Elliott]] Octet, ''Jamaica Jazz'' (ABC-Paramount, 1958)\n*1958: Miles Davis, ''[[Porgy and Bess (Miles Davis album)|Porgy and Bess]]'' (Columbia, 1959)\n*1959-60: Miles Davis, ''[[Sketches of Spain]]'' (Columbia, 1960) \u2013 [[3rd Annual Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Best Original Jazz Composition|Best Jazz Composition of More Than Five Minutes Duration]]\n*1961: Miles Davis, ''[[Miles Davis at Carnegie Hall]]'' (Columbia, 1962)\n*1962-63: Miles Davis, ''[[Quiet Nights (Miles Davis and Gil Evans album)|Quiet Nights]]'' (Columbia, 1963)\n*1964-65: [[Kenny Burrell]], ''[[Guitar Forms]]'' ([[Verve Records|Verve]], 1965)\n*1965-66: [[Astrud Gilberto]], ''[[Look to the Rainbow (Astrud Gilberto album)|Look to the Rainbow]]'' (Verve, 1966)\n*1968: Miles Davis, ''[[Filles de Kilimanjaro]]'' (Columbia, 1968) \u2013 without credits<ref name=\"szwed\">{{cite book|last=Szwed|first=John|title=So What: The Life of Miles Davis|url=https://archive.org/details/sowhatlifeofmile00szwe|url-access=registration|edition=first|year=2002|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|location=New York|isbn=0-684-85982-3}}</ref>{{Rp|273}}\n*1982-83: Miles Davis, ''[[Star People]]'' (Columbia, 1983)\n*1983: Miles Davis, ''[[Decoy (album)|Decoy]]'' (Columbia, 1984) \u2013 only \"That's Right\"\n\n===Compilation/Box set===\n* With [[Kenny Burrell]] and [[Phil Woods]], ''Gil Evans Orch., Kenny Burrell and Phil Woods \u2013 Previously Unreleased Recordings'' (Verve, 1973) \u2013 recorded in 1963 and 1964\n*''Take Me To The Sun'' (Last Chance Music, 1990) \u2013 tracks #1\u2013#3 are live recording at \"[[Montreux Jazz Festival]] 1983\" with [[RMS (band)|RMS]]. track #4 is the last studio recording in 1988<!-- at RPM Studio NYC-->.\n*''Verve Jazz Masters 23: Gil Evans'' (Verve, 1994)\n* With [[Miles Davis]], ''[[Miles Davis & Gil Evans: The Complete Columbia Studio Recordings]]'' ([[Columbia records|Columbia]], 1996) \u2013 recorded from 1957 to 1968. [[39th Annual Grammy Awards|39th Annual Grammy]] [[Grammy Award for Best Historical Album|Best Historical Album]].\n* With Miles Davis, ''The Historic Collaboration In Words & Music'' (Columbia, 1996)\n*''Voodoo Chile''\uff08Jazz Door, 2005) \u2013  Live recording of 1974 in Sweden and 1978 in Germany.\n\n===Soundtrack album===\n* ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)#Soundtrack|Absolute Beginners: The Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' (EMI, 1986)\n\n===Tribute albums===\n* The Gil Evans Orchestra, ''Tribute to Gil'' (Soul Note, 1988) \u2013 at Umbria and Sicilia Jazz Festival\n* [[Ryan Truesdell]]'s Gil Evans Project, ''[[Centennial - Newly Discovered Works of Gil Evans]]'' (ArtistShare, 2013) \u2013 recorded in 2012. [[55th Annual Grammy Awards|55th Annual Grammy]] [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement|Best Instrumental Arrangement]]: \"How About You\".\n* Ryan Truesdell's Gil Evans Project, ''[[Lines of Color]]'' ([[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], 2015) \u2013 recorded in 2014\n\n==Filmography==\n*2004: ''RMS Live with Gil Evans at the Montreux Jazz Festival 1983'' (Angel Air)\n*2007: ''Gil Evans and His Orchestra'' (V.I.E.W. Video)<ref>{{cite web|author=Evans, Gil|work=View Video|url=http://www.view.com/gil_evans_and_his_orchestra_dvd.aspx|title=Gil Evans and his Orchestra|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n*2007: ''Strange Fruit with Sting''\n*2009: ''Miles Davis \u2013 The Cool Jazz Sound''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of jazz arrangers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Gil Evans}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.gilevans.com}}\n*{{Discogs artist|255137-Gil-Evans}}\n*{{IMDb name|0262789}}\n*{{Find a Grave|19222}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CCX2874500158|title=Evans, Gil|encyclopedia= The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives|volume=2: 1986-1990|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|editor1-first=Kenneth T. |editor1-last=Jackson |editor2-first= Karen|editor2-last=Markoe |editor3-first=Arnold|editor3-last=Markoe|date=1999|via=[[Gale Academic Onefile]]}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/gil-evans|title=Gil Evans|date=2019-02-15|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-15}}\n\n{{Gil Evans}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Gil}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jazz arrangers]]\n[[Category:Cool jazz arrangers]]\n[[Category:Jazz fusion arrangers]]\n[[Category:Post-bop arrangers]]\n[[Category:Experimental big band arrangers]]\n[[Category:Canadian jazz bandleaders]]\n[[Category:Big band bandleaders]]\n[[Category:Canadian Music Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Antilles Records artists]]\n[[Category:Verve Records artists]]\n[[Category:Enja Records artists]]\n[[Category:EmArcy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Impulse! Records artists]]\n[[Category:ACT Music artists]]\n[[Category:Miles Davis]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Progressive big band musicians]]\n[[Category:New York Jazz Repertory Company members]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Gil Evans\n|image           = Ryo-gil.jpg\n|landscape       = yes\n|caption         = Evans (left) with guitarist [[Ryo Kawasaki]] at [[Sweet Basil Jazz Club|Sweet Basil]],  New York City, 1982\n|background      = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|birth_name      = Ian Ernest Gilmore Green\n|birth_date      = May 13, 1912\n|birth_place     = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n|death_date      = {{death date and age|1988|3|20|1912|5|13}}\n|death_place     = [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico\n|instrument      = [[Piano]]\n|genre           = [[Jazz]], [[third stream]], [[cool jazz]], [[modal jazz]], [[jazz fusion]], [[free jazz]]\n|occupation      = Musician, composer, arranger, bandleader\n|years_active    = 1933\u201388\n|label           = [[Prestige Records|Prestige]], [[World Pacific Records|World Pacific]], [[Impulse! Records|Impulse!]], [[RCA Records|RCA]], [[Verve Records|Verve]], [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[King Records (Japan)|King]], [[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]]\n|associated_acts = [[Miles Davis]], [[Masabumi Kikuchi]], [[Ryo Kawasaki]], [[Kenny Burrell]], [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]], [[Lew Soloff]]\n|website         = {{URL|www.gilevans.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Ian Ernest Gilmore Evans''' (born '''Green'''; May 13, 1912 \u2013 March 20, 1988)<ref name=\"nytobit\"/> was a Canadian-American [[jazz]] pianist, [[Music arranger|arranger]], composer and [[bandleader]]. He is widely recognized as one of the greatest orchestrators in jazz, playing an important role in the development of [[cool jazz]], [[modal jazz]], [[free jazz]], and [[jazz fusion]]. He is best known for his acclaimed collaborations with [[Miles Davis]].<ref name=ALLMUSIC>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=gil-evans-mn0000551815|tab=biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Gil Evans Biography|author=[[Scott Yanow|Yanow, Scott]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGil Evans was born to Ian Ernest Green and Margaret Julia McConnachy on May 13, 1912. Originally named Ian Ernest Gilmore Green, he would eventually change his name from Green to Evans, taking the name of his step-father, John Evans. His father was a doctor and his mother was a homemaker and he had two siblings, Jean and Montgomery.{{fact|date=September 2019}}\n\nFrom a young age, Evans moved many times; from his birthplace in Toronto to western Canada, then to Washington State before finally settling in [[Stockton, California]]. He graduated from [[Stockton High School (California)|Stockton High School]] and [[Modesto Junior College]]. Evans remained a Canadian citizen until he entered the US Army during the second World War. After 1946, he lived and worked primarily in [[New York City]], living for many years at [[Westbeth Artists Community]].<ref name=\"ALLMUSIC\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBetween 1941 and 1948, Evans worked as an arranger for the [[Claude Thornhill]] Orchestra.<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=1997|edition=Concise|isbn=1-85227-745-9|pages=441/2}}</ref> Even then, early in his career, his arrangements were such  a challenge to musicians that bassist Bill Crow recalled that bandleader Thornhill would bring out Evans\u2019s arrangements \"when he wanted to punish the band.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Gil-Evans|title=Gil Evans Canadian composer|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref> Evans' modest basement apartment behind a New York City Chinese laundry soon became a meeting place for musicians looking to develop new musical styles outside of the dominant [[bebop]] style of the day. Those present included the leading bebop performer, [[Charlie Parker]], as well as [[Gerry Mulligan]] and [[John Carisi]]. In 1948, Evans, with [[Miles Davis]], Mulligan, and others, collaborated on a band book for a nonet.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> These ensembles, larger than the trio-to-quintet \"combos\", but smaller than the \"big bands\" which were on the brink of economic unviability, allowed arrangers to have a larger palette of colors by using [[French horn in Jazz|French horns]] and [[tuba]]. [[Claude Thornhill]] had employed hornist [[John Graas]] in 1942, and composer-arranger [[Bob Graettinger]] had scored for horns and tubas with the [[Stan Kenton]] orchestra, but the \"Kenton sound\" was in the context of a dense orchestral wall of sound that Evans avoided.\n\nThe Miles Davis-led group was booked for a week at the \"[[Royal Roost]]\" as an intermission group on the bill with the [[Count Basie]] Orchestra. [[Capitol Records]] recorded 12 numbers by the nonet at three sessions in 1949 and 1950. These recordings were reissued on a 1957 Miles Davis LP titled ''[[Birth of the Cool]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/>\n\nLater, while Davis was under contract with [[Columbia Records]], producer [[George Avakian]] suggested that Davis could work with any of several arrangers. Davis immediately chose Evans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/nov/23/george-avakian-jazz-scholar-miles-davis-dies|title=George Avakian, jazz producer of Miles Davis and more, dies at 98|work=[[The Guardian]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=November 23, 2007|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref> The three albums that resulted from the collaboration are ''[[Miles Ahead (album)|Miles Ahead]]'' (1957), ''[[Porgy and Bess (Miles Davis album)|Porgy and Bess]]'' (1958), and ''[[Sketches of Spain]]'' (1960).<ref name=\"Larkin\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.jazziz.com/miles-davis-gil-evans-miles-ahead/|author=Brian Zimmerman|title=Miles Davis & Gil Evans \u2013 \u201cMiles Ahead\u201d|magazine=Jazziz|date=May 6, 2019}}</ref> Another collaboration from this period, ''[[Quiet Nights (Miles Davis and Gil Evans album)|Quiet Nights]]'' (1962) was issued later, against the wishes of Davis, who broke with his then-producer [[Teo Macero]] for a time as a result. Although these four records were marketed primarily under Davis's name (and credited to ''Miles Davis with Orchestra Under the Direction of Gil Evans''), Evans's contribution was as important as Davis's. Their work coupled Evans's classic [[big band]] jazz stylings and arrangements with Davis's solo playing. Evans also contributed behind the scenes to Davis' classic quintet albums of the 1960s.\n\nThe demands of the score for ''[[Porgy and Bess]]'' were legendary, from the very first note for the lead trumpet. The limited time allotted for rehearsals revealed that the ability to read such a challenging score was not consistent among jazz musicians, and there are many audible errors. Yet the recording is now regarded by many as one of the greatest reinterpretations of [[George Gershwin|Gershwin]]'s music in any musical style, because Evans and Davis were each devoted to going outside the \"mainstream\" of commercial expectations for jazz musicians. Evans was a great influence on Davis's interest in \"non-jazz\" music, especially orchestral music. Unfortunately, Evans's orchestral scores from the ''Porgy and Bess'' sessions were later found to be incomplete (or simply lost), and [[Quincy Jones]] and [[Gil Goldstein]] attempted to reconstruct these for Miles Davis's final 1991 concerts at [[Montreux]], recorded as ''[[Miles & Quincy Live at Montreux]]''. Davis had relented after years of refusing to revisit this material, but he was clearly ill, recovering from [[pneumonia]], and trumpeter [[Wallace Roney]], who was mentored by Davis, covered many of the challenging passages. Davis died before the release of the album.\n\nFrom 1957 onwards, Evans recorded albums under his own name. Tubist [[Bill Barber (musician)|Bill Barber]] and trumpeter Louis Mucci from Thornhill's band were both stalwarts in Evans's early ensembles, with Mucci finding a spot on nearly every pre1980s Evans recording. Among the featured soloists on these records were [[Lee Konitz]], [[Jimmy Cleveland]], [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]], [[Johnny Coles]] and [[Cannonball Adderley]]. In 1965 he arranged the big band tracks on [[Kenny Burrell]]'s ''[[Guitar Forms]]'' album.\n\nEvans was influenced by Spanish composers [[Manuel de Falla]] and [[Joaqu\u00edn Rodrigo]], and by other Latin and Brazilian music, as well as by German expatriate [[Kurt Weill]]. His arrangements of pieces already well known to some listeners from their original cabaret, concert hall or Broadway stage arrangements, revealed aspects of the music in a wholly original way. Sometimes in an unexpected contrast to the original atmosphere of the piece, and sometimes taking a dark ballad such as Weill's \"Barbara Song\" into an even darker place. The personnel list for ''[[The Individualism of Gil Evans]]'' (1964), not only features [[Bill Barber (musician)|Bill Barber]] and hornists [[James Buffington]] and [[Julius Watkins]] (along with two others), but each section features the cream of the younger (some more classically trained) musicians who were making their names in jazz. The presence of four of the most acclaimed young bassists ([[Richard Davis (bassist)|Richard Davis]], [[Paul Chambers]], [[Ron Carter]], and [[Ben Tucker]]) along with veteran [[Milt Hinton]] would ordinarily indicate that each is used individually for separate tracks, but Evans's scores usually required at least two bassists on any given track, some playing ''arco'' (with the bow) and some ''pizzicato'' (plucking with fingers, the standard jazz method). These arrangements frequently featured greatly slowed-down tempos with [[polyrhythmic]] percussion and no prevailing \"beat\". To his by-now standard French horns and tuba, Evans's scores added [[Alto flute|alto]] and [[bass flute]]s, [[double reed]]s, and [[harp]]; orchestral instruments not associated with \"swing\" bands, providing a larger pallette of orchestral colors, and allowing him to attain the ethereal quality heard in his arrangements during his Thornhill days.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> He frequently wrote a part for the [[tenor violin]] of [[Harry Lookofsky]]. Yet, this album featured an orchestral arrangement of \"[[Spoonful]]\" by bluesman [[Willie Dixon]], an early indication of Evans's breadth and a hint of things to come.\n\nIn 1966, he recorded an album with Brazilian singer [[Astrud Gilberto]], ''[[Look to the Rainbow (Astrud Gilberto album)|Look to the Rainbow]]''.<ref name=book>{{cite book|title=Gil Evans: Out of the Cool: His Life and Music|url=https://archive.org/details/gilevansoutofco00stei|url-access=registration|author=Crease, Stephanie Stein|publisher=A Capella Books|pages=[https://archive.org/details/gilevansoutofco00stei/page/362 362-366]|year=2002|isbn=1556529864}}</ref> He was discouraged by the commercial direction [[Verve Records]] was taking with the Gilberto sessions, and he went into a period of hiatus.\n\nDuring this period while he was somewhat depressed about the commercial and logistical difficulties of his previous scoring requirements, his wife suggested that he listen to the guitarist [[Jimi Hendrix]]. Evans developed a particular interest in the work of the rock guitarist. Evans gradually built another orchestra in the 1970s, with none of the coloration instruments from his past arrangements. Working in the [[free jazz]] and [[jazz-rock]] idioms, he gained a new generation of admirers. These ensembles, rarely more than fifteen and frequently smaller, allowed him to make more contributions on keyboards, and with the development of truly portable [[synthesizers]], he began using these to provide additional color.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> Hendrix's 1970 death precluded a scheduled meeting with Evans to discuss having Hendrix collaborate with a big band led by Evans.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jerryjazzmusician.com/2001/12/stephanie-stein-crease-author-of-gil-evans-out-of-the-cool/|title=Gil Evans: Out of the Cool: His Life and Music|author=Crease, Stephanie Stein|publisher=[[Chicago Review Press]]|year=2003|isbn=978-1556524936}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, he released an album of his, and other band member's, arrangements of music by Hendrix with guitarists [[John Abercrombie (guitarist)|John Abercrombie]] and [[Ryo Kawasaki]].<ref name=book/> From then on Evans's ensembles featured electric instruments, i.e. guitars, basses, and synthesizers including a collaboration with bassist [[Jaco Pastorius]]. In contrast to his intricate scores for large ensembles, which required precision orchestral playing accompanying a single soloist, his later arrangements would feature more unison playing by the entire ensemble, such as on Hendrix's \"[[Little Wing]]\", with improvisational touches added throughout by the musicians.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> Live recordings demonstrate that some entire pieces were collaborative efforts, and Evans can be heard giving cues from the keyboard (behind the band) to guide the band. Before the 1970s, his keyboard playing was generally sparse on recordings but after the 1970s he took a more active role in the rhythm section of the band.\n\n''[[Where Flamingos Fly]]'' (recorded 1971, released 1981) demonstrated his ability to contract the most accomplished musicians, with veterans Coles, [[Harry Lookofsky]], [[Richard Davis (double bassist)|Richard Davis]] and [[Jimmy Knepper]] (who played the solo on the \"Where Flamingos Fly\" track on 1961's ''[[Out of the Cool]]'') alongside young multi-instrumentalist [[Howard Johnson (jazz musician)|Howard Johnson]], synthesizer player [[Don Preston]] (at that time still a member of [[The Mothers of Invention]]), and [[Billy Harper]].\n\nIn April 1983, the Gil Evans Orchestra was booked into the [[Sweet Basil Jazz Club]] ([[Greenwich Village]], [[New York (state)|New York]]) by jazz producer and Sweet Basil owner [[Horst Liepolt]]. This turned out to be a regular Monday night engagement for Evans for nearly five years and also resulted in the release of a number of successful albums by ''Gil Evans and the Monday Night Orchestra''.<ref name=aaj>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/hidden-treasures-vol-1-monday-nights-the-gil-evans-orchestra-bopper-spock-suns-music-review-by-jerome-wilson.php|author=Jerome Wilson|title=The Gil Evans Orchestra: Hidden Treasures Vol. 1, Monday Nights|website=All About Jazz|date=December 31, 2018|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Nakayama |first=Yasuki |date=2018 |title=\u30b9\u30a4\u30f3\u30b0\u30b8\u30e3\u30fc\u30ca\u30eb\u6642\u4ee3\u306e\u4e2d\u5c71\u5eb7\u6a39 |trans-title=Yasuki Nakayama in \"Swing Journal\" era |url= |language=Japanese |location=Tokyo, Japan |publisher=Shinko Music Entertainment |chapter=\u30ae\u30eb\u30fb\u30a8\u30f4\u30a1\u30f3\u30b9\u306e\u30de\u30f3\u30c7\u30a3\u30fb\u30ca\u30a4\u30c8\u30fb\u30bb\u30c3\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 |trans-chapter=Gil Evans' Monday night sessions |pages=68-78 |isbn=}}</ref> Evans's ensemble featured many of the top-call musicians in New York, many of whom were also in the [[NBC]] [[Saturday Night Live Band]] and there were many conflicts, so their \"deputies\" for the night might be other world-class musicians. Yet Evans was also known to let newcomers \"sit in\" occasionally. The band also performed arrangements by band members, current and past. Stalwarts in this ensemble were [[Lew Soloff]], [[Alan Rubin]], [[Marvin Peterson]], [[Tom Malone (musician)|Tom \"Bones\" Malone]], [[George Adams (musician)]], [[David Sanborn]], [[Hiram Bullock]], Mark Eagan, drummer Kenwood Dennard, saxophonist [[Bill Evans (saxophonist)|Bill Evans]] (no relation) and Gil Goldstein. In 1987, Evans recorded a live album with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], featuring big band arrangements of songs by and with [[The Police]]. In the same spirit of introducing new talent in his bands, he collaborated with [[Maria Schneider (musician)|Maria Schneider]] with her as an apprentice arranger on this and other final projects. His final project was Nov. 3 & 26, 1987, his arrangements for the Laurent Cugny Big Band in Paris, on the recording \u201cGolden Hair\u201d on Emarcy/Polygram.\n\n===Ryan Truesdell presents the Gil Evans Project===\n[[Ryan Truesdell]] [[:de:Ryan Truesdell|(de)]] began the Gil Evans Project, which resulted in a 2012 CD entitled ''Centennial'', featuring previously unrecorded compositions and arrangements. These were produced with the permission of the Gil Evans estate, who gave Truesdell access to these scores and materials. Miles Evans, Gil's son, also led the Gil Evans Orchestra for a centennial concert at New York's [[Highline Ballroom]], featuring many of the musicians heard in the orchestra during Evans's lifetime.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allaboutjazz.com/ryan-truesdell-the-gil-evans-project-ryan-truesdell-by-victor-l-schermer.php|title=Ryan Truesdell: The Gil Evans Project|author=Victor L. Schermer|website=[[All About Jazz]]|date=July 25, 2011|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Film music==\nIn 1986, Evans produced and arranged the soundtrack to the film of the [[Colin MacInnes]] book ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)|Absolute Beginners]]'', thereby working with such contemporary artists as [[Sade Adu]], [[Patsy Kensit]]'s Eighth Wonder, [[the Style Council]], [[Jerry Dammers]], [[Smiley Culture]], [[Edward Tudor-Pole]], and [[David Bowie]].\n\nHe also arranged the music for the 1986 [[Martin Scorsese]] film ''[[The Color of Money]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nEvans first married following the 1949 ''[[Birth of the Cool]]'' recording sessions to Lillian Grace. Very little is known about this marriage. In 1963, he would marry again. Evans was survived by his second wife Anita (Cooper) and two children, Noah and Miles. His son Miles played trumpet in his ''Monday Night Orchestra''.<ref name=aaj/>\n\nEvans died of [[peritonitis]] in [[Cuernavaca]], Mexico, contracting it shortly after a surgery for his prostate and subsequent travel to Mexico to recover. Evans died at the age of 75.<ref name=nytobit>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/22/obituaries/gil-evans-a-key-jazz-composer-and-orchestrator-is-dead-at-75.html|title=Gil Evans, a Key Jazz Composer And Orchestrator, Is Dead at 75|author=Watrous, Peter|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 22, 1988}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, [[Columbia Studio Recordings]] had released a box set which besides the masterpieces, featured outtakes and rarities of Miles Davis and Gil Evans.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Picks and Pans Review: Miles Davis & Gil Evans: the Complete Columbia Studio Recordings|magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]]|date=October 14, 1996|volume=46|number=16}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Gil Evans among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Rosen, Jody|title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html|magazine=[[The New York Times Magazine]]|date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n*In 1986, Evans was inducted into the ''[[Down Beat]]'' Jazz Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://downbeat.com/archives/detail/downbeat-hall-of-fame|title=DownBeat Hall of Fame|magazine=[[DownBeat]]}}</ref> He was also inducted into the Canadian Music Hall of Fame in 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canadianmusichalloffame.ca/inductee/gil-evans/|title=Gil Evans \u2013 Canadian Music Hall Of Fame|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Grammy Awards===\nAwarded as followings:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/gil-evans |title=Artist: Gil Evans |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=The GRAMMYs|publisher=Recording Academy |access-date=March 23, 2020 |quote=}}</ref>\n*[[3rd Annual Grammy Awards|1960]]: ''[[Sketches of Spain]]'' (with [[Miles Davis]], [[Grammy Award for Best Original Jazz Composition|Best Jazz Composition of More Than Five Minutes Duration]])\n*[[31st Annual Grammy Awards|1988]]: ''[[Bud and Bird]]'' (posthumously with the Monday Night Orchestra, [[Grammy Award for Best Large Jazz Ensemble Album|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Big Band]])\n*[[39th Annual Grammy Awards|1997]]: (''[[Miles Davis & Gil Evans: The Complete Columbia Studio Recordings]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Historical Album|Best Historical Album]] for the Compilation Producers and/or Mastering Engineers))\n*[[55th Annual Grammy Awards|2012]]: \"How About You\" in ''[[Centennial - Newly Discovered Works of Gil Evans]]'' (posthumously with Gil Evans Project, [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement|Best Instrumental Arrangement]])\n\n====Grammy Award nominations====\n*[[4th Annual Grammy Awards|1961]]: ''[[Out of the Cool]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Performance Solo or Small Group]])\n*[[5th Annual Grammy Awards|1962]]: ''[[Miles Davis at Carnegie Hall]]'' (with [[Miles Davis]], [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Performance Solo or Small Group (Instrumental)]])\n*[[7th Annual Grammy Awards|1964]]: ''[[The Individualism of Gil Evans]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Instrumental Jazz Performance \u2013 Small Group or Soloist]])\n*1964: ''[[Quiet Nights (Miles Davis and Gil Evans album)|Quiet Nights]]'' (with Miles Davis, Best Instrumental Jazz Performance \u2013 Small Group or Soloist)\n*[[8th Annual Grammy Awards|1965]]: [[Kenny Burrell]]'s ''[[Guitar Forms]]'' (with Kenny Burrell, [[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Instrumental Jazz Performance \u2013 Soloist or Small Group]])\n*1965: \"Greensleeves\" in Kenny Burrell's ''Guitar Forms'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Arrangement, Instrumental or A Cappella|Best Instrumental Arrangement]])\n*[[16th Annual Grammy Awards|1973]]: ''[[Svengali (album)|Svengali]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Performance by a Group]])\n*[[26th Annual Grammy Awards|1983]]: ''[[Priestess (album)|Priestess]]'' ([[Grammy Award for Best Jazz Instrumental Album|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Group]])\n*[[55th Annual Grammy Awards|2012]]: \"Look to the Rainbow\" in ''[[Centennial - Newly Discovered Works of Gil Evans]]'' (posthumously with Gil Evans Project & [[Luciana Souza]], [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)|Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)]])\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Gil Evans & Ten]]'' ([[Prestige Records|Prestige]], 1958) \u2013 recorded in 1957\n* ''[[New Bottle Old Wine]]'' ([[World Pacific Records|World Pacific]], 1958)\n* ''[[Great Jazz Standards]]'' (World Pacific, 1959)\n* ''[[Out of the Cool]]'' ([[Impulse! Records|Impulse!]], 1961) \u2013 recorded in 1960\n* ''[[Into the Hot (Gil Evans album)|Into the Hot]]'' (Impulse!, 1962) \u2013 recorded in 1961\n* ''[[The Individualism of Gil Evans]]'' ([[Verve Records|Verve]], 1964) \u2013 recorded in 1963 and 1964\n* ''Gil Evans'' ([[Ampex#Record labels|Ampex]], 1969) - rereleased as ''[[Blues in Orbit (Gil Evans album)|Blues in Orbit]]'' ([[Enja Records|Enja]], 1971) \u2013 rerecorded two tracks\n* ''[[Satin Doll (Kimiko Kasai album)|Satin Doll]]'' ([[Sony Music Entertainment Japan|CBS/Sony]], 1972) \u2013 with [[Kimiko Kasai]]\n* ''[[Masabumi Kikuchi with Gil Evans]]'' ([[Philips Records|Philips]] [Japan], 1972) \u2013 CD version ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]], 1989)\n* ''[[The Gil Evans Orchestra Plays the Music of Jimi Hendrix]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]], 1974)\n* ''[[There Comes a Time (album)|There Comes a Time]]'' (RCA, 1976)  \u2013 recorded in 1975\n* ''[[Parabola (album)|Parabola]]'' (Horo, 1979) \u2013 recorded in 1978\n* ''[[Where Flamingos Fly]]'' ([[Artists House]], 1981) \u2013 recorded in 1971\n* ''[[Collaboration (Helen Merrill and Gil Evans album)|Collaboration]]'' (EmArcy, 1987) - with [[Helen Merrill]]\n'''Posthumous releases'''\n* ''[[Paris Blues (album)|Paris Blues]]'' (Owl, 1988) - recorded in 1987 with [[Steve Lacy (saxophonist)|Steve Lacy]]\n* ''[[Rhythm A Ning (album)|Rhythm A Ning]]'' (EmArcy, 1988) \u2013 recorded in 1987 with [[Laurent Cugny]] Big Band Lumiere\n* ''[[Golden Hair (album)|Golden Hair]]'' (EmArcy, 1989) - recorded in 1987 with Laurent Cugny Big Band Lumiere\n* ''The Mother of the Book'' (InRespect, 1994<!--; [[Entertainment One Music|Koch Jazz]], 1996-->) - recorded in <!--February 23-24, -->1985 with {{ill|Glen Hall (musician)|de|Glen Hall}}\n\n===Live albums===\n''In recorded date order''\n*1973: ''[[Svengali (album)|Svengali]]'' ([[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], 1973)\n*1974: ''Montreux Jazz Festival '74'' ([[Philips Records|Philips]] [Japan], 1975)\n*<!--May 24 \u2013 June 8, -->1976: ''Tokyo Concert'' (Studio Songs, 2010) \u2013 remastering by [[Ryo Kawasaki]]\n*<!--October 23, -->1976: ''Synthetic Evans'' (PolJazz, unknown)  also released as ''Live 76'' (EPM Zeta, 1988) \u2013 unofficial release\n*<!--October 30, -->1976: ''Live in Dortmund 1976'' (Jazz Trafffic, 2012) \u2013 with guest [[Roland Kirk]]\n*1977: ''[[Priestess (album)|Priestess]]'' (Antilles, 1983)\n*<!--February 25, -->1978: ''[[Gil Evans Live at the Royal Festival Hall London 1978]]'' ([[RCA Records|RCA]], 1979)\n*<!--February 25, -->1978: ''The Rest of Gil Evans at the Royal Festival Hall 1978'' (Mole Jazz, 1981)\n*<!--October 19, -->1978: ''Little Wing: Live in Germany'' ([[Circle Records (Germany)|Circle]], 1978)\n*1980: ''[[Heroes (Gil Evans and Lee Konitz album)|Heroes]]'' (Verve/Remark, 1991) \u2013 with [[Lee Konitz]]\n*1980: ''[[Anti-Heroes (Lee Konitz and Gil Evans album)|Anti-Heroes]]'' (Verve/Remark, 1991) - with Lee Konitz\n*1980: ''[[Live at the Public Theater (New York 1980)]]'' Vol.1 (Trio, 1980)\n*1980: ''Live at the Public Theater (New York 1980)'' Vol.2 (Trio, 1981)\n*1981: ''Lunar Eclypse'' (Newtone, 2000)\n*1983: ''British Orchestra: the Complete Concert'' (Mole Jazz, 1983)\n*1984: ''[[Live at Sweet Basil (Gil Evans album)|Live at Sweet Basil]]'' ([[King Records (Japan)|King]]/Electric Bird, 1985)\n*1984: ''[[Live at Sweet Basil Vol. 2]]'' (King/Electric Bird, 1987)\n*1986: ''Live 1986 - Unissued'' (Musica Jazz, 1994) \u2013 also released as ''The Honey Man'' (New Tone, 1995)\n*1986: ''[[Bud and Bird]]'' (King, 1987) \u2013 [[31st Annual Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Best Large Jazz Ensemble Album|Best Jazz Instrumental Performance, Big Band]]\n*1986: ''[[Farewell (Gil Evans album)|Farewell]]'' (King, 1992)\n*1987: ''75th Birthday Concert'' ([[BBC Music|BBC Legends]], 2001)\n*1987: ''Last Session - Live at \"Perugia Jazz Festival\" July 11, 1987'' (Jazz Door, 1992) \u2013 with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], unofficial release.\n*1987: ''Live at Umbria Jazz'' Volume 1 (Egea, 2000)\n*1987: ''Live at Umbria Jazz'' Volume 2 (Egea, 2001)\n\n===Arranged albums===\n''In recorded date order''\n*1947-49: [[Claude Thornhill]] Orchestra, ''The Real Birth of the Cool: Studio Recordings'' ([[Sony Music Entertainment Japan|CBS/Sony]], 1971)\n*1949-50: [[Miles Davis]], ''[[Birth of the Cool]]'' ([[Capitol Records|Capitol]], 1957)\n*1950-52: [[Charlie Parker]], ''[[Big Band (Charlie Parker album)|Big Band]]'' ([[Clef Records|Clef]], 1954)\n*<!--December -->1955: [[Hal McKusick]], ''The Jazz Workshop'' ([[RCA Victor Records|RCA Victor]], 1956)\n*1956: [[Johnny Mathis]], ''[[Johnny Mathis (album)|Johnny Mathis]]'' ([[Columbia Records|Columbia]], 1956)\n*1956: Marcy Lutes, ''Debut'' ([[Decca Records|Decca]], 1956)\n*<!--January -->1957: [[Lucy Reed]], ''This Is Lucy Reed'' ([[Fantasy Records|Fantasy]], 1957)\n*1956-<!--February -->57: [[Helen Merrill]], ''[[Dream of You (Helen Merrill album)|Dream of You]]'' ([[EmArcy Records|EmArcy]], 1957)\n*<!--May & August -->1957: Miles Davis, ''[[Miles Ahead (album)|Miles Ahead]]'' (Columbia, 1957)\n*1958?: [[Don Elliott]] Octet, ''Jamaica Jazz'' (ABC-Paramount, 1958)\n*1958: Miles Davis, ''[[Porgy and Bess (Miles Davis album)|Porgy and Bess]]'' (Columbia, 1959)\n*1959-60: Miles Davis, ''[[Sketches of Spain]]'' (Columbia, 1960) \u2013 [[3rd Annual Grammy Awards]]: [[Grammy Award for Best Original Jazz Composition|Best Jazz Composition of More Than Five Minutes Duration]]\n*1961: Miles Davis, ''[[Miles Davis at Carnegie Hall]]'' (Columbia, 1962)\n*1962-63: Miles Davis, ''[[Quiet Nights (Miles Davis and Gil Evans album)|Quiet Nights]]'' (Columbia, 1963)\n*1964-65: [[Kenny Burrell]], ''[[Guitar Forms]]'' ([[Verve Records|Verve]], 1965)\n*1965-66: [[Astrud Gilberto]], ''[[Look to the Rainbow (Astrud Gilberto album)|Look to the Rainbow]]'' (Verve, 1966)\n*1968: Miles Davis, ''[[Filles de Kilimanjaro]]'' (Columbia, 1968) \u2013 without credits<ref name=\"szwed\">{{cite book|last=Szwed|first=John|title=So What: The Life of Miles Davis|url=https://archive.org/details/sowhatlifeofmile00szwe|url-access=registration|edition=first|year=2002|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|location=New York|isbn=0-684-85982-3}}</ref>{{Rp|273}}\n*1982-83: Miles Davis, ''[[Star People]]'' (Columbia, 1983)\n*1983: Miles Davis, ''[[Decoy (album)|Decoy]]'' (Columbia, 1984) \u2013 only \"That's Right\"\n\n===Compilation/Box set===\n* With [[Kenny Burrell]] and [[Phil Woods]], ''Gil Evans Orch., Kenny Burrell and Phil Woods \u2013 Previously Unreleased Recordings'' (Verve, 1973) \u2013 recorded in 1963 and 1964\n*''Take Me To The Sun'' (Last Chance Music, 1990) \u2013 tracks #1\u2013#3 are live recording at \"[[Montreux Jazz Festival]] 1983\" with [[RMS (band)|RMS]]. track #4 is the last studio recording in 1988<!-- at RPM Studio NYC-->.\n*''Verve Jazz Masters 23: Gil Evans'' (Verve, 1994)\n* With [[Miles Davis]], ''[[Miles Davis & Gil Evans: The Complete Columbia Studio Recordings]]'' ([[Columbia records|Columbia]], 1996) \u2013 recorded from 1957 to 1968. [[39th Annual Grammy Awards|39th Annual Grammy]] [[Grammy Award for Best Historical Album|Best Historical Album]].\n* With Miles Davis, ''The Historic Collaboration In Words & Music'' (Columbia, 1996)\n*''Voodoo Chile''\uff08Jazz Door, 2005) \u2013  Live recording of 1974 in Sweden and 1978 in Germany.\n\n===Soundtrack album===\n* ''[[Absolute Beginners (film)#Soundtrack|Absolute Beginners: The Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' (EMI, 1986)\n\n===Tribute albums===\n* The Gil Evans Orchestra, ''Tribute to Gil'' (Soul Note, 1988) \u2013 at Umbria and Sicilia Jazz Festival\n* [[Ryan Truesdell]]'s Gil Evans Project, ''[[Centennial - Newly Discovered Works of Gil Evans]]'' (ArtistShare, 2013) \u2013 recorded in 2012. [[55th Annual Grammy Awards|55th Annual Grammy]] [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement|Best Instrumental Arrangement]]: \"How About You\".\n* Ryan Truesdell's Gil Evans Project, ''[[Lines of Color]]'' ([[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]], 2015) \u2013 recorded in 2014\n\n==Filmography==\n*2005: ''RMS Live with Gil Evans at the Montreux Jazz Festival 1983''\n*2007: ''Gil Evans and His Orchestra''<ref>{{cite web|author=Evans, Gil|work=View Video|url=http://www.view.com/gil_evans_and_his_orchestra_dvd.aspx|title=Gil Evans and his Orchestra|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n*2007: ''Strange Fruit with Sting''\n*2009: ''Miles Davis \u2013 The Cool Jazz Sound''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of jazz arrangers]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{commons category|Gil Evans}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.gilevans.com}}\n*{{Discogs artist|255137-Gil-Evans}}\n*{{IMDb name|0262789}}\n*{{Find a Grave|19222}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CCX2874500158|title=Evans, Gil|encyclopedia= The Scribner Encyclopedia of American Lives|volume=2: 1986-1990|publisher=Charles Scribner's Sons|editor1-first=Kenneth T. |editor1-last=Jackson |editor2-first= Karen|editor2-last=Markoe |editor3-first=Arnold|editor3-last=Markoe|date=1999|via=[[Gale Academic Onefile]]}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/gil-evans|title=Gil Evans|date=2019-02-15|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-15}}\n\n{{Gil Evans}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evans, Gil}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:Jazz arrangers]]\n[[Category:Cool jazz arrangers]]\n[[Category:Jazz fusion arrangers]]\n[[Category:Post-bop arrangers]]\n[[Category:Experimental big band arrangers]]\n[[Category:Canadian jazz bandleaders]]\n[[Category:Big band bandleaders]]\n[[Category:Canadian Music Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Antilles Records artists]]\n[[Category:Verve Records artists]]\n[[Category:Enja Records artists]]\n[[Category:EmArcy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Impulse! Records artists]]\n[[Category:ACT Music artists]]\n[[Category:Miles Davis]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian musicians]]\n[[Category:Progressive big band musicians]]\n[[Category:New York Jazz Repertory Company members]]\n", "name_user": "Yasuo Miyakawa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gil_Evans"}
{"title_page": "Grease (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1978 romantic musical film directed by Randal Kleiser}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Grease\n| image          = Grease ver2.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Randal Kleiser]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Stigwood]]\n* [[Allan Carr]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''|[[Jim Jacobs]]<br/>[[Warren Casey]]}}\n| screenplay     = [[Bronte Woodard]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John Travolta]]\n* [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n* [[Stockard Channing]]\n* [[Jeff Conway]]\n* [[Eve Arden]]\n* [[Frankie Avalon]]\n* [[Joan Blondell]]\n* [[Edd Byrnes]]\n* [[Sid Caesar]]\n* [[Alice Ghostley]]\n* [[Dody Goodman]]\n* [[Sha Na Na]]}}\n| music          = [[Michael Gibson (musician)|Michael Gibson]]\n| cinematography = [[Bill Butler (cinematographer)|Bill Butler]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* John F. Burnett\n* Robert Pergament\n}}\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Pictures]]\n* [[Allan Carr|Allan Carr Productions]]\n* [[RSO Records|Robert Stigwood Organization]]\n* [[Polydor Records]]\n}}\n| distributor    = Paramount Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1978|6|16}}\n| runtime        = 110 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $6 million<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n| gross          = $396 million<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\">{{mojo title|grease|Grease}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Grease''''' is a 1978 American [[Musical film|musical]] [[romantic comedy]] film based on the [[Grease (musical)|1971 musical of the same name]] by [[Jim Jacobs]] and [[Warren Casey]]. Written by [[Bronte Woodard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/grease-movie-soundtrack-earns-its-second-1-hit |title=Grease movie soundtrack earns its second #1 hit |publisher=History.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref> and directed by [[Randal Kleiser]] in his theatrical feature film debut, the film depicts the lives of [[Greaser (subculture)|greaser]] Danny Zuko and Australian transfer student Sandy Olsson who develop an attraction for each other. The film stars [[John Travolta]] as Danny, [[Olivia Newton-John]] as Sandy, and [[Stockard Channing]] as Betty Rizzo, the leader of the Pink Ladies.\n\nReleased on June 16, 1978, ''Grease'' was successful both critically and commercially becoming the [[List of highest-grossing musicals#Timeline of highest-grossing musical films|highest-grossing musical film ever]] at the time.<ref name=Carr>{{cite book |last=Hofler |first=Robert |title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock 'N' Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr |publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com |year=2010 |isbn=9781459600072 |page=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iqRezpQzUcAC&pg=PA145 145] |quote=Despite the fact that Grease was well on its way to becoming the highest-grossing movie musical in the world, and eventually grossed over $341&nbsp;million...}}</ref> Its [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture|soundtrack album]] ended 1978 as the [[List of best-selling albums by year in the United States#1970s|second-best-selling album of the year in the United States]], behind the [[Saturday Night Fever: The Original Movie Sound Track|soundtrack]] of the 1977 blockbuster ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'' (which also starred Travolta)<ref name=\"bboard78\"/> and earned the film its lone [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nomination for \"[[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\" (which lost the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] to [[Donna Summer]]'s \"[[Last Dance (Donna Summer song)|Last Dance]]\" from ''[[Thank God It's Friday (film)|Thank God It's Friday]]'' at the [[51st Academy Awards]]).\n\nA sequel, ''[[Grease 2]]'', was released in 1982, starring [[Maxwell Caulfield]] and [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] as a newer class of greasers. Few of the original cast members reprised their roles. As of 2019, an HBO Max series based on the film is in production.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inquirer.com/entertainment/movies/grease-rydell-high-hbo-max-streaming-summer-loving-radnor-high-school-20191017.html}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- PER WP:FILMPLOT, PLOT SUMMARIES SHOULD BE 400-700 WORDS. -->\nIn the summer of 1958, local boy Danny Zuko and vacationing Sandy Olsson meet at the beach and fall in love. When the summer comes to an end, Sandy\u2014who is going back to Australia\u2014frets that they may never meet again, but Danny tells her that their love is \"only beginning\". The film moves to the start of the seniors' term at Rydell High School. Danny is a member and leader of the T-Birds [[greaser (subculture)|greaser]] gang, consisting of his best friend Kenickie, Doody, Sonny, and Putzie. The Pink Ladies, a clique of greaser girls, also arrive, consisting of leader Rizzo, Frenchy, Marty, and Jan.\n\nAfter her parents decide not to return to Australia, Sandy enrolls at Rydell and is befriended by Frenchy, who considers dropping out of school to become a beautician. Unaware of each other's presence at Rydell, Danny and Sandy tell their respective groups the accounts of events during the pair's brief romance, without initially mentioning the other's name (\"Summer Nights\"). Sandy's version emphasizes the romance of the relationship, while Danny's version is more sexual.\n\nWhen Sandy finally says Danny's name, Rizzo arranges a surprise reunion for the two, but Danny is forced to maintain his bad-boy attitude in front of his pals, upsetting Sandy, who storms off and begins dating Tom, a [[jock (subculture)|jock]]. Kenickie unveils the used car, Greased Lightnin', that he plans on restoring and racing (\"Greased Lightnin'\"). Frenchy invites the girls to a pajama party, but Sandy falls ill from the sight of blood after getting her ears pierced by Frenchy, Rizzo starts to make fun of Sandy (\"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee\"). While Sandy is outside, she soon starts to think of Danny, and how much she loves him even though he hurt her (\"Hopelessly Devoted to You\"). Rizzo departs to have sex with Kenickie, during which his condom breaks. The two are disturbed by Leo, leader of the T-Birds' rival gang, the Scorpions, and his girlfriend Cha-Cha.\n\nIn an attempt to impress Sandy, Danny turns to Coach Calhoun to get into sports, eventually becoming a runner. He reunites with Sandy and they attempt to go on a date, but their friends crash it. Kenickie and a distressed Rizzo argue and split up. Left alone, Frenchy is visited by a [[guardian angel]] who advises her to return to school after a mishap in beauty class leaves her with candy-pink hair (\"Beauty School Dropout\").\n\nThe school dance arrives, broadcast live on television and hosted by DJ Vince Fontaine, who flirts with Marty. Rizzo and Kenickie attempt to spite one another by bringing Leo and Cha-Cha as their dates. Danny and Sandy arrive together and dance well during the chaotic [[hand jive]] contest (\"Born to Hand Jive\"); just before the end of the contest Sonny pulls Sandy off the dance floor, and Cha-Cha cuts in to win the contest with Danny, causing Sandy to leave the event broken-hearted.\n\nDanny tries to make it up to Sandy by taking her to a drive-in theater (\"Alone at the Drive-in Movies\") but forces himself on her, causing Sandy to leave (\"Sandy\"). Meanwhile Rizzo fears she is pregnant after missing a period and confides in Marty, but Marty tells Sonny and he inadvertently spreads the rumor to Kenickie, the apparent father, though Rizzo denies this to him. At school, Rizzo is getting laughed at by other girls, and she soon realizes that she isn't as tough as she seems (\"There Are Worse Things I Could Do\").\n\nOn race day, Kenickie suffers a concussion when hit by his own car door, so Danny takes the wheel. He and Leo race until Leo crashes and leaves humiliated, with Danny as the victor. Sandy watches from afar, concluding she still loves Danny, and decides to change her attitude and look to impress him; she then asks Frenchy for help to achieve this goal (\"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee (Reprise)\").\n\nOn the last day of school, Principal McGee and her assistant Blanche sob about the departing class. Rizzo discovers she is not pregnant and reunites with Kenickie. Danny has lettered in track but is shocked when Sandy arrives dressed as a female T-Bird. In song (\"You're the One That I Want\"), they confess their mutual love and reconcile. The class celebrates their graduation at the fair on school grounds (\"We Go Together\"). Sandy and Danny depart in Greased Lightnin', which takes flight (\"Grease\").\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Principal cast===\n* [[John Travolta]] as Danny Zuko, who lives a double life as leader of the greaser gang the T-Birds and as Sandy's boyfriend\n* [[Olivia Newton-John]] as Sandy Olsson, Danny's girlfriend and an Australian [[immigrant]] and [[ing\u00e9nue]], who transforms from square to greaser\n* [[Stockard Channing]] as Betty Rizzo, Kenickie's girlfriend and the cynical leader of the Pink Ladies clique\n* [[Jeff Conaway]] as Kenickie Murdoch, Danny's best friend, Rizzo's boyfriend and the owner of Greased Lightnin'\n* [[Barry Pearl]] as Doody, a member of the T-Birds; he pairs with Frenchy at the school dance\n* [[Michael Tucci]] as Sonny LaTieri, a trouble-making wannabe womanizer and T-Bird who courts Marty with little success over the course of the film\n* [[Kelly Ward]] as Putzie, a member of the T-Birds whose relationship with Jan builds over the course of the film\n* [[Didi Conn]] as Frenchy, Sandy's closest friend in the Pink Ladies and an aspiring beautician\n* [[Jamie Donnelly]] as Jan, a quirky member of the Pink Ladies with a liking for [[Ipana]] toothpaste\n* [[Dinah Manoff]] as Marty Maraschino, a member of the Pink Ladies whose attractiveness regularly draws the attention of men, including Sonny and Vince Fontaine\n\n===Secondary cast===\n* [[Eve Arden]] as Principal McGee, who shows discomfort at the goings-on at Rydell High.\n* [[Dody Goodman]] as Secretary Blanche Hodel, who enjoys even the wilder antics at the school.\n* [[Sid Caesar]] as Coach Vince Calhoun, the tough-talking gym teacher and coach of all the school's perennially losing sports teams\n* [[Eddie Deezen]] as Eugene Felsnick, the class nerd\n* [[Susan Buckner]] as Patty Simcox, the head cheerleader and a rival for Danny's affections\n* [[Lorenzo Lamas]] as Tom Chisum, a popular jock who competes for Sandy's affections\n* [[Dennis Cleveland Stewart|Dennis C. Stewart]] as Leo \"Craterface\" Balmudo, leader of the Scorpions, a rival greaser gang\n* [[Annette Charles]] as Charlene \"Cha-Cha\" Di Gregorio, Leo's girlfriend\n* [[Joan Blondell]] as Vi, a waitress at the Frosty Palace\n* [[Ellen Travolta]] as Waitress\n* [[Frankie Avalon]] as Teen Angel\n* [[Edd Byrnes]] as Vince Fontaine, on-air personality at KZAZ radio and television\n* [[Sha-Na-Na]] as Johnny Casino and the Gamblers, a rock and roll band\n* [[Alice Ghostley]] as Mrs. Murdock, a rogue auto shop teacher who helps build Greased Lightnin' for the T-Birds\n* [[Darrell Zwerling]] as Mr. Lynch\n* Dick Patterson as Mr. Rudie\n* [[Fannie Flagg]] as Nurse Wilkins\n\n==Production==\n\n===Casting===\n[[John Travolta]] had previously worked with producer [[Robert Stigwood]] on ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'', had a nascent singing career at the time (including the top-10 hit \"[[Let Her In]]\" in 1976), and had previously appeared as Doody in a touring production of the stage version of ''Grease''. He made a number of casting recommendations that Stigwood ultimately accepted, including suggesting [[Randal Kleiser]] (who had never directed a theatrical feature before this but had directed Travolta in the 1976 telefilm ''[[The Boy in the Plastic Bubble]]'') as director, and [[Olivia Newton-John]], then known almost exclusively as a multiple Grammy winning pop and country singer, as Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Travolta|first=John|title=Inside the Actor's Studio}}</ref> Newton-John had done little acting before this film, with only two film credits (1965's ''[[Funny Things Happen Down Under]]'' and the unreleased 1970 film ''[[Toomorrow (film)|Toomorrow]]'', which predated her singing breakthrough) to her name up to that time. Before accepting the role, Newton-John requested a [[screen test]] for ''Grease'' to avoid another career setback.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20071391,00.html |title=Ohh Sandy! \u2013 Olivia Newton-John |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |first=Robert |last=Windeler |date=July 31, 1978 |accessdate=November 10, 2008}}</ref> The screen test was done with the drive-in movie scene. Newton-John, who is native to England and lived most of her life in Australia, was unable to perform with a convincing American accent, and thus her character was rewritten to be Australian. Before Newton-John was hired, [[Allan Carr]] was considering numerous names such as [[Ann-Margret]], [[Susan Dey]] and [[Marie Osmond]] for the lead role; Newton-John agreed to a reduced asking price in exchange for star billing.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> In a case of life imitating art, Newton-John's own musical career would undergo a transformation similar to that of the Sandy Olsson character; her next album after ''Grease'', the provocatively titled ''[[Totally Hot]]'', featured a much more sexual and pop-oriented approach, with Newton-John appearing on the album cover in similar all-leather attire and teased hair.<ref name=\"google3\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo7xm-X1r4C&pg=PA334#PPA335,M1 |title=All music guide to country: the ... |publisher= Google Books |date= |accessdate=August 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeff Conaway]], like Travolta, had previously appeared in the stage version of ''Grease''; he had played Danny Zuko during the show's run on Broadway.<ref name=newsdayobit>{{cite news|authorlink=Frank Lovece |last=Lovece |first=Frank |url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/obituaries/grease-taxi-star-jeff-conaway-dies-1.2907909 |title='Grease,' 'Taxi' Star Jeff Conaway Dies |work=[[Newsday]] |date=May 27, 2011 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4Hujzwq?url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/obituaries/grease-taxi-star-jeff-conaway-dies-1.2907909?p= |archivedate=May 30, 2011 |df= }} (Subscription required.) . Print edition, May 28, 2011, p. A32</ref> [[Jamie Donnelly]] reprised her role as Jan from the Broadway show, the only cast member to do so; as her hair had begun to gray by this point, she had to dye her hair to resemble her stage character.<ref name=people98>Gliatto, Tom; and O'Neill Anne-Marie. [http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20124959,00.html \"Grease Is the Word: Twenty Years Later, the Stars Are Still True to Their School\"], ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', April 13, 1998. Accessed September 13, 2011.</ref> [[Kelly Ward]] had previously appeared as a similar sarcastic supporting character in ''The Boy in the Plastic Bubble'' with Travolta under Kleiser; he was cast as Putzie, a mostly new character.\n\n[[Lorenzo Lamas]] was a last-minute replacement for [[Steven Ford]], who developed [[stage fright]] shortly before filming and backed out. His role contained no spoken dialogue and required Lamas to dye his hair blond to avoid looking like one of the T-Birds.<ref name=people98/>\n\nAdult film star [[Harry Reems]] was originally signed to play Coach Calhoun; however, executives at Paramount nixed the idea, concerned that his reputation as a porn star would hinder box office returns in the [[Southern United States]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/features/10988|title=The Afterlife of a Porn Star|publisher=New York Media, LLC|work=New York Magazine|date=May 21, 2005|accessdate=May 8, 2011|author=Itzkoff, Dave}}</ref> and producers cast [[Sid Caesar]] instead.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hofler|first=Robert |title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock 'n' Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr|year=2010|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=0-306-81655-5|page=66}}</ref> Caesar was one of several veterans of 1950s television ([[Eve Arden]], [[Frankie Avalon]], [[Joan Blondell]], [[Edd Byrnes]], [[Alice Ghostley]], [[Dody Goodman]]) to be cast in supporting roles. Coincidentally, Frankie Avalon and Randal Kleiser had both appeared in 1966's ''[[Fireball 500]]'', the latter as an extra.\n\n===Filming locations===\n[[File:Grease car race LA river.jpg|thumb|The car race in the film took place at the Los Angeles River.]]\nThe opening beach scene was shot at Malibu's [[Leo Carrillo State Park|Leo Carrillo State Beach]], making explicit reference to ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''. The exterior Rydell scenes, including the basketball, baseball and track segments, were shot at [[Venice High School (Los Angeles)|Venice High School]] in [[Venice, Los Angeles|Venice, California]], while the Rydell interiors, including the high school dance, were filmed at [[Huntington Park High School]]. The sleepover was shot at a private house in [[East Hollywood, Los Angeles|East Hollywood]]. The Paramount Pictures studio lot was the location of the scenes that involve Frosty Palace and the musical numbers \"Greased Lightning\" and \"Beauty School Dropout\". The drive-in movie scenes were shot at the Burbank Pickwick Drive-In (it was closed and torn down in 1989 and a shopping center took its place). The race was filmed at the [[Los Angeles River]], between the First and Seventh Street Bridges, where many other films have been shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/g/grease.html |title=Film locations for Grease (1978) |publisher=Movie-locations.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref> The final scene where the carnival took place used [[John Marshall High School (Los Angeles)|John Marshall High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seeing-stars.com/locations/grease.shtml |title=Grease Filming Locations {{ndash}} part 1 |publisher=Seeing-stars.com |date= |accessdate=2011-10-09}}</ref> Furthermore, owing to budget cuts, a short scene was filmed at [[Hazard Park]] in Los Angeles.\n\n===Post-production===\nScenes inside the Frosty Palace contain obvious blurring of various [[Coca-Cola]] signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scenesteal.com/html/grease |title=Grease |publisher=Scenesteal.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309185814/http://scenesteal.com/html/grease |archivedate=2011-03-09 |df= }}</ref> Prior to the film's release, producer Allan Carr had made a product-placement deal with Coca-Cola's main competitor [[Pepsi]] (for example, a Pepsi logo can be seen in the animated opening sequence). When Carr saw the footage of the scene with Coca-Cola products and signage, he ordered director Randal Kleiser to either reshoot the scene with Pepsi products or remove the Coca-Cola logos from the scene. As reshoots were deemed too expensive and time-consuming, optical mattes were used to cover up or blur out the Coca-Cola references. The 'blurring' covered up trademarked menu signage and a large wall poster, but a red cooler with the logo could not be sufficiently altered so was left unchanged. According to Kleiser, \"We just had to hope that Pepsi wouldn't complain. They didn't.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.stupidquestion.net/sq102600.html |title=Stupid Question |publisher=Archives.stupidquestion.net |date=2000-10-26 |accessdate=2010-08-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130071914/http://archives.stupidquestion.net/sq102600.html |archivedate=2007-11-30 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dvdtalk.com/dvdsavant/s70grease.html |title=DVD Savant: GREASE and the Curse of Product Placement |publisher= Dvdtalk.com |date=1998-08-18 |accessdate= 2010-08-16}}</ref>\n\nDue to an editing error, a closing scene in which Danny and Sandy kiss was removed from the finished print and lost before its theatrical release. The scene was preserved only in black-and-white; Kleiser attempted to have the existing footage [[Film colorization|colorized]] and restored to the film for the film's re-release in 1998 but was dissatisfied with the results. The scene is included as an extra on the 40th anniversary home video release, and Kleiser hopes to make another attempt at colorizing the footage that is effective enough for the footage to be inserted into the film as he originally intended by the time the film's 50th anniversary comes in 2028.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/05/21/grease-anniversary-danny-sandy-finally-get-their-movie-ending-kiss/625512002/|title=Danny and Sandy finally get their movie-ending 'Grease' kiss, 40 years after it was cut|first=Bryan|last=Alexander|work=USA Today|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n===Box office===\n''Grease'' was originally released to North American theaters on June 16, 1978 and was an immediate box office success. In its opening weekend, the film grossed $8,941,717 in 862 theaters in the United States and Canada, ranking at No. 2 (behind ''[[Jaws 2]]'') at the box office for the weekend<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=1978&wknd=24&p=.htm Week June 16-18, 1978]</ref> and with the all-time opening weekend records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/pastrecords.htm |title=Weekend Records Through the Years |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date= |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> Despite losing the weekend, it set a record gross in its first 19 days with $40,272,000.<ref>{{Cite news|  title ='Superman' adds more records to his collection | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] | date = January 3, 1979 | page = 1}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and globally, it became the [[List of highest-grossing musicals|highest-grossing musical ever]] at the time, eclipsing the 13-year-old record held by ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'' with a worldwide gross of $341 million.<ref name=Carr/>\n\nIt was re-released in March 1998 for its 20th anniversary where it grossed a further $28 million in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n\nIt remained the highest-grossing live-action musical until 2012 when it was overtaken by ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (2012 film)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]''<ref name=Forbes/> and the US champion until 2017 when it was surpassed by ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=musical.htm|title=Musical|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=July 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706234750/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=musical.htm|archive-date=July 6, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Grease'' is now the seventh-highest-grossing live-action musical worldwide.<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2019/06/19/aladdin-is-actually-the-second-most-successful-musical-ever/#4cfce8123fb9|title=Aladdin Is Actually The Second-Most Successful Musical Ever|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA further re-issue for its 40th anniversary in 2018 grossed $1 million.<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n\nTo date, ''Grease'' has grossed $189,969,103 domestically and $206.2 million internationally, totaling $396 million worldwide.<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''Grease'' received mostly positive reviews from film critics<ref name=\"metacritic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/grease |title=Grease Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate= August 16, 2010}}</ref> and is considered by many as one of the best films of 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/1978.html |title=Greatest Films of 1978 |website=[[Filmsite.org]] |accessdate= August 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.film.com/features/story/10-best-movies-of-1978/14955431 |title=The 10 Best Movies of 1978 |website=Film.com |date=June 1, 2007 |accessdate= August 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701173433/http://www.film.com/features/story/10-best-movies-of-1978/14955431 |archivedate=July 1, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/year/1978|title=Most Popular Feature Films Released in 1978|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=April 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.films101.com/y1978r.htm |title=The Best Movies of 1978 by Rank |work=Films101 |date= |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} [[Vincent Canby]], on its initial release in June 1978, called the film \"terrific fun\", describing it as a \"contemporary fantasy about a 1950s teen-age musical&mdash;a larger, funnier, wittier and more imaginative-than-Hollywood movie with a life that is all its own\"; Canby pointed out that the film was \"somewhat in the manner of ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'', which recalls the science-fiction films of the '50s in a manner more elegant and more benign than anything that was ever made then, ''Grease'' is a multimillion-dollar evocation of the B-picture quickies that [[Sam Katzman]] used to turn out in the '50s (''[[Don't Knock the Rock]]'', 1956) and that [[American International Pictures|American International]] carried to the sea in the 1960s (''[[Beach Party]]'', 1963).\"<ref>{{cite news| url= https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D0CE7D61031E632A25755C1A9609C946990D6CF | title= A Slick Version of 'Grease': Fantasy of the 50s | first=Vincent | last=Canby |authorlink=Vincent Canby | date= June 16, 1978 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=December 20, 2010}}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film three stars out of four, calling it \"exciting only when John Travolta is on the screen\" but still recommending it to viewers, adding, \"Four of its musical numbers are genuine showstoppers that should bring applause.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (June 16, 1978). \"Travolta cuts through flaws in suburbanized 'Grease'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 3, p. 1.</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the \"zesty choreography and very excellent new plus revived music\", and thought Travolta and Newton-John \"play together quite well.\"<ref>\"Film Reviews: Grease\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. June 7, 1978. 28.</ref> [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' was negative, writing, \"I didn't see 'Grease' onstage, but on the testimony of this strident, cluttered, uninvolving and unattractive movie, it is the '50s\u2014maybe the last innocent decade allowed to us\u2014played back through a grotesquely distorting '70s consciousness.\"<ref>[[Charles Champlin|Champlin, Charles]] (June 16, 1978). \"'50s as Seen Through 'Grease'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Part IV, p. 30.</ref> Gary Arnold of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' also panned the film, writing, \"Despite the obvious attempts to recall bits from [[Stanley Donen]] musicals or [[Elvis Presley]] musicals or [[Frankie Avalon|Frankie]]-and-[[Annette Funicello|Annette]] musicals, the spirit is closer to the New Tastelessness exemplified by [[Ken Russell]], minus Russell's slick visual style ... I've never seen an uglier large-scale musical.\"<ref>Arnold, Gary (June 17, 1978). \"'Grease': Grin and Grimace\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. B5.</ref> [[David Ansen]] of ''[[Newsweek]]'' wrote, \"Too often, 'Grease' is simply mediocre, full of broad high-school humor, flat dramatic scenes and lethargic pacing. Fortunately, there's nothing flat about John Travolta ... Travolta can't dominate this movie as he did 'Fever,' but when he's on screen you can't watch anyone else.\"<ref>[[David Ansen|Ansen, David]] (June 12, 1978). \"Greasy Kid Stuff\". ''[[Newsweek]]''. 92.</ref>\n\nRetrospective reviews have generally been positive. In a 1998 review, [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, calling it \"an average musical, pleasant and upbeat and plastic.\" He found John Travolta's [[Elvis Presley]]-inspired performance to be the highlight, but felt that ''Grease'' \"sees the material as silly [[Camp (style)|camp]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/grease-1998|title=Grease movie review & film summary (1998) |publisher=RogerEbert.com|date=1998-03-27|accessdate=2020-01-31}}</ref> In 2018, [[Peter Bradshaw]] from ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave it 5 out of 5 stars, saying \"It's still a sugar-rush of a film.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/18/grease-review-john-travolta-olivia-newton-john|title=Grease review - Travolta and Newton-John's summer lovin' still a blast|publisher=The Guardian|date=2018-04-18 |accessdate=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n''Grease'' was voted the best musical ever on [[Channel 4]]'s 100 greatest musicals in <!-- Earliest Internet Archive save was in April 2004. -->2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/film/newsfeatures/microsites/M/musicals/results_5to1.html |title=100 Greatest Musicals: Channel 4 Film |publisher=Channel4.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519084313/http://www.channel4.com/film/newsfeatures/microsites/M/musicals/results_5to1.html|archive-date=May 19, 2009|accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref> The film holds a 75% approval rating on the [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 71 reviews with an average rating of 6.7/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Grease'' is a pleasing, energetic musical with infectiously catchy songs and an ode to young love that never gets old.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/grease/ |title=Grease (1978) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> It holds a score of 70/100 on the review aggregator [[Metacritic]] based on 15 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"metacritic1\"/>\n\nThe film was also ranked number 21 on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s list of the 50 Best High School Movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/50besthsfilms2.html |title=Entertainment Weekly's The 50 Best High School Movies |publisher=[[AMC Networks]] |work=[[Filmsite.org]] |date= |accessdate= July 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Entertainment-Weeklys-Best-School-Movies/lm/R301DE1BM2HTIQ |title=''Entertainment Weekly's'' 50 Best High School Movies (25-1) |publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |accessdate= July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home Entertainment===\n''Grease'' was first released in the US on [[VHS]] by [[Paramount Home Media Distribution|Paramount Home Video]] in 1979, 1982, 1989, 1992 and 1994; the last VHS release was on June 23, 1998 and titled the ''20th Anniversary Edition'' following a theatrical re-release that March.\n\nOn September 24, 2002, it was released on [[DVD]] for the first time. On September 19, 2006, it was re-released on DVD as the ''Rockin' Rydell Edition'', which came with a black Rydell High T-Bird jacket cover, a white Rydell \"R\" letterman's sweater cover or the [[Target Corporation|Target]]-exclusive Pink Ladies cover. It was released on [[Blu-ray]] Disc on May 5, 2009.\n\nOn March 12, 2013, ''Grease'' and ''Grease 2'' were packaged together in a double feature DVD set from [[Warner Home Video]].\n\nIn connection with the film's 40th anniversary, Paramount released Grease on 4K [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]], Blu-ray and DVD on April 24, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/56637/grease4kultrahdbluray.html|title=Grease: 40th Anniversary Edition - 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray Ultra HD Review {{!}} High Def Digest|website=ultrahd.highdefdigest.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{{Awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1978\n|''Grease''\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|John Travolta\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|Olivia Newton-John\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|\"Grease\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|\"You're the One That I Want\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 1979\n|CIC\n| [[Goldene Leinwand|Golden Screen Award]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|Stockard Channing\n| [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award for Favorite Motion Picture Supporting Actress]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|''Grease''\n| [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award for Favorite Musical Motion Picture]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|''Grease''\n| [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award for Favorite Overall Motion Picture]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|\"Hopelessly Devoted to You\"\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2006\n|''Grease''\n| [[11th Satellite Awards#Best Classic DVD|Satellite Award for Best Classic DVD]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008\n|\"You're the One That I Want\"\n| [[TV Land Award|TV Land Award for Movie Dance Sequence You Reenacted in Your Living Room]]\n| {{nom}}\n{{end table}}\n\n===American Film Institute Recognition===\n; [[American Film Institute]] Lists\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]]: No. 97\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]: No. 70 for \"[[Summer Nights (Grease song)|Summer Nights]]\"\n* [[AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals]]: No. 20\n\n==Legacy==\n===Sequel===\nThe sequel, ''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982), stars [[Maxwell Caulfield]] and [[Michelle Pfeiffer]]. Most of the adult characters reprised their roles, though the sequel focused on a younger class of greasers and thus most of the main characters from ''Grease'' did not appear. It was disowned by [[Jim Jacobs]], who co-created the characters. Patricia Birch, the original film's choreographer, directed the sequel. It would be the only film that she would direct.\n\n===Sing-along version===\n{{anchor|Grease Sing-A-Long}} On July 8, 2010, a sing-along version of ''Grease'' was released to select theaters around the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screencrave.com/2010-05-21/wanna-sing-a-long-with-grease-with-lyrics/ |title=Wanna Sing-A-Long with Grease? With Lyrics?!? |publisher=Screencrave.com |date=May 21, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522020741/http://screencrave.com/2010-05-21/wanna-sing-a-long-with-grease-with-lyrics/ |archivedate=May 22, 2010 |df= }}</ref> A trailer was released in May 2010, with cigarettes digitally removed from certain scenes, implying heavy editing; however, Paramount confirmed these changes were done only for the film's advertising,<ref>[http://www.ocala.com/article/20100604/ARTICLES/6041009 \"'Grease Sing-A-Long' trailer cuts cigarette from iconic scene: Smoking was not removed from the film itself], Ocala.com, June 4, 2010.</ref> and the [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|rating]] for the film itself changed from its original PG to that of PG-13 for \"sexual content including references, teen smoking and drinking, and language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/films.php?id=66254 |title=Grease Sing-A-Long\u2014Trailers, Videos, and Reviews ComingSoon.net Movie Database |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=July 8, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref> The film was shown for two weekends only; additional cities lobbied by fans from the Paramount official website started a week later and screened for one weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greasemovie.com |title=Grease Sing-A-Long (2010) &#124; Trailer & Official Movie Site |website=Greasemovie.com |date= |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Prequel===\nIn March 2019, it was announced that a prequel, titled ''Summer Loving'', is currently in development from [[Paramount Players]] film studio. The project will be a joint-production collaboration with [[Temple Hill Entertainment|Temple Hill Productions]] and Picturestart Productions. [[John August]] signed on to serve as screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grease-prequel-summer-loving-works-1200358|title='Grease' Prequel 'Summer Loving' in the Works With John August Writing (Exclusive)|first=Borys|last=Kit|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 9, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Main|Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture}}\n\nThe [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture|soundtrack album]] ended 1978 as the [[List of best-selling albums by year in the United States#1970s|second-best-selling album of the year in the United States]], exceeded only by [[Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|another soundtrack album]], from the film ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'', which also starred Travolta.<ref name=\"bboard78\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=The+Billboard+200&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1978 |title=Year End Charts\u2014Year-end Albums\u2014The Billboard 200 |publisher= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.com]] |accessdate=2010-12-20 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071211064005/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=The+Billboard+200&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1978 |archivedate = 2007-12-11}}</ref> The song \"Hopelessly Devoted to You\" was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song#1970s|Academy Award for Best Music \u2013 Original Song]]. The song \"You're the One That I Want\" was released as a single prior to the film's release and became an immediate chart-topper, despite not being in the stage show or having been seen in the film at that time.<ref>VH1's \"Behind the Music: Grease\"</ref> Additionally, the dance number to \"You're the One That I Want\" was nominated for TV Land's award for \"Movie Dance Sequence You Reenacted in Your Living Room\" in 2008.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631/awards</ref> In the United Kingdom, the two Travolta/Newton-John duets, \"You're the One That I Want\" and \"Summer Nights\", were both number one hits and {{as of|2011|lc=y}} are still among the 20 best-selling singles of all time (at Nos. 6 and 19, respectively).<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tknyg BBC Radio {{ndash}} Top selling singles of all time]</ref> The film's title song was also a number-one hit single for [[Frankie Valli]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=frankie valli|chart=all}}|title=''Billboard'' Hot 100|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe song \"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee\" refers to [[Sal Mineo]] in the original stage version. Mineo was stabbed to death a year before filming, so the line was changed to refer to [[Elvis Presley]] instead. The references to [[Troy Donohue]], [[Doris Day]], [[Rock Hudson]] and [[Annette Funicello]] are from the original stage version. Coincidentally, this scene as well as the scene before and the scene after it were filmed on August 16, 1977, the date of Elvis Presley's death.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/tales_of_ancient_grease_c9DsjHTfLgATW1VPqpizZP|title=Tales of Ancient 'Grease'|work=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=April 27, 2012|first=Larry|last=Getlen|date=2010-07-04}}</ref>\n\nSome of the songs were not present in the film; songs that appear in the film but not in the soundtrack are \"[[La Bamba (song)|La Bamba]]\" by Ritchie Valens, \"Whole Lotta Shaking Going On\" by [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], \"Alma Mater\", \"Alma Mater Parody\", and \"Rydell Fight Song\". \"Alone at a Drive-in Movie (instrumental)\", \"Mooning\", and \"Freddy My Love\" are not present in the film, although all three are listed in the end credits in-addition to being on the soundtrack. (Both \"Mooning\" and \"Rock'n'Roll Party Queen\", the latter of which was played in the film as background music, were written in the musical for a character named Roger that was written out of the film, replaced by the non-singing Putzie. In general, all of the songs in the musical that were performed by characters other than Danny, Rizzo, Sandy, Johnny Casino, or the Teen Angel were either taken out of the film or given to other characters, including Marty Maraschino's number \"Freddy My Love\", Kenickie's \"Greased Lightnin'\", and Doody's \"Those Magic Changes\".) Two songs from the musical, \"Shakin' at the High School Hop\" and \"All Choked Up\", were left off both the film and the soundtrack.\n\nThe songs appear in the film in the following order:\n{{div col}}\n# \"[[Love is a Many-Splendored Thing (song)|Love is a Many-Splendored Thing]]\"\n# \"[[Grease (song)|Grease]]\"\n# \"Alma Mater\"\n# \"[[Summer Nights (Grease song)|Summer Nights]]\" \u2013 Danny, Sandy, Pink Ladies and T-Birds\n# \"Rydell Fight Song\" \u2013 Rydell Marching Band\n# \"[[Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee]]\" \u2013 Rizzo and Pink Ladies\n# \"[[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\" \u2013 Sandy\n# \"[[Greased Lightnin' (song)|Greased Lightnin']]\" \u2013 Danny and T-Birds\n# \"[[La Bamba (song)|La Bamba]]\"\n# \"It's Raining on Prom Night\"\n# \"[[Whole Lotta Shakin' Goin' On]]\"\n# \"[[Beauty School Dropout]]\" \u2013 Teen Angel and Female Angels\n# \"[[Rock n' Roll Party Queen]]\"\n# \"[[Rock and Roll Is Here to Stay]]\"\n# \"[[Those Magic Changes]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers; Danny sings along onscreen\n# \"[[Tears on My Pillow]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Hound Dog (song)|Hound Dog]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Born to Hand Jive]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Blue Moon (1934 song)|Blue Moon]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Sandy (Grease song)|Sandy]]\" \u2013 Danny\n# \"[[There Are Worse Things I Could Do]]\" \u2013 Rizzo\n# \"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee (Reprise)\" \u2013 Sandy\n# \"Alma Mater Parody\" (instrumental)\n# \"[[You're the One That I Want]]\" \u2013 Danny, Sandy, Pink Ladies, and T-Birds\n# \"We Go Together\" <!-- There is no article for this song. Wiki-linking this phrase will lead to the album by George Jones and Tammy Wynette. Putting (song) as a dab will lead to the present article.) -->\u2013 Cast\n# \"Grease (Reprise)\"\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Television==\n{{main|Somos t\u00fa y yo|Grease: Live}}\nOn August 17, 2009, a [[Somos t\u00fa y yo|television series]] inspired by the film premiered in Venezuela. The series was produced and directed by Vladimir Perez. The show explores and expands on the characters and story from the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Venevisi\u00f3n estrena 'Somos t\u00fa y yo, un nuevo d\u00eda, inspirada en Grease'|url=http://www.todotvnews.com/news/Venevision-estrena-serie-Somos-T-y-Yo-Un-Nuevo-Da.html|access-date=July 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622190035/http://www.todotvnews.com/news/Venevision-estrena-serie-Somos-T-y-Yo-Un-Nuevo-Da.html|archive-date=June 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=De regreso a los a\u00f1os 50 con el musical 'Grease'|url=http://www.eluniverso.com/vida-estilo/2015/09/25/nota/5145359/regreso-anos-50-musical-grease}}</ref>\n\nOn January 31, 2016, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] aired a [[Grease: Live|live television-adapted special]] of the musical, using components from both the 1978 film and the original Broadway show. Starring [[Julianne Hough]], [[Aaron Tveit]], and [[Vanessa Hudgens]], the adaptation received positive reviews, especially towards Hudgens, whose father passed away hours before the live airing, and ten [[Emmy]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Grease: Live |url=https://www.fox.com/grease-live/ |website=Fox}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.greasemovie.com/ Official Sing-A-Long Site]\n* {{IMDb title|0077631|Grease}}\n* {{tcmdb title|4603|Grease}}\n* {{AllMovie title|20546|Grease}}\n* {{mojo title|grease|Grease}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|grease|Grease}}\n* {{metacritic film|grease|Grease}}\n* {{YouTube|wzWmxjYNfz4|Original 1978 Release Trailer}}\n* [https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/grease Paramount Movies - Grease]\n{{Grease}}\n{{Randal Kleiser}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grease}}\n[[Category:1970s dance films]]\n[[Category:1970s high school films]]\n[[Category:1970s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:1970s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:1978 films]]\n[[Category:American dance films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American rock musicals]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen musical films]]\n[[Category:American teen romance films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on musicals]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Randal Kleiser]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1958]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1959]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Allan Carr]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Bronte Woodard]]\n[[Category:Flying cars in fiction]]\n[[Category:Grease (musical)]]\n[[Category:Paramount Pictures films]]\n[[Category:1978 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1978 romantic musical film directed by Randal Kleiser}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Grease\n| image          = Grease ver2.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Randal Kleiser]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Robert Stigwood]]\n* [[Allan Carr]]\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]]''|[[Jim Jacobs]]<br/>[[Warren Casey]]}}\n| screenplay     = [[Bronte Woodard]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[John Travolta]]\n* [[Olivia Newton-John]]\n* [[Stockard Channing]]\n* [[Eve Arden]]\n* [[Frankie Avalon]]\n* [[Joan Blondell]]\n* [[Edd Byrnes]]\n* [[Sid Caesar]]\n* [[Alice Ghostley]]\n* [[Dody Goodman]]\n* [[Sha Na Na]]}}\n| music          = [[Michael Gibson (musician)|Michael Gibson]]\n| cinematography = [[Bill Butler (cinematographer)|Bill Butler]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* John F. Burnett\n* Robert Pergament\n}}\n| studio         = {{plainlist|\n* [[Paramount Pictures]]\n* [[Allan Carr|Allan Carr Productions]]\n* [[RSO Records|Robert Stigwood Organization]]\n* [[Polydor Records]]\n}}\n| distributor    = Paramount Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1978|6|16}}\n| runtime        = 110 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $6 million<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n| gross          = $396 million<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\">{{mojo title|grease|Grease}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Grease''''' is a 1978 American [[Musical film|musical]] [[romantic comedy]] film based on the [[Grease (musical)|1971 musical of the same name]] by [[Jim Jacobs]] and [[Warren Casey]]. Written by [[Bronte Woodard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/this-day-in-history/grease-movie-soundtrack-earns-its-second-1-hit |title=Grease movie soundtrack earns its second #1 hit |publisher=History.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref> and directed by [[Randal Kleiser]] in his theatrical feature film debut, the film depicts the lives of [[Greaser (subculture)|greaser]] Danny Zuko and Australian transfer student Sandy Olsson who develop an attraction for each other. The film stars [[John Travolta]] as Danny, [[Olivia Newton-John]] as Sandy, and [[Stockard Channing]] as Betty Rizzo, the leader of the Pink Ladies.\n\nReleased on June 16, 1978, ''Grease'' was successful both critically and commercially becoming the [[List of highest-grossing musicals#Timeline of highest-grossing musical films|highest-grossing musical film ever]] at the time.<ref name=Carr>{{cite book |last=Hofler |first=Robert |title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock 'N' Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr |publisher=ReadHowYouWant.com |year=2010 |isbn=9781459600072 |page=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iqRezpQzUcAC&pg=PA145 145] |quote=Despite the fact that Grease was well on its way to becoming the highest-grossing movie musical in the world, and eventually grossed over $341&nbsp;million...}}</ref> Its [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture|soundtrack album]] ended 1978 as the [[List of best-selling albums by year in the United States#1970s|second-best-selling album of the year in the United States]], behind the [[Saturday Night Fever: The Original Movie Sound Track|soundtrack]] of the 1977 blockbuster ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'' (which also starred Travolta)<ref name=\"bboard78\"/> and earned the film its lone [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nomination for \"[[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\" (which lost the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] to [[Donna Summer]]'s \"[[Last Dance (Donna Summer song)|Last Dance]]\" from ''[[Thank God It's Friday (film)|Thank God It's Friday]]'' at the [[51st Academy Awards]]).\n\nA sequel, ''[[Grease 2]]'', was released in 1982, starring [[Maxwell Caulfield]] and [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] as a newer class of greasers. Few of the original cast members reprised their roles. As of 2019, an HBO Max series based on the film is in production.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.inquirer.com/entertainment/movies/grease-rydell-high-hbo-max-streaming-summer-loving-radnor-high-school-20191017.html}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n<!-- PER WP:FILMPLOT, PLOT SUMMARIES SHOULD BE 400-700 WORDS. -->\nIn the summer of 1958, local boy Danny Zuko and vacationing Sandy Olsson meet at the beach and fall in love. When the summer comes to an end, Sandy\u2014who is going back to Australia\u2014frets that they may never meet again, but Danny tells her that their love is \"only beginning\". The film moves to the start of the seniors' term at Rydell High School. Danny is a member and leader of the T-Birds [[greaser (subculture)|greaser]] gang, consisting of his best friend Kenickie, Doody, Sonny, and Putzie. The Pink Ladies, a clique of greaser girls, also arrive, consisting of leader Rizzo, Frenchy, Marty, and Jan.\n\nAfter her parents decide not to return to Australia, Sandy enrolls at Rydell and is befriended by Frenchy, who considers dropping out of school to become a beautician. Unaware of each other's presence at Rydell, Danny and Sandy tell their respective groups the accounts of events during the pair's brief romance, without initially mentioning the other's name (\"Summer Nights\"). Sandy's version emphasizes the romance of the relationship, while Danny's version is more sexual.\n\nWhen Sandy finally says Danny's name, Rizzo arranges a surprise reunion for the two, but Danny is forced to maintain his bad-boy attitude in front of his pals, upsetting Sandy, who storms off and begins dating Tom, a [[jock (subculture)|jock]]. Kenickie unveils the used car, Greased Lightnin', that he plans on restoring and racing (\"Greased Lightnin'\"). Frenchy invites the girls to a pajama party, but Sandy falls ill from the sight of blood after getting her ears pierced by Frenchy, Rizzo starts to make fun of Sandy (\"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee\"). While Sandy is outside, she soon starts to think of Danny, and how much she loves him even though he hurt her (\"Hopelessly Devoted to You\"). Rizzo departs to have sex with Kenickie, during which his condom breaks. The two are disturbed by Leo, leader of the T-Birds' rival gang, the Scorpions, and his girlfriend Cha-Cha.\n\nIn an attempt to impress Sandy, Danny turns to Coach Calhoun to get into sports, eventually becoming a runner. He reunites with Sandy and they attempt to go on a date, but their friends crash it. Kenickie and a distressed Rizzo argue and split up. Left alone, Frenchy is visited by a [[guardian angel]] who advises her to return to school after a mishap in beauty class leaves her with candy-pink hair (\"Beauty School Dropout\").\n\nThe school dance arrives, broadcast live on television and hosted by DJ Vince Fontaine, who flirts with Marty. Rizzo and Kenickie attempt to spite one another by bringing Leo and Cha-Cha as their dates. Danny and Sandy arrive together and dance well during the chaotic [[hand jive]] contest (\"Born to Hand Jive\"); just before the end of the contest Sonny pulls Sandy off the dance floor, and Cha-Cha cuts in to win the contest with Danny, causing Sandy to leave the event broken-hearted.\n\nDanny tries to make it up to Sandy by taking her to a drive-in theater (\"Alone at the Drive-in Movies\") but forces himself on her, causing Sandy to leave (\"Sandy\"). Meanwhile Rizzo fears she is pregnant after missing a period and confides in Marty, but Marty tells Sonny and he inadvertently spreads the rumor to Kenickie, the apparent father, though Rizzo denies this to him. At school, Rizzo is getting laughed at by other girls, and she soon realizes that she isn't as tough as she seems (\"There Are Worse Things I Could Do\").\n\nOn race day, Kenickie suffers a concussion when hit by his own car door, so Danny takes the wheel. He and Leo race until Leo crashes and leaves humiliated, with Danny as the victor. Sandy watches from afar, concluding she still loves Danny, and decides to change her attitude and look to impress him; she then asks Frenchy for help to achieve this goal (\"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee (Reprise)\").\n\nOn the last day of school, Principal McGee and her assistant Blanche sob about the departing class. Rizzo discovers she is not pregnant and reunites with Kenickie. Danny has lettered in track but is shocked when Sandy arrives dressed as a female T-Bird. In song (\"You're the One That I Want\"), they confess their mutual love and reconcile. The class celebrates their graduation at the fair on school grounds (\"We Go Together\"). Sandy and Danny depart in Greased Lightnin', which takes flight (\"Grease\").\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Principal cast===\n* [[John Travolta]] as Danny Zuko, who lives a double life as leader of the greaser gang the T-Birds and as Sandy's boyfriend\n* [[Olivia Newton-John]] as Sandy Olsson, Danny's girlfriend and an Australian [[immigrant]] and [[ing\u00e9nue]], who transforms from square to greaser\n* [[Stockard Channing]] as Betty Rizzo, Kenickie's girlfriend and the cynical leader of the Pink Ladies clique\n* [[Jeff Conaway]] as Kenickie Murdoch, Danny's best friend, Rizzo's boyfriend and the owner of Greased Lightnin'\n* [[Barry Pearl]] as Doody, a member of the T-Birds; he pairs with Frenchy at the school dance\n* [[Michael Tucci]] as Sonny LaTieri, a trouble-making wannabe womanizer and T-Bird who courts Marty with little success over the course of the film\n* [[Kelly Ward]] as Putzie, a member of the T-Birds whose relationship with Jan builds over the course of the film\n* [[Didi Conn]] as Frenchy, Sandy's closest friend in the Pink Ladies and an aspiring beautician\n* [[Jamie Donnelly]] as Jan, a quirky member of the Pink Ladies with a liking for [[Ipana]] toothpaste\n* [[Dinah Manoff]] as Marty Maraschino, a member of the Pink Ladies whose attractiveness regularly draws the attention of men, including Sonny and Vince Fontaine\n\n===Secondary cast===\n* [[Eve Arden]] as Principal McGee, who shows discomfort at the goings-on at Rydell High.\n* [[Dody Goodman]] as Secretary Blanche Hodel, who enjoys even the wilder antics at the school.\n* [[Sid Caesar]] as Coach Vince Calhoun, the tough-talking gym teacher and coach of all the school's perennially losing sports teams\n* [[Eddie Deezen]] as Eugene Felsnick, the class nerd\n* [[Susan Buckner]] as Patty Simcox, the head cheerleader and a rival for Danny's affections\n* [[Lorenzo Lamas]] as Tom Chisum, a popular jock who competes for Sandy's affections\n* [[Dennis Cleveland Stewart|Dennis C. Stewart]] as Leo \"Craterface\" Balmudo, leader of the Scorpions, a rival greaser gang\n* [[Annette Charles]] as Charlene \"Cha-Cha\" Di Gregorio, Leo's girlfriend\n* [[Joan Blondell]] as Vi, a waitress at the Frosty Palace\n* [[Ellen Travolta]] as Waitress\n* [[Frankie Avalon]] as Teen Angel\n* [[Edd Byrnes]] as Vince Fontaine, on-air personality at KZAZ radio and television\n* [[Sha-Na-Na]] as Johnny Casino and the Gamblers, a rock and roll band\n* [[Alice Ghostley]] as Mrs. Murdock, a rogue auto shop teacher who helps build Greased Lightnin' for the T-Birds\n* [[Darrell Zwerling]] as Mr. Lynch\n* Dick Patterson as Mr. Rudie\n* [[Fannie Flagg]] as Nurse Wilkins\n\n==Production==\n\n===Casting===\n[[John Travolta]] had previously worked with producer [[Robert Stigwood]] on ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'', had a nascent singing career at the time (including the top-10 hit \"[[Let Her In]]\" in 1976), and had previously appeared as Doody in a touring production of the stage version of ''Grease''. He made a number of casting recommendations that Stigwood ultimately accepted, including suggesting [[Randal Kleiser]] (who had never directed a theatrical feature before this but had directed Travolta in the 1976 telefilm ''[[The Boy in the Plastic Bubble]]'') as director, and [[Olivia Newton-John]], then known almost exclusively as a multiple Grammy winning pop and country singer, as Sandy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Travolta|first=John|title=Inside the Actor's Studio}}</ref> Newton-John had done little acting before this film, with only two film credits (1965's ''[[Funny Things Happen Down Under]]'' and the unreleased 1970 film ''[[Toomorrow (film)|Toomorrow]]'', which predated her singing breakthrough) to her name up to that time. Before accepting the role, Newton-John requested a [[screen test]] for ''Grease'' to avoid another career setback.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20071391,00.html |title=Ohh Sandy! \u2013 Olivia Newton-John |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |first=Robert |last=Windeler |date=July 31, 1978 |accessdate=November 10, 2008}}</ref> The screen test was done with the drive-in movie scene. Newton-John, who is native to England and lived most of her life in Australia, was unable to perform with a convincing American accent, and thus her character was rewritten to be Australian. Before Newton-John was hired, [[Allan Carr]] was considering numerous names such as [[Ann-Margret]], [[Susan Dey]] and [[Marie Osmond]] for the lead role; Newton-John agreed to a reduced asking price in exchange for star billing.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> In a case of life imitating art, Newton-John's own musical career would undergo a transformation similar to that of the Sandy Olsson character; her next album after ''Grease'', the provocatively titled ''[[Totally Hot]]'', featured a much more sexual and pop-oriented approach, with Newton-John appearing on the album cover in similar all-leather attire and teased hair.<ref name=\"google3\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Mo7xm-X1r4C&pg=PA334#PPA335,M1 |title=All music guide to country: the ... |publisher= Google Books |date= |accessdate=August 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[Jeff Conaway]], like Travolta, had previously appeared in the stage version of ''Grease''; he had played Danny Zuko during the show's run on Broadway.<ref name=newsdayobit>{{cite news|authorlink=Frank Lovece |last=Lovece |first=Frank |url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/obituaries/grease-taxi-star-jeff-conaway-dies-1.2907909 |title='Grease,' 'Taxi' Star Jeff Conaway Dies |work=[[Newsday]] |date=May 27, 2011 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z4Hujzwq?url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/obituaries/grease-taxi-star-jeff-conaway-dies-1.2907909?p= |archivedate=May 30, 2011 |df= }} (Subscription required.) . Print edition, May 28, 2011, p. A32</ref> [[Jamie Donnelly]] reprised her role as Jan from the Broadway show, the only cast member to do so; as her hair had begun to gray by this point, she had to dye her hair to resemble her stage character.<ref name=people98>Gliatto, Tom; and O'Neill Anne-Marie. [http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20124959,00.html \"Grease Is the Word: Twenty Years Later, the Stars Are Still True to Their School\"], ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', April 13, 1998. Accessed September 13, 2011.</ref> [[Kelly Ward]] had previously appeared as a similar sarcastic supporting character in ''The Boy in the Plastic Bubble'' with Travolta under Kleiser; he was cast as Putzie, a mostly new character.\n\n[[Lorenzo Lamas]] was a last-minute replacement for [[Steven Ford]], who developed [[stage fright]] shortly before filming and backed out. His role contained no spoken dialogue and required Lamas to dye his hair blond to avoid looking like one of the T-Birds.<ref name=people98/>\n\nAdult film star [[Harry Reems]] was originally signed to play Coach Calhoun; however, executives at Paramount nixed the idea, concerned that his reputation as a porn star would hinder box office returns in the [[Southern United States]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/nymetro/movies/features/10988|title=The Afterlife of a Porn Star|publisher=New York Media, LLC|work=New York Magazine|date=May 21, 2005|accessdate=May 8, 2011|author=Itzkoff, Dave}}</ref> and producers cast [[Sid Caesar]] instead.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hofler|first=Robert |title=Party Animals: A Hollywood Tale of Sex, Drugs, and Rock 'n' Roll Starring the Fabulous Allan Carr|year=2010|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=0-306-81655-5|page=66}}</ref> Caesar was one of several veterans of 1950s television ([[Eve Arden]], [[Frankie Avalon]], [[Joan Blondell]], [[Edd Byrnes]], [[Alice Ghostley]], [[Dody Goodman]]) to be cast in supporting roles. Coincidentally, Frankie Avalon and Randal Kleiser had both appeared in 1966's ''[[Fireball 500]]'', the latter as an extra.\n\n===Filming locations===\n[[File:Grease car race LA river.jpg|thumb|The car race in the film took place at the Los Angeles River.]]\nThe opening beach scene was shot at Malibu's [[Leo Carrillo State Park|Leo Carrillo State Beach]], making explicit reference to ''[[From Here to Eternity]]''. The exterior Rydell scenes, including the basketball, baseball and track segments, were shot at [[Venice High School (Los Angeles)|Venice High School]] in [[Venice, Los Angeles|Venice, California]], while the Rydell interiors, including the high school dance, were filmed at [[Huntington Park High School]]. The sleepover was shot at a private house in [[East Hollywood, Los Angeles|East Hollywood]]. The Paramount Pictures studio lot was the location of the scenes that involve Frosty Palace and the musical numbers \"Greased Lightning\" and \"Beauty School Dropout\". The drive-in movie scenes were shot at the Burbank Pickwick Drive-In (it was closed and torn down in 1989 and a shopping center took its place). The race was filmed at the [[Los Angeles River]], between the First and Seventh Street Bridges, where many other films have been shot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movie-locations.com/movies/g/grease.html |title=Film locations for Grease (1978) |publisher=Movie-locations.com |date= |accessdate=2012-10-30}}</ref> The final scene where the carnival took place used [[John Marshall High School (Los Angeles)|John Marshall High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seeing-stars.com/locations/grease.shtml |title=Grease Filming Locations {{ndash}} part 1 |publisher=Seeing-stars.com |date= |accessdate=2011-10-09}}</ref> Furthermore, owing to budget cuts, a short scene was filmed at [[Hazard Park]] in Los Angeles.\n\n===Post-production===\nScenes inside the Frosty Palace contain obvious blurring of various [[Coca-Cola]] signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://scenesteal.com/html/grease |title=Grease |publisher=Scenesteal.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110309185814/http://scenesteal.com/html/grease |archivedate=2011-03-09 |df= }}</ref> Prior to the film's release, producer Allan Carr had made a product-placement deal with Coca-Cola's main competitor [[Pepsi]] (for example, a Pepsi logo can be seen in the animated opening sequence). When Carr saw the footage of the scene with Coca-Cola products and signage, he ordered director Randal Kleiser to either reshoot the scene with Pepsi products or remove the Coca-Cola logos from the scene. As reshoots were deemed too expensive and time-consuming, optical mattes were used to cover up or blur out the Coca-Cola references. The 'blurring' covered up trademarked menu signage and a large wall poster, but a red cooler with the logo could not be sufficiently altered so was left unchanged. According to Kleiser, \"We just had to hope that Pepsi wouldn't complain. They didn't.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.stupidquestion.net/sq102600.html |title=Stupid Question |publisher=Archives.stupidquestion.net |date=2000-10-26 |accessdate=2010-08-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130071914/http://archives.stupidquestion.net/sq102600.html |archivedate=2007-11-30 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dvdtalk.com/dvdsavant/s70grease.html |title=DVD Savant: GREASE and the Curse of Product Placement |publisher= Dvdtalk.com |date=1998-08-18 |accessdate= 2010-08-16}}</ref>\n\nDue to an editing error, a closing scene in which Danny and Sandy kiss was removed from the finished print and lost before its theatrical release. The scene was preserved only in black-and-white; Kleiser attempted to have the existing footage [[Film colorization|colorized]] and restored to the film for the film's re-release in 1998 but was dissatisfied with the results. The scene is included as an extra on the 40th anniversary home video release, and Kleiser hopes to make another attempt at colorizing the footage that is effective enough for the footage to be inserted into the film as he originally intended by the time the film's 50th anniversary comes in 2028.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2018/05/21/grease-anniversary-danny-sandy-finally-get-their-movie-ending-kiss/625512002/|title=Danny and Sandy finally get their movie-ending 'Grease' kiss, 40 years after it was cut|first=Bryan|last=Alexander|work=USA Today|date=May 21, 2018|accessdate=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release and reception==\n===Box office===\n''Grease'' was originally released to North American theaters on June 16, 1978 and was an immediate box office success. In its opening weekend, the film grossed $8,941,717 in 862 theaters in the United States and Canada, ranking at No. 2 (behind ''[[Jaws 2]]'') at the box office for the weekend<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=1978&wknd=24&p=.htm Week June 16-18, 1978]</ref> and with the all-time opening weekend records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/pastrecords.htm |title=Weekend Records Through the Years |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date= |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> Despite losing the weekend, it set a record gross in its first 19 days with $40,272,000.<ref>{{Cite news|  title ='Superman' adds more records to his collection | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Daily Variety]] | date = January 3, 1979 | page = 1}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and globally, it became the [[List of highest-grossing musicals|highest-grossing musical ever]] at the time, eclipsing the 13-year-old record held by ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'' with a worldwide gross of $341 million.<ref name=Carr/>\n\nIt was re-released in March 1998 for its 20th anniversary where it grossed a further $28 million in the United States and Canada.<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n\nIt remained the highest-grossing live-action musical until 2012 when it was overtaken by ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (2012 film)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]''<ref name=Forbes/> and the US champion until 2017 when it was surpassed by ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=musical.htm|title=Musical|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=July 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706234750/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/genres/chart/?id=musical.htm|archive-date=July 6, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> ''Grease'' is now the seventh-highest-grossing live-action musical worldwide.<ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/travisbean/2019/06/19/aladdin-is-actually-the-second-most-successful-musical-ever/#4cfce8123fb9|title=Aladdin Is Actually The Second-Most Successful Musical Ever|publisher=Forbes|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA further re-issue for its 40th anniversary in 2018 grossed $1 million.<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n\nTo date, ''Grease'' has grossed $189,969,103 domestically and $206.2 million internationally, totaling $396 million worldwide.<ref name=\"boxoffmojo\"/>\n\n===Critical reception===\n''Grease'' received mostly positive reviews from film critics<ref name=\"metacritic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/grease |title=Grease Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate= August 16, 2010}}</ref> and is considered by many as one of the best films of 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/1978.html |title=Greatest Films of 1978 |website=[[Filmsite.org]] |accessdate= August 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.film.com/features/story/10-best-movies-of-1978/14955431 |title=The 10 Best Movies of 1978 |website=Film.com |date=June 1, 2007 |accessdate= August 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701173433/http://www.film.com/features/story/10-best-movies-of-1978/14955431 |archivedate=July 1, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/year/1978|title=Most Popular Feature Films Released in 1978|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=April 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.films101.com/y1978r.htm |title=The Best Movies of 1978 by Rank |work=Films101 |date= |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} [[Vincent Canby]], on its initial release in June 1978, called the film \"terrific fun\", describing it as a \"contemporary fantasy about a 1950s teen-age musical&mdash;a larger, funnier, wittier and more imaginative-than-Hollywood movie with a life that is all its own\"; Canby pointed out that the film was \"somewhat in the manner of ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'', which recalls the science-fiction films of the '50s in a manner more elegant and more benign than anything that was ever made then, ''Grease'' is a multimillion-dollar evocation of the B-picture quickies that [[Sam Katzman]] used to turn out in the '50s (''[[Don't Knock the Rock]]'', 1956) and that [[American International Pictures|American International]] carried to the sea in the 1960s (''[[Beach Party]]'', 1963).\"<ref>{{cite news| url= https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D0CE7D61031E632A25755C1A9609C946990D6CF | title= A Slick Version of 'Grease': Fantasy of the 50s | first=Vincent | last=Canby |authorlink=Vincent Canby | date= June 16, 1978 | work=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=December 20, 2010}}</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] gave the film three stars out of four, calling it \"exciting only when John Travolta is on the screen\" but still recommending it to viewers, adding, \"Four of its musical numbers are genuine showstoppers that should bring applause.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (June 16, 1978). \"Travolta cuts through flaws in suburbanized 'Grease'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 3, p. 1.</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the \"zesty choreography and very excellent new plus revived music\", and thought Travolta and Newton-John \"play together quite well.\"<ref>\"Film Reviews: Grease\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. June 7, 1978. 28.</ref> [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' was negative, writing, \"I didn't see 'Grease' onstage, but on the testimony of this strident, cluttered, uninvolving and unattractive movie, it is the '50s\u2014maybe the last innocent decade allowed to us\u2014played back through a grotesquely distorting '70s consciousness.\"<ref>[[Charles Champlin|Champlin, Charles]] (June 16, 1978). \"'50s as Seen Through 'Grease'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Part IV, p. 30.</ref> Gary Arnold of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' also panned the film, writing, \"Despite the obvious attempts to recall bits from [[Stanley Donen]] musicals or [[Elvis Presley]] musicals or [[Frankie Avalon|Frankie]]-and-[[Annette Funicello|Annette]] musicals, the spirit is closer to the New Tastelessness exemplified by [[Ken Russell]], minus Russell's slick visual style ... I've never seen an uglier large-scale musical.\"<ref>Arnold, Gary (June 17, 1978). \"'Grease': Grin and Grimace\". ''[[The Washington Post]]''. B5.</ref> [[David Ansen]] of ''[[Newsweek]]'' wrote, \"Too often, 'Grease' is simply mediocre, full of broad high-school humor, flat dramatic scenes and lethargic pacing. Fortunately, there's nothing flat about John Travolta ... Travolta can't dominate this movie as he did 'Fever,' but when he's on screen you can't watch anyone else.\"<ref>[[David Ansen|Ansen, David]] (June 12, 1978). \"Greasy Kid Stuff\". ''[[Newsweek]]''. 92.</ref>\n\nRetrospective reviews have generally been positive. In a 1998 review, [[Roger Ebert]] gave the film 3 out of 4 stars, calling it \"an average musical, pleasant and upbeat and plastic.\" He found John Travolta's [[Elvis Presley]]-inspired performance to be the highlight, but felt that ''Grease'' \"sees the material as silly [[Camp (style)|camp]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/grease-1998|title=Grease movie review & film summary (1998) |publisher=RogerEbert.com|date=1998-03-27|accessdate=2020-01-31}}</ref> In 2018, [[Peter Bradshaw]] from ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave it 5 out of 5 stars, saying \"It's still a sugar-rush of a film.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/apr/18/grease-review-john-travolta-olivia-newton-john|title=Grease review - Travolta and Newton-John's summer lovin' still a blast|publisher=The Guardian|date=2018-04-18 |accessdate=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n''Grease'' was voted the best musical ever on [[Channel 4]]'s 100 greatest musicals in <!-- Earliest Internet Archive save was in April 2004. -->2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/film/newsfeatures/microsites/M/musicals/results_5to1.html |title=100 Greatest Musicals: Channel 4 Film |publisher=Channel4.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519084313/http://www.channel4.com/film/newsfeatures/microsites/M/musicals/results_5to1.html|archive-date=May 19, 2009|accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref> The film holds a 75% approval rating on the [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], based on 71 reviews with an average rating of 6.7/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Grease'' is a pleasing, energetic musical with infectiously catchy songs and an ode to young love that never gets old.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/grease/ |title=Grease (1978) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref> It holds a score of 70/100 on the review aggregator [[Metacritic]] based on 15 reviews, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=\"metacritic1\"/>\n\nThe film was also ranked number 21 on ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'}}s list of the 50 Best High School Movies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsite.org/50besthsfilms2.html |title=Entertainment Weekly's The 50 Best High School Movies |publisher=[[AMC Networks]] |work=[[Filmsite.org]] |date= |accessdate= July 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Entertainment-Weeklys-Best-School-Movies/lm/R301DE1BM2HTIQ |title=''Entertainment Weekly's'' 50 Best High School Movies (25-1) |publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] |accessdate= July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Home Entertainment===\n''Grease'' was first released in the US on [[VHS]] by [[Paramount Home Media Distribution|Paramount Home Video]] in 1979, 1982, 1989, 1992 and 1994; the last VHS release was on June 23, 1998 and titled the ''20th Anniversary Edition'' following a theatrical re-release that March.\n\nOn September 24, 2002, it was released on [[DVD]] for the first time. On September 19, 2006, it was re-released on DVD as the ''Rockin' Rydell Edition'', which came with a black Rydell High T-Bird jacket cover, a white Rydell \"R\" letterman's sweater cover or the [[Target Corporation|Target]]-exclusive Pink Ladies cover. It was released on [[Blu-ray]] Disc on May 5, 2009.\n\nOn March 12, 2013, ''Grease'' and ''Grease 2'' were packaged together in a double feature DVD set from [[Warner Home Video]].\n\nIn connection with the film's 40th anniversary, Paramount released Grease on 4K [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]], Blu-ray and DVD on April 24, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultrahd.highdefdigest.com/56637/grease4kultrahdbluray.html|title=Grease: 40th Anniversary Edition - 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray Ultra HD Review {{!}} High Def Digest|website=ultrahd.highdefdigest.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-04}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{{Awards table}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"|1978\n|''Grease''\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|John Travolta\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|Olivia Newton-John\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|\"Grease\"\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|\"You're the One That I Want\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 1979\n|CIC\n| [[Goldene Leinwand|Golden Screen Award]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|Stockard Channing\n| [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award for Favorite Motion Picture Supporting Actress]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|''Grease''\n| [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award for Favorite Musical Motion Picture]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|''Grease''\n| [[People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Award for Favorite Overall Motion Picture]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|\"Hopelessly Devoted to You\"\n| [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2006\n|''Grease''\n| [[11th Satellite Awards#Best Classic DVD|Satellite Award for Best Classic DVD]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008\n|\"You're the One That I Want\"\n| [[TV Land Award|TV Land Award for Movie Dance Sequence You Reenacted in Your Living Room]]\n| {{nom}}\n{{end table}}\n\n===American Film Institute Recognition===\n; [[American Film Institute]] Lists\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Passions]]: No. 97\n* [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]]: No. 70 for \"[[Summer Nights (Grease song)|Summer Nights]]\"\n* [[AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals]]: No. 20\n\n==Legacy==\n===Sequel===\nThe sequel, ''[[Grease 2]]'' (1982), stars [[Maxwell Caulfield]] and [[Michelle Pfeiffer]]. Most of the adult characters reprised their roles, though the sequel focused on a younger class of greasers and thus most of the main characters from ''Grease'' did not appear. It was disowned by [[Jim Jacobs]], who co-created the characters. Patricia Birch, the original film's choreographer, directed the sequel. It would be the only film that she would direct.\n\n===Sing-along version===\n{{anchor|Grease Sing-A-Long}} On July 8, 2010, a sing-along version of ''Grease'' was released to select theaters around the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screencrave.com/2010-05-21/wanna-sing-a-long-with-grease-with-lyrics/ |title=Wanna Sing-A-Long with Grease? With Lyrics?!? |publisher=Screencrave.com |date=May 21, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100522020741/http://screencrave.com/2010-05-21/wanna-sing-a-long-with-grease-with-lyrics/ |archivedate=May 22, 2010 |df= }}</ref> A trailer was released in May 2010, with cigarettes digitally removed from certain scenes, implying heavy editing; however, Paramount confirmed these changes were done only for the film's advertising,<ref>[http://www.ocala.com/article/20100604/ARTICLES/6041009 \"'Grease Sing-A-Long' trailer cuts cigarette from iconic scene: Smoking was not removed from the film itself], Ocala.com, June 4, 2010.</ref> and the [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|rating]] for the film itself changed from its original PG to that of PG-13 for \"sexual content including references, teen smoking and drinking, and language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/films.php?id=66254 |title=Grease Sing-A-Long\u2014Trailers, Videos, and Reviews ComingSoon.net Movie Database |publisher=Comingsoon.net |date=July 8, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref> The film was shown for two weekends only; additional cities lobbied by fans from the Paramount official website started a week later and screened for one weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greasemovie.com |title=Grease Sing-A-Long (2010) &#124; Trailer & Official Movie Site |website=Greasemovie.com |date= |accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Prequel===\nIn March 2019, it was announced that a prequel, titled ''Summer Loving'', is currently in development from [[Paramount Players]] film studio. The project will be a joint-production collaboration with [[Temple Hill Entertainment|Temple Hill Productions]] and Picturestart Productions. [[John August]] signed on to serve as screenwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/grease-prequel-summer-loving-works-1200358|title='Grease' Prequel 'Summer Loving' in the Works With John August Writing (Exclusive)|first=Borys|last=Kit|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=April 9, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Main|Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture}}\n\nThe [[Grease: The Original Soundtrack from the Motion Picture|soundtrack album]] ended 1978 as the [[List of best-selling albums by year in the United States#1970s|second-best-selling album of the year in the United States]], exceeded only by [[Saturday Night Fever (soundtrack)|another soundtrack album]], from the film ''[[Saturday Night Fever]]'', which also starred Travolta.<ref name=\"bboard78\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=The+Billboard+200&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1978 |title=Year End Charts\u2014Year-end Albums\u2014The Billboard 200 |publisher= [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard.com]] |accessdate=2010-12-20 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071211064005/http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/charts/yearend_chart_display.jsp?f=The+Billboard+200&g=Year-end+Albums&year=1978 |archivedate = 2007-12-11}}</ref> The song \"Hopelessly Devoted to You\" was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Original Song#1970s|Academy Award for Best Music \u2013 Original Song]]. The song \"You're the One That I Want\" was released as a single prior to the film's release and became an immediate chart-topper, despite not being in the stage show or having been seen in the film at that time.<ref>VH1's \"Behind the Music: Grease\"</ref> Additionally, the dance number to \"You're the One That I Want\" was nominated for TV Land's award for \"Movie Dance Sequence You Reenacted in Your Living Room\" in 2008.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0077631/awards</ref> In the United Kingdom, the two Travolta/Newton-John duets, \"You're the One That I Want\" and \"Summer Nights\", were both number one hits and {{as of|2011|lc=y}} are still among the 20 best-selling singles of all time (at Nos. 6 and 19, respectively).<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00tknyg BBC Radio {{ndash}} Top selling singles of all time]</ref> The film's title song was also a number-one hit single for [[Frankie Valli]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=frankie valli|chart=all}}|title=''Billboard'' Hot 100|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe song \"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee\" refers to [[Sal Mineo]] in the original stage version. Mineo was stabbed to death a year before filming, so the line was changed to refer to [[Elvis Presley]] instead. The references to [[Troy Donohue]], [[Doris Day]], [[Rock Hudson]] and [[Annette Funicello]] are from the original stage version. Coincidentally, this scene as well as the scene before and the scene after it were filmed on August 16, 1977, the date of Elvis Presley's death.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/entertainment/movies/tales_of_ancient_grease_c9DsjHTfLgATW1VPqpizZP|title=Tales of Ancient 'Grease'|work=[[New York Post]]|accessdate=April 27, 2012|first=Larry|last=Getlen|date=2010-07-04}}</ref>\n\nSome of the songs were not present in the film; songs that appear in the film but not in the soundtrack are \"[[La Bamba (song)|La Bamba]]\" by Ritchie Valens, \"Whole Lotta Shaking Going On\" by [[Jerry Lee Lewis]], \"Alma Mater\", \"Alma Mater Parody\", and \"Rydell Fight Song\". \"Alone at a Drive-in Movie (instrumental)\", \"Mooning\", and \"Freddy My Love\" are not present in the film, although all three are listed in the end credits in-addition to being on the soundtrack. (Both \"Mooning\" and \"Rock'n'Roll Party Queen\", the latter of which was played in the film as background music, were written in the musical for a character named Roger that was written out of the film, replaced by the non-singing Putzie. In general, all of the songs in the musical that were performed by characters other than Danny, Rizzo, Sandy, Johnny Casino, or the Teen Angel were either taken out of the film or given to other characters, including Marty Maraschino's number \"Freddy My Love\", Kenickie's \"Greased Lightnin'\", and Doody's \"Those Magic Changes\".) Two songs from the musical, \"Shakin' at the High School Hop\" and \"All Choked Up\", were left off both the film and the soundtrack.\n\nThe songs appear in the film in the following order:\n{{div col}}\n# \"[[Love is a Many-Splendored Thing (song)|Love is a Many-Splendored Thing]]\"\n# \"[[Grease (song)|Grease]]\"\n# \"Alma Mater\"\n# \"[[Summer Nights (Grease song)|Summer Nights]]\" \u2013 Danny, Sandy, Pink Ladies and T-Birds\n# \"Rydell Fight Song\" \u2013 Rydell Marching Band\n# \"[[Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee]]\" \u2013 Rizzo and Pink Ladies\n# \"[[Hopelessly Devoted to You]]\" \u2013 Sandy\n# \"[[Greased Lightnin' (song)|Greased Lightnin']]\" \u2013 Danny and T-Birds\n# \"[[La Bamba (song)|La Bamba]]\"\n# \"It's Raining on Prom Night\"\n# \"[[Whole Lotta Shakin' Goin' On]]\"\n# \"[[Beauty School Dropout]]\" \u2013 Teen Angel and Female Angels\n# \"[[Rock n' Roll Party Queen]]\"\n# \"[[Rock and Roll Is Here to Stay]]\"\n# \"[[Those Magic Changes]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers; Danny sings along onscreen\n# \"[[Tears on My Pillow]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Hound Dog (song)|Hound Dog]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Born to Hand Jive]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Blue Moon (1934 song)|Blue Moon]]\" \u2013 Johnny Casino and the Gamblers\n# \"[[Sandy (Grease song)|Sandy]]\" \u2013 Danny\n# \"[[There Are Worse Things I Could Do]]\" \u2013 Rizzo\n# \"Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee (Reprise)\" \u2013 Sandy\n# \"Alma Mater Parody\" (instrumental)\n# \"[[You're the One That I Want]]\" \u2013 Danny, Sandy, Pink Ladies, and T-Birds\n# \"We Go Together\" <!-- There is no article for this song. Wiki-linking this phrase will lead to the album by George Jones and Tammy Wynette. Putting (song) as a dab will lead to the present article.) -->\u2013 Cast\n# \"Grease (Reprise)\"\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Television==\n{{main|Somos t\u00fa y yo|Grease: Live}}\nOn August 17, 2009, a [[Somos t\u00fa y yo|television series]] inspired by the film premiered in Venezuela. The series was produced and directed by Vladimir Perez. The show explores and expands on the characters and story from the film.<ref>{{cite news|title=Venevisi\u00f3n estrena 'Somos t\u00fa y yo, un nuevo d\u00eda, inspirada en Grease'|url=http://www.todotvnews.com/news/Venevision-estrena-serie-Somos-T-y-Yo-Un-Nuevo-Da.html|access-date=July 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170622190035/http://www.todotvnews.com/news/Venevision-estrena-serie-Somos-T-y-Yo-Un-Nuevo-Da.html|archive-date=June 22, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=De regreso a los a\u00f1os 50 con el musical 'Grease'|url=http://www.eluniverso.com/vida-estilo/2015/09/25/nota/5145359/regreso-anos-50-musical-grease}}</ref>\n\nOn January 31, 2016, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] aired a [[Grease: Live|live television-adapted special]] of the musical, using components from both the 1978 film and the original Broadway show. Starring [[Julianne Hough]], [[Aaron Tveit]], and [[Vanessa Hudgens]], the adaptation received positive reviews, especially towards Hudgens, whose father passed away hours before the live airing, and ten [[Emmy]] nominations.<ref>{{cite web |title=About Grease: Live |url=https://www.fox.com/grease-live/ |website=Fox}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.greasemovie.com/ Official Sing-A-Long Site]\n* {{IMDb title|0077631|Grease}}\n* {{tcmdb title|4603|Grease}}\n* {{AllMovie title|20546|Grease}}\n* {{mojo title|grease|Grease}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|grease|Grease}}\n* {{metacritic film|grease|Grease}}\n* {{YouTube|wzWmxjYNfz4|Original 1978 Release Trailer}}\n* [https://www.paramountmovies.com/movies/grease Paramount Movies - Grease]\n{{Grease}}\n{{Randal Kleiser}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grease}}\n[[Category:1970s dance films]]\n[[Category:1970s high school films]]\n[[Category:1970s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:1970s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:1978 films]]\n[[Category:American dance films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American rock musicals]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen musical films]]\n[[Category:American teen romance fi